{"title_page": "List of people from the Bronx", "text_new": "This is a list of people who were either born or have lived in [[The Bronx]], a [[borough (New York City)|borough]] of [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], at some time in their lives.  Many of the early historical figures lived in that part of [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]] which later became part of The Bronx.\n\n{{dynamic list|date=October 2011}}\n\n== Academics and science ==\n{{colbegin|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Jill Bargonetti]] (born 1962) \u2013 biologist and Presidential Early Career Award winner\n* [[Marshall Berman]] (1940\u20132013) \u2013 philosopher of modernity; author of ''All That Is Solid Melts into Air''\n* [[Norman Birnbaum]] (1926\u20132019) \u2013 author, educator, political advisor; University Professor Emeritus, [[Georgetown University Law Center]]; taught at [[Amherst College]], [[London School of Economics]], [[Oxford University]], [[University of Strasbourg]]\n* [[Ira Black]] (1941\u20132006) \u2013 [[neuroscientist]] and [[stem cell|stem-cell]] researcher; first director of the [[Stem Cell Institute of New Jersey]]<ref>Pearce, Jeremy (January 12, 2006). [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/12/nyregion/12black.html \"Dr. Ira B. Black, 64, Leader in New Jersey Stem Cell Effort, Dies\"]. ''[[The New York Times]]''.  Retrieved October 29, 2011.</ref>\n* [[Xavier Briggs]] (born 1968) Former professor of planning at [[MIT]], former associate director of [[Office of Management and Budget]], current vice-president of [[Ford Foundation]]. Sometimes known as \"Xavier de Souza Briggs\"\n* [[Roscoe Brown]] (1922\u20132016) \u2013 [[Tuskegee airmen|Tuskegee airman]], exercise physiologist, President, [[Bronx Community College]], New York City political adviser<ref>Sam Roberts, \"Roscoe C. Brown, 94, Tuskegee Airman and Political Confidant,\" ''New York Times'', July 7, 2016</ref>\n* [[Morton Deutsch]] (1920\u20132017) \u2013 [[conflict resolution]] expert<ref>Sam Roberts, \"Morton Deutsch, conflict resolution expert, dies at 97,\" ''New York Times,'' March 23, 2017</ref>\n* [[W.E.B. Du Bois]] (1868\u20131963) - sociologist, historian, civil rights activist, Pan-Africanist.<ref>Ian Frazer, \"Old Hatreds,\" ''New Yorker'', August 26, 2019, p. 36.</ref>\n* [[Gertrude B. Elion]] (1918\u20131999) - Nobel Prize biochemist and pharmacologist<ref name=\"jwa.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://jwa.org/encyclopedia/article/elion-gertrude-belle|title=Gertrude Elion {{!}} Jewish Women's Archive|website=jwa.org|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref>\n* [[Murray Gell-Mann]] (1929\u20132019), Nobel Prize physicist of sub-atomic particle.<ref>George Johnson, \"Murray Gell-Mann,Who Peered at Particles and Saw the Universe, Dies at 89.\" ''New York Times, May 25, 2019.</ref>\n* [[Todd Gitlin]] (born 1943) \u2013 [[sociology|sociologist]]; co-founder of [[Students for a Democratic Society]]<ref>Miller, Jim (November 8, 1987). [https://www.nytimes.com/1987/11/08/books/tears-and-riots-love-and-regrets.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm \"Tears and Riots, Love and Regrets\"]. ''[[The New York Times]]''. Retrieved October 29, 2011. \"Mr. Gitlin was born in 1943. Growing up in the Bronx, the middle-class son of liberal Jewish parents, he was, as he recalls, 'studious and clean-cut,' a straight-arrow fan of Adlai Stevenson.\"</ref>\n* [[Fred Greenstein]] (1930\u20132018) \u2013 political scientist who psychologically assessed U.S. presidents<ref>Katherine Seelye, \"Fred Greenstein, 88, A Political 'Psychologist' Who Assessed Presidents.\" ''New York Times,'' December 16, 2018</ref>\n* [[Henry Heimlich]] (1920\u20132016) \u2013 physician inventor of the Heimlich maneuver<ref>Robert McFadden, \"Inventor of a life-saving maneuver\", ''New York Times, Dec. 21, 2016</ref>\n* [[Matthew Henson]] (1866\u20131955) \u2013 Explorer, co-discoverer of the North Pole (with Robert Peary)\n* [[Gary Hermalyn]] (born 1953) \u2013 Centennial Historian of New York City, [[Edgar Allan Poe]] scholar\n* [[Irving Howe]] (1920\u20131993) \u2013 literary critic, socialist writer, author of ''World of Our Fathers'' \n* [[Samuel P. Huntington]] (1927\u20132008) \u2013 Government Professor at [[Harvard University]]; co-editor of ''[[Foreign Policy (magazine)|Foreign Policy]]''; author of political science works related to the modernization of societies, particularly those of developing nations\n* Barbara Jasny (born 1952) \u2013 deputy editor of Science; co-editor Catalysts, Women of Science Fiction\n* [[Adrian Kantrowitz]] (1918\u20132008) \u2013 [[cardiac surgery|cardiac-surgery]] pioneer<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">''[[The New York Times]]'' obituary. November 20, 2008.</ref>\n* [[Arthur Kantrowitz]] (1913\u20132008) \u2013 [[nose cone]] [[physicist]]; co-inventor of the [[intra-aortic balloon pump]]<ref>''[[The New York Times]]'' obituary. December 10, 2008.</ref>\n* [[Jeffrey Lane]] \u2013 urban ethnographer, [[Rutgers University]]\n* [[Robert Lefkowitz]] (born 1943) \u2013 2012 recipient of Nobel prize for chemistry of protein receptors<ref>\"Nobel Prize Winner Hails from the Bronx,\" MyFoxNY.com {{cite web |url=http://www.myfoxny.com/story/19782014/winner-of-nobel-prize-talks-with-good-day-new-york |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-09-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121029074053/http://www.myfoxny.com/story/19782014/winner-of-nobel-prize-talks-with-good-day-new-york |archivedate=2012-10-29 }}</ref>\n* [[Norman Levitt]] (1943\u20132009) \u2013 [[mathematician]] at [[Rutgers University]]<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pasachoff|first1=Jay M.|title=Norm Levitt: An Obituary|journal=The Skeptical Inquirer|date=February 2010|volume=34|issue=1|publisher=[[Committee for Skeptical Inquiry]]|url=http://www.csicop.org/si/show/norm_levitt_an_obituary|accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Paul Levinson]] (born 1947) \u2013 [[science fiction|science-fiction]] and [[non-fiction]] author; [[Communication theory|communications professor]]\n* [[Ronald Mallett]] (born 1945) \u2013 [[Theoretical physics|theoretical physicist]] of [[time travel]]\n* [[Barry Mazur]] (born 1937)  \u2013 mathematician and Fellow of the [[National Academy of Science]]\n* [[Joseph M. McShane]] (born 1942) \u2013 [[Jesuit]] priest; president of [[Fordham University]]\n* [[Stanley Milgram]] (1933\u20131984) \u2013 psychologist known for [[obedience to authority]] and [[Small-world experiment|small world]] studies<ref>[[Thomas Blass]], \"The Man Who Shocked the World\" ''Psychology Today'', March 1, 2002</ref>\n* [[Joseph A. O'Hare]] (born 1931) \u2013 [[Jesuit]] priest; longest-serving president of [[Fordham University]] (1984\u20132003); first chair of [[New York City Campaign Finance Board]] (1988\u20132003)\n* [[Jay Pasachoff]] (born 1943) \u2013 [[astronomer]], [[solar eclipse|umbraphile]]<ref>Jason Kersten, \"Dept. of Superlatives: Totally\" ''New Yorker'', August 28, 2017: 28-29</ref>\n* [[Carolyn Porco]] (born 1953) \u2013 [[planetary science|planetary scientist]]; leader of the [[Cassini\u2013Huygens|Cassini]] space observatory team at the [[Colorado]] [[Space Science Institute]], studying [[Saturn]]<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/22/science/space/22prof.html?partner=rss&emc=rss | work= [[The New York Times]] | author = [[Dennis Overbye|Overbye, Dennis]] | title=An Odyssey from the Bronx to Saturn's Rings | date=September 21, 2009 | accessdate= October 29, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Allan Pred]] (1936\u20132007) \u2013 geographer at [[University of Chicago]] and [[University of California, Berkeley]]<ref>Natalia Vonnegut, \"Alan Pred in Memoriam\",{{cite web |url=http://oldweb.geog.berkeley.edu/PeopleHistory/faculty/AllanPred_InMemoriam.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331134549/http://oldweb.geog.berkeley.edu/PeopleHistory/faculty/AllanPred_InMemoriam.html |archivedate=2012-03-31 }}</ref>\n* [[Howard Raiffa]] (1924\u20132016) \u2013 [[economist]]; negotiation scientist<ref>Sam Roberts, \"Howard Raifa, 92, Negotiation Scientist\" ''New York Times'', July 18, 2016</ref>\n* [[Murray Rothbard]] (1926\u20131995) \u2013 [[economist]]; helped define modern [[libertarianism]]\n* [[Ken Schaffer]] (born 1947) \u2013 [[inventor]]; invented [[wireless guitar]], video [[placeshifting]]<ref>\"Ken Schaffer: What's the Frequency?\" http://www.nutcom.com/?cat=3</ref>\n* [[Joseph Francis Shea]] (1925\u20131999) \u2013 [[Aerospace engineering|aerospace engineer]]; headed [[NASA]]'s [[Apollo program]]\n* Gary Simons \u2013 founder of [[Prep for Prep]] gifted education program in NYC<ref>Vinson Cunningham, \"Test Case.\" ''New Yorker'', March 9, 2020, 5667</ref>\n* [[Robert Sobel]] (1931\u20131999) \u2013 [[historian]] and writer; history professor at [[Hofstra University]]; writer of business histories\n* [[Edward Soja]] (1940\u20132015) \u2013 postmodern political geography and urban theorist at [[UCLA]]<ref>[http://news.aag.org/2015/12/in-memoriam-edward-w-soja/]</ref>\n* [[Michael I. Sovern]] (born 1931) \u2013 Chancellor Kent Professor of Law and President Emeritus of Columbia University\n* [[Robert Spinrad]] (1932\u20132009) \u2013 [[computer designer]]; director of the [[PARC (company)|Xerox Palo Alto Research Center]]<ref>[[John Markoff|Markoff, John]] (September 6, 2009). [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/07/technology/07spinrad.html Robert Spinrad, a Pioneer in Computing, Dies at 77\"]. ''[[The New York Times]]''.  Retrieved October 29, 2011.</ref>\n* [[Leonard Susskind]] (born 1940) \u2013 theoretical physicist<ref>Byrne, Peter (July 2011). \"Bad Boy of Physics\". ''[[Scientific American]]''. pp. 80\u201383.</ref>\n* [[Neil deGrasse Tyson]] (born 1959) \u2013 [[astrophysicist]]; director of the [[American Museum of Natural History]]'s [[Hayden Planetarium]]; host of [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS's]] [[educational television|educational-television]] series ''[[NOVA scienceNOW]]'' and Cosmos: A SpaceTime Odyssey (2014) and Cosmos: Possible Worlds (2020).\n* [[Lloyd Ultan (historian)]] (born 1938) \u2013 official historian of the Bronx\n* [[Allen Weinstein]] (1937\u20132015) \u2013 historian; [[Archivist of the United States]]\n* [[Barry Wellman]] (born 1942) \u2013 [[sociology|sociologist]]; [[University of Toronto]] professor studying [[social networks]], [[community]] and the [[Internet]]\n* [[Rosalyn Sussman Yalow]] (1921\u20132011) \u2013 [[Medical physics|medical physicist]]; co-winner of the 1977 [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]]<ref>Gellene, Denise (June 2, 2011). \"Rosalyn S. Yalow, Nobel Medical Physicist, Dies at 89\". ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref>\n* [[Yosef Hayim Yerushalmi]] (1932\u20132009) \u2013 [[historian]]; [[Salo Wittmayer Baron|Salo Baron]] Professor of [[Jewish history|Jewish History]] at [[Columbia University]]<ref>Berger, Joseph (December 10, 2009). [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/11/nyregion/11yerushalmi.html \"Yosef H. Yerushalmi, Scholar of Jewish History, Dies at 77\"]. ''[[The New York Times]]''. Retrieved October 29, 2011.</ref>\n{{colend}}\n\n==Arts==\n===Architecture, art and photography===\n{{colbegin|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Vito Acconci]] (1940\u20132017) \u2013 [[architect]], [[landscape architect]] and [[installation artist]]\n* [[Robert Altman (photographer)|Robert Altman]] (born 1944) \u2013 [[photographer]]\n* [[Richard Avedon]] (1923\u20132004) \u2013 photographer\n* [[Alvin Baltrop]] (1948\u20132004) \u2013 photographer\n* [[Margaret Bourke-White]] (1904\u20131971) \u2013 photographer (including [[documentary photography|documentary photographer]])\n* [[Cope2]] (born 1968) \u2013 [[graffiti artist]]\n* [[Willie Cole]] (born 1955) \u2013 artist; uses found material such as his \"America\" blackboard<ref name=\"autogenerated50\">[[Ian Frazier|Frazier, Ian]] (December 21, 2009). \"Dept. of Orientation: El Super\". ''[[The New Yorker]]'', p. 50.</ref>\n* [[Ralph Fasanella]] (1914\u20131997) \u2013 painter\n* [[Ron Galella]] (born 1931) \u2013 [[paparazzi|paparazzo photographer]]<ref>[[Tad Friend|Friend, Tad]] (May 31, 2010). \"Big Game Dept.: No Pictures\".  ''[[The New Yorker]]'', pp. 24\u201325.</ref>\n* [[Horace Ginsbern]] (1902\u20131987) \u2013 architect; designed the landmark [[Art Deco]] [[Park Plaza Apartments (New York)|Park Plaza Apartments]] on [[Jerome Avenue]] in the Bronx, and other New York City structures<ref name=\"nytimes1\">[[Constance Rosenblum|Rosenblum, Constance]] (August 20, 2009). [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/21/arts/design/21concourse.html?_r=2&pagewanted=all \"Grand Wasn't It?\"]. ''[[The New York Times]]''.  Retrieved October 29, 2011.</ref>\n* [[Milton Glaser]] (born 1929) \u2013 [[graphic designer]]; designer of the \"[[I Love New York]]\" [[logo]]\n* [[Garry Gross]] (1937\u20132010) \u2013 [[fashion photography|fashion photographer]] (including nude images of [[Brooke Shields]] at age ten), dog [[Portrait photography|portraiture]] photographer and [[dog trainer]]<ref>Hevesi, Dennis (December 7, 2010).[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/07/arts/design/07gross.html \"Garry Gross Is Dead at 73; Photographer of Clothes and Their Absence\"]. ''[[The New York Times]]''.  Retrieved October 29, 2011.</ref>\n* [[Sabin Howard]] (born 1963) \u2013 figurative sculptor, noted for U.S. [[World War 1]] national monument\n* [[Al Held]] (1928\u20132005) \u2013 abstract painter; associated with [[Abstract expressionism]], [[Hard-edge painting|Hard-edge]] and [[Color Field painting]]<ref>{{cite news|author= McNay, Michael |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2005/aug/01/guardianobituaries.artsobituaries |title=Al Held \u2013 American Painter Who Found His Voice in Hard Edge Abstraction |work = [[The Guardian]] |date= July 31, 2005|accessdate= October 29, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Joel Iskowitz]] (born 1946) illustrator, artist, designer for [[United States Mint]]<ref>(November 21, 2017). [https://www.usmint.gov/learn/artists/aip-joel-iskowitz \"Joel Iskowitz Artistic Infusion Program Designer\"]. ''[[United States Mint]]''.  Retrieved December 27, 2017.</ref>\n* [[Marcey Jacobson]] (1911\u20132009) \u2013 photographer; images of daily life in [[Chiapas]], [[Mexico]]<ref>Weber, Bruce. (August 11, 2009). [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/11/arts/design/11jacobson.html \"Marcey Jacobson, a Photographer Inspired by Mexico, Dies at 97\"]. ''[[The New York Times]]''.  Retrieved October 29, 2011.</ref>\n* [[C. Paul Jennewein]] (1890\u20131978) \u2013 sculptor\n* [[Ivan Karp]] (1926\u20132012) \u2013 [[art dealer]]\n* [[Stanley Kubrick]] (1926\u20131999) \u2013 director, screenwriter, editor, cinematographer, storyteller\n* [[Ronnie Landfield]] (born 1947) \u2013 abstract painter; associated with [[lyrical abstraction]], and [[color field]] painting<ref>[[Ronnie Landfield|Landfield, Ronnie]]; [[Robert C. Morgan|Morgan, Robert C.]]; Landfield, Jenny (2007).  ''Ronnie Landfield \u2013 Paintings from Five Decades \u2013 September 16 \u2013 November 25, 2007'' ([[exhibition catalogue]]). [[Youngstown, Ohio|Youngstown]], [[Ohio]]: [[Butler Institute of American Art]]. \"Beginnings\". pp. 7\u201310. {{ISBN|978-1-882790-50-0}}.</ref>\n* [[Daniel Libeskind]] (born 1946) \u2013 [[architect]]\n* [[Glenn Ligon]] (born 1960) \u2013 [[conceptual artist]]\n* [[Whitfield Lovell]]<ref>[http://www.lehman.cuny.edu/vpadvance/artgallery/gallery/whitfield_lovell/biographical_notes.htm Whitfield Lovell]</ref> (born 1959) \u2013 painter and [[installation artist]];<ref>{{cite web| author = [[John Yau|Yau, John]] |url=http://www.brooklynrail.org/2006/07/art/whitfield-lovell |title=Whitfield Lovell with John Yau | work = [[The Brooklyn Rail]] |date= July\u2013August 2006 |accessdate= October 29, 2011}}</ref> focuses on [[African American|African-American]] themes; [[MacArthur Fellows Program|MacArthur Fellow]] (2007)<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff |url=http://www.macfound.org/site/c.lkLXJ8MQKrH/b.2913825/apps/nl/content2.asp?content_id=%7B491135C4-E552-4ADB-80CA-B640676A5BF6%7D&notoc=1 |title=MacArthur Fellows 2007 \u2013 Whitfield Lovell |publisher=[[John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation]] |date=September 2007 |accessdate=October 29, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027032553/http://www.macfound.org/site/c.lkLXJ8MQKrH/b.2913825/apps/nl/content2.asp?content_id=%7B491135C4-E552-4ADB-80CA-B640676A5BF6%7D&notoc=1 |archivedate=October 27, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| author = Video (requires [[Adobe Flash]]; 00:02:11) | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a0S_C9ZjR10&feature=user |title=2007 MacArthur Fellow: Whitfield Lovell |publisher= [[John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation]] (via its [[YouTube]] channel) | date= June 11, 2008 |accessdate= October 29, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Joel Meyerowitz]] (born 1938) \u2013 [[photographer]]\n* [[Rick Meyerowitz]] (born 1943) \u2013 artist\n* [[Ralph Morse]] (1917\u20132015) \u2013 photographer\n* [[Piccirilli Brothers]] (including father, Giuseppe Piccirilli (1844\u20131910), and his six sons \u2013 Ferruccio (born 1864), [[Attilio Piccirilli|Attilio]] (1866\u20131945), [[Furio Piccirilli|Furio]] (1868\u20131949), Masaniello (1870\u20131951), Orazio (1872\u20131954) and Getulio (1874\u20131956)) \u2013 [[sculpture|sculptors]]\n* [[Louis Risse]] \u2013 French-born [[engineer]]; conceived of the [[Grand Concourse (Bronx)|Grand Concourse]], a boulevard in the Bronx<ref name=\"nytimes1\"/>\n* [[Larry Rivers]] (1923\u20132002) \u2013 artist\n* [[Joel Arthur Rosenthal]] (born 1943) \u2013 jeweler\n* [[Merryll Saylan]] (born 1936) \u2013 [[Woodturning|woodturner]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-merryll-saylan-13576|title=Oral history interview with Merryll Saylan, 2006 May 20-June 5|publisher=[[Archives of American Art]], [[Smithsonian Institution]]|date=2006|accessdate=September 22, 2019}}</ref> \n* [[Edwin Scheier]] (1910\u20132008) \u2013 artist\n* [[Phil Stern]] (1919\u20132014) \u2013 Hollywood, WWII and White House photographer<ref>Robert McFadden, \"Phil Stern, Photographer; Chronicler of Movie Stars and a President was 95\" ''New York Times, December 16, 2014\"</ref>\n* [[George Sugarman]] (1912\u20131999) \u2013 [[sculpture|sculptor]]<ref>{{cite news| author = [[Roberta Smith|Smith, Roberta]] |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CE1D9113BF932A0575BC0A96F958260 |title= George Sugarman, a Sculptor Of Colorful Works, Dies at 87 |work = [[The New York Times]] |date=August 31, 1999 |accessdate= October 28, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Raven B. Varona]] \u2013 phtographer.<ref>Kate Dwyer, \"A Photographer of the Hip-Hop Age.\" ''New York Times'', December 1, 2019, p. ST10</ref>\n* [[Lawrence Weiner]] (born 1942) \u2013 artist; associated with [[conceptual art]]\n* [[Marian Zazeela]] (born 1940) \u2013 [[light art]]ist, painter, and [[set design]]er; also musician of [[Hindustani classical music]]\n{{colend}}\n\n===Journalists and writers===\n[[File:P1020279.JPG|thumb|[[Edgar Allan Poe Cottage]] 2640 Grand Concourse, in the [[Fordham, Bronx|Fordham]] section of the Bronx. Poe spent the last few years of his life there.]]\n* [[Sholem Aleichem]] (1859\u20131916) \u2013 author\n* [[Nahshon Dion Anderson]] (born 1978) \u2013 non-fiction writer and screenwriter\n* [[William Henry Appleton]] (1814\u20131899) \u2013 publisher\n* [[Army Archerd]] (1922\u20131999) \u2013 columnist for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''\n* [[James Baldwin]] (1924\u20131987) \u2013 playwright and essayist\n* [[Harold Bloom]] (1930\u20132019) \u2013 literary critic\n* [[Leslie Brody]] (born 1952) \u2013 [[non-fiction]] author\n* [[Robert Caro]] (born 1935) \u2013 [[non-fiction]] author of biographies of [[Robert Moses]] and [[Lyndon Johnson]]\n* [[Jerome Charyn]] (born 1937) \u2013 prolific novelist and author of several memoirs\n* [[Mary Higgins Clark]] (1927\u20132020) \u2013 best-selling author of suspense novels\n* [[Avery Corman]] (born 1935) \u2013 novelist; author of ''The Old Neighborhood'', set in the Bronx\n* [[Don DeLillo]] (born 1936) \u2013 novelist\n* [[E. L. Doctorow]] (1931\u20132015) \u2013 author\n* [[Will Eisner]] (1917\u20132005) \u2013 author of ''[[A Contract with God]]'' and other [[graphic novels]] and instruction books\n* [[Jules Feiffer]] (born 1929) \u2013 cartoonist (primarily in ''[[The Village Voice]]''); playwright, screenwriter\n* [[Bill Finger]] (1917\u20131974) \u2013 writer co-creator of Batman comic book<ref>George Gene Gustines, \"At Bronx Corner, Gothamd City Honors One of Its Own.\" ''New York Times'', December 17, 2017</ref>\n* [[Vivian Gornick]] (born 1935) \u2013 American critic, journalist, essayist, and memoirist\n* [[Marilyn Hacker]] (born 1942) \u2013 poet, critic, reviewer\n* [[David Halberstam]] (1934\u20132007) \u2013 Pulitzer Prize-winning author, ''[[New York Times]]'' journalist\n* [[Phil Hall (US writer)|Phil Hall]] (born 1964) \u2013 film critic\n* [[Hy Hollinger]] (1918\u20132015) \u2013 journalist for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' and ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''<ref>[https://variety.com/2015/film/news/hy-hollinger-dies-dead-variety-reporter-1201613764/ Hy Hollinger, Longtime Variety Reporter, Dies at 97]</ref>\n* [[Max Kadushin]] (1895\u20131980) \u2013 rabbi, theologian and author at [[Conservative Synagogue Adath Israel of Riverdale]]\n* [[Bel Kaufman]] (1911\u20132014) \u2013 novelist author of ''Up the Down Staircase'' about NYC schools in the 1950s<ref>Margalit Fox, \"Bel Kaufman, Who Told What School Was Really Like, Dies at 103.\" ''New York Times'', July 28, 2014. [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/26/arts/bel-kaufman-up-the-down-staircase-writer-dies-at-103.html?smid=tw-share]</ref>\n* [[William Melvin Kelley]] (1937\u20132017) \u2013 novelist, short-story writer, university professor\n* [[Annie Lanzillotto]] (born 1963) \u2013 poet, author, dramatist, songwriter\n* [[Stan Lee]] (1922\u20132018) \u2013 leading creator of [[Marvel Comics]]\n* [[Paul Levinson]] (born 1947) \u2013 science fiction and non-fiction author\n* [[Anthony Lewis]] (1927\u20132013) \u2013 ''New York Times'' legal reporter, specializing in coverage of the U.S. Supreme Court<ref>[[Adam Liptak|Liptak, Adam]] (March 25, 2013). \"Anthony Lewis, Supreme Court Reporter Who Brought Law to Life, Dies at 85\". ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref>\n* [[Miles Marshall Lewis]] (born 1970) \u2013 pop-culture critic\n* [[Kenneth Lonergan]] (born 1962) \u2013 playwright and screenwriter<ref>Hilton Als, \"Urban Blight: The World of Kenneth Lonergan,\" ''New Yorker, September 22, 2014, pp 107-109</ref>\n* [[Lynda Lopez]] (born 1971) \u2013 journalist, multiple [[broadcast network]]s\n* [[Ray Marcano]] \u2013 medical reporter and music critic\n* [[John Matteson]] (born 1961) \u2013 [[Pulitzer Prize]]\u2013winning biographer\n* Stanley Meisler (1931\u20132016) \u2013 foreign correspondent, biographer, art historian<ref>William Grimes, \"Stanley Meisler, 85, Reporter Who Pivoted to Art History,\" ''New York Times'', July 7, 2016</ref>\n* [[Judith Merril]] (1923\u20131997) \u2013 science-fiction editor and author\n* [[Steve Mirsky]] \u2013 ''[[Scientific American]]'' columnist\n* [[Nicholasa Mohr]] (born 1938) \u2013 [[Nuyorican]] writer about [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] women in New York\n* [[Mwalim]] (born 1968) \u2013 playwright, composer, and novelist\n* [[Davi Napoleon]] (born 1946) \u2013 theater historian and arts journalist\n* [[Clifford Odets]] (1906\u20131963) \u2013 playwright, co-founder of the [[Group Theatre (New York)|Group Theatre]]\n* [[Cynthia Ozick]] (born 1928) \u2013 award-winning novelist and short-story writer\n* [[Grace Paley]] (1922\u20132007) \u2013 award-winning short-story writer<ref>Sarah Crown, \"A Reading Class in Masters of the Short Story.\" ''Guardian News Service'', accessed via ''Toronto Globe and Mail'', Review section, December 12, 2009.</ref>\n* [[Michael Pearson (author)|Michael Pearson]] (born 1949) \u2013 [[Old Dominion University]] Engli