llows Program|MacArthur Genius Award]]-winning founder of [[Sustainable South Bronx]]\n* [[Claudette Colvin]] (born 1939) \u2013 first person to be arrested protesting bus segregation in the U.S. South, in [[Montgomery, Alabama]], March 2, 1955<ref>{{\u2022}}Hoose, Phillip H. (2009). ''Claudette Colvin \u2013 Twice Toward Justice''. New York City: [[Farrar, Straus and Giroux]].  {{ISBN|978-0-374-31322-7}}. <br />{{\u2022}}Barnes, Brooks (November 26, 2009).  \"From Footnote to Fame in Civil Rights History\". ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref>\n* [[Ita Ford]] (1940\u20131980) \u2013 Maryknoll nun, murdered by Salvadoran death squad\n* [[Jack Greenberg (lawyer)|Jack Greenberg]] (1924\u20132016) \u2013 civil rights lawyer as head of [[NAACP Legal Defense and Education Fund]] for 23 years<ref>Richard Severo and William McDonald, \"Jack Greenberg Dies at 91, Las Survivor of a Legendary Civil Rights Legal Team,\" ''New York Times'', October 13, 2016</ref>\n* [[Ray McGovern]] (born 1939) \u2013 retired [[Central Intelligence Agency]] officer turned [[political activist]]\n* [[Maurice Paprin]] (1920\u20132005) \u2013 [[Mitchell Lama]] apartments developer and social activist\n* [[Arlyn Phoenix]] (born 1943) \u2013 head of River Phoenix Center for Peacebuilding; mother of [[Joaquin Phoenix]], [[River Phoenix]]\n* [[Sally Regenhard]] \u2013 9/11 activist; [[Co-op City]] resident\n* Sylvia Rivera (1951\u20132002) \u2013 transgender activist, \"the Rosa Parks of the transgender movement\"<ref>Gina Bellafante, \"These Pioneers Reclaimed Pride,\" ''New York Times'', May 19, 2019, p. A26''</ref> \n* [[Jim Steyer]] (born 1956) \u2013 child advocate<ref>Connie Loizos, \"Jim Steyer runs the powerful nonprofit Common Sense Media; now he\u2019s using his influence to battle big tech\". 'TechCrunch'', February 12, 2019.[https://techcrunch.com/2019/02/12/jim-steyer-runs-the-powerful-nonprofits-common-sense-media-and-hes-increasingly-using-his-influence-around-tech-consumption/]</ref>\n* [[Stephen Spiro]] (1939\u20132007) \u2013 conscientious objector and Vietnam War opponent\n* Elizabeth Sturz (1917\u20132010) \u2013 founder of Argus Community and [[Harbor House]]; folklorist with husband [[Alan Lomax]]<ref>Martin, Douglas (October 22, 2010). \"Elizabeth L. Sturz, 93, Dies; Salvaged Troubled Lives\". ''[[The New York Times]]'', p. A23.</ref>\n*Gary Waldron (born 1943) \u2013 founder of Glie Farms, commercial organic herb garden in low-income neighborhood.<ref>Sam Howe Verhovek, \"Herb Garden, an Oasis in Bronx, Withers\". ''New York Times'', June 23, 1988; Ligaya Mishan, \"How It Changed: Food.\" ''New York Times T Magazine,'' April 22, 2018</ref>\n* Suzanne (Werner) Wright (1946\u20132016) \u2013 co-founder of [[Autism Speaks]]<ref>Daniel S. Slotnik, \"Suzanne Wright, 69, a Founder of the Charity Autism Speaks,\" ''New York Times'', August 2, 2016</ref>\n{{colend}}\n\n==Business==\n{{colbegin|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Joseph Beninati]] (born 1964) \u2013 real estate developer and private equity investor\n* [[Lloyd Blankfein]] (born 1954) \u2013 businessman; chief executive officer of [[Goldman Sachs]] (since 2006)<ref>\"Report on Business\".  ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''. April 17, 2010.</ref>\n* [[Eli Broad]] (born 1933) \u2013 businessman and arts philanthropist; co-founder of [[Kaufman & Broad]]<ref>Bruch, Connie (December 10, 2010). \"The Art of the Billionaire\". ''[[The New Yorker]]''.</ref>\n* [[B. Gerald Cantor]] (1916\u20131996) \u2013 businessman; co-founder of [[securities]] firm [[Cantor Fitzgerald]]; with his wife Iris, amassed and then donated the largest private collection of sculptures by [[Auguste Rodin]]\n* [[Stanley Chais]] (1926\u20132010), investment advisor in the Madoff investment scandal\n* [[Fred DeLuca]] (1947\u20132015) \u2013 founder and CEO of Subway fast food sandwich chain\n* Richelieu Dennis \u2013 co-founder of Sundial Brands personal care products.<ref>[https://www.sundialbrands.com/our-story/]; Jeffrey Toobin, \"After Trump\", ''New Yorker'', Nov. 19, 2018, p.26.</ref>\n* [[Millard Drexler|Millard \"Mickey\" Drexler\"]] (born 1944) \u2013 businessman; chief executive officer of [[J. Crew]]; former chief executive officer of the [[Gap (clothing retailer)|Gap]]<ref>Paumgarten, Nick (September 20, 2010). \"The Merchant\" ''[[The New Yorker]]'',  pp. 74\u201387.</ref>\n* [[Reggie Fils-Aim\u00e9]] (born 1961) \u2013 president of Nintendo of America\n* [[Michael J. Freeman (inventor)|Michael J. Freeman]] (born 1947) \u2013 inventor, educator, business consultant, and entrepreneur\n* Mike Greco (1929-2019) \u2013 'salami king'<ref>Sam Roberts, \"Mike Greco, 89, Colorful 'Salami King' of Little Italy in the Bronx, Dies.\" ''New York Times, April 2, 2019''.</ref>\n* [[Harry Helmsley]] (1909\u20131997) \u2013 real estate magnate in New York City\n* [[Roger Hertog]] (born 1941) \u2013 co-founder of investment firm; co-publisher of ''[[The New Republic]]'' magazine; philanthropist<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/the-man-who-bailed-out-conrad-black/article1647276/ |title=This page is available to GlobePlus subscribers | work = [[The Globe and Mail]]|date= |accessdate=March 14, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Richard March Hoe]] (1812\u20131886) \u2013 inventor of rotary printing press <ref>The Inland Printer, Volume 69, \nMaclean-Hunter Publishing Corporation, 1922, p.851.</ref>\n* [[Collis Potter Huntington]] (1821\u20131900) \u2013 railroad and shipbuilding [[magnate]]; created the privately endowed [[Huntington Free Library and Reading Room]] near his summer home in the [[Throggs Neck]] neighborhood of the Bronx\n* [[Elaine Kaufman]] (1929\u20132010) \u2013 businessperson; proprietor of [[Elaine's]], a restaurant in the [[Manhattan]] [[borough (New York City)|borough]] of New York City that was a haunt of writers, actors, politicians<ref>[[Gay Talese|Talese, Gay]] (January 22, 2011). \"Four Hundred Dresses\". ''[[The New Yorker]]'', p. 22.</ref>\n* [[Calvin Klein]] (