nn Ligon]] (born 1960) \u2013 [[conceptual artist]]\n* [[Whitfield Lovell]]<ref>[http://www.lehman.cuny.edu/vpadvance/artgallery/gallery/whitfield_lovell/biographical_notes.htm Whitfield Lovell]</ref> (born 1959) \u2013 painter and [[installation artist]];<ref>{{cite web| author = [[John Yau|Yau, John]] |url=http://www.brooklynrail.org/2006/07/art/whitfield-lovell |title=Whitfield Lovell with John Yau | work = [[The Brooklyn Rail]] |date= July\u2013August 2006 |accessdate= October 29, 2011}}</ref> focuses on [[African American|African-American]] themes; [[MacArthur Fellows Program|MacArthur Fellow]] (2007)<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff |url=http://www.macfound.org/site/c.lkLXJ8MQKrH/b.2913825/apps/nl/content2.asp?content_id=%7B491135C4-E552-4ADB-80CA-B640676A5BF6%7D&notoc=1 |title=MacArthur Fellows 2007 \u2013 Whitfield Lovell |publisher=[[John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation]] |date=September 2007 |accessdate=October 29, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027032553/http://www.macfound.org/site/c.lkLXJ8MQKrH/b.2913825/apps/nl/content2.asp?content_id=%7B491135C4-E552-4ADB-80CA-B640676A5BF6%7D&notoc=1 |archivedate=October 27, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| author = Video (requires [[Adobe Flash]]; 00:02:11) | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a0S_C9ZjR10&feature=user |title=2007 MacArthur Fellow: Whitfield Lovell |publisher= [[John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation]] (via its [[YouTube]] channel) | date= June 11, 2008 |accessdate= October 29, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Joel Meyerowitz]] (born 1938) \u2013 [[photographer]]\n* [[Rick Meyerowitz]] (born 1943) \u2013 artist\n* [[Ralph Morse]] (1917\u20132015) \u2013 photographer\n* [[Piccirilli Brothers]] (including father, Giuseppe Piccirilli (1844\u20131910), and his six sons \u2013 Ferruccio (born 1864), [[Attilio Piccirilli|Attilio]] (1866\u20131945), [[Furio Piccirilli|Furio]] (1868\u20131949), Masaniello (1870\u20131951), Orazio (1872\u20131954) and Getulio (1874\u20131956)) \u2013 [[sculpture|sculptors]]\n* [[Louis Risse]] \u2013 French-born [[engineer]]; conceived of the [[Grand Concourse (Bronx)|Grand Concourse]], a boulevard in the Bronx<ref name=\"nytimes1\"/>\n* [[Larry Rivers]] (1923\u20132002) \u2013 artist\n* [[Joel Arthur Rosenthal]] (born 1943) \u2013 jeweler\n* [[Merryll Saylan]] (born 1936) \u2013 [[Woodturning|woodturner]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/interviews/oral-history-interview-merryll-saylan-13576|title=Oral history interview with Merryll Saylan, 2006 May 20-June 5|publisher=[[Archives of American Art]], [[Smithsonian Institution]]|date=2006|accessdate=September 22, 2019}}</ref> \n* [[Edwin Scheier]] (1910\u20132008) \u2013 artist\n* [[Phil Stern]] (1919\u20132014) \u2013 Hollywood, WWII and White House photographer<ref>Robert McFadden, \"Phil Stern, Photographer; Chronicler of Movie Stars and a President was 95\" ''New York Times, December 16, 2014\"</ref>\n* [[George Sugarman]] (1912\u20131999) \u2013 [[sculpture|sculptor]]<ref>{{cite news| author = [[Roberta Smith|Smith, Roberta]] |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CE1D9113BF932A0575BC0A96F958260 |title= George Sugarman, a Sculptor Of Colorful Works, Dies at 87 |work = [[The New York Times]] |date=August 31, 1999 |accessdate= October 28, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Raven B. Varona]] \u2013 phtographer.<ref>Kate Dwyer, \"A Photographer of the Hip-Hop Age.\" ''New York Times'', December 1, 2019, p. ST10</ref>\n* [[Lawrence Weiner]] (born 1942) \u2013 artist; associated with [[conceptual art]]\n* [[Marian Zazeela]] (born 1940) \u2013 [[light art]]ist, painter, and [[set design]]er; also musician of [[Hindustani classical music]]\n{{colend}}\n\n===Journalists and writers===\n[[File:P1020279.JPG|thumb|[[Edgar Allan Poe Cottage]] 2640 Grand Concourse, in the [[Fordham, Bronx|Fordham]] section of the Bronx. Poe spent the last few years of his life there.]]\n* [[Sholem Aleichem]] (1859\u20131916) \u2013 author\n* [[Nahshon Dion Anderson]