3 businessman and arts philanthropist; co-founder of [[Kaufman & Broad]]<ref>Bruch, Connie (December 10, 2010). \"The Art of the Billionaire\". ''[[The New Yorker]]''.</ref>\n* [[B. Gerald Cantor]] (1916\u20131996) \u2013 businessman; co-founder of [[securities]] firm [[Cantor Fitzgerald]]; with his wife Iris, amassed and then donated the largest private collection of sculptures by [[Auguste Rodin]]\n* [[Stanley Chais]] (1926\u20132010), investment advisor in the Madoff investment scandal\n* [[Fred DeLuca]] (1947\u20132015) \u2013 founder and CEO of Subway fast food sandwich chain\n* Richelieu Dennis \u2013 co-founder of Sundial Brands personal care products.<ref>[https://www.sundialbrands.com/our-story/]; Jeffrey Toobin, \"After Trump\", ''New Yorker'', Nov. 19, 2018, p.26.</ref>\n* [[Millard Drexler|Millard \"Mickey\" Drexler\"]] (born 1944) \u2013 businessman; chief executive officer of [[J. Crew]]; former chief executive officer of the [[Gap (clothing retailer)|Gap]]<ref>Paumgarten, Nick (September 20, 2010). \"The Merchant\" ''[[The New Yorker]]'',  pp. 74\u201387.</ref>\n* [[Reggie Fils-Aim\u00e9]] (born 1961) \u2013 president of Nintendo of America\n* [[Michael J. Freeman (inventor)|Michael J. Freeman]] (born 1947) \u2013 inventor, educator, business consultant, and entrepreneur\n* Mike Greco (1929-2019) \u2013 'salami king'<ref>Sam Roberts, \"Mike Greco, 89, Colorful 'Salami King' of Little Italy in the Bronx, Dies.\" ''New York Times, April 2, 2019''.</ref>\n* [[Harry Helmsley]] (1909\u20131997) \u2013 real estate magnate in New York City\n* [[Roger Hertog]] (born 1941) \u2013 co-founder of investment firm; co-publisher of ''[[The New Republic]]'' magazine; philanthropist<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/the-man-who-bailed-out-conrad-black/article1647276/ |title=This page is available to GlobePlus subscribers | work = [[The Globe and Mail]]|date= |accessdate=March 14, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Richard March Hoe]] (1812\u20131886) \u2013 inventor of rotary printing press <ref>The Inland Printer, Volume 69, \nMaclean-Hunter Publishing Corporation, 1922, p.851.</ref>\n* [[Collis Potter Huntington]] (1821\u20131900) \u2013 railroad and shipbuilding [[magnate]]; created the privately endowed [[Huntington Free Library and Reading Room]] near his summer home in the [[Throggs Neck]] neighborhood of the Bronx\n* [[Elaine Kaufman]] (1929\u20132010) \u2013 businessperson; proprietor of [[Elaine's]], a restaurant in the [[Manhattan]] [[borough (New York City)|borough]] of New York City that was a haunt of writers, actors, politicians<ref>[[Gay Talese|Talese, Gay]] (January 22, 2011). \"Four Hundred Dresses\". ''[[The New Yorker]]'', p. 22.</ref>\n* [[Calvin Klein]] (born 1942) \u2013 clothing designer\n* [[Ralph Lauren]] (born 1939) \u2013 clothing designer\n* [[George Lois]] (born 1932) \u2013 advertising<ref>James Barron, \"An Adman's Big Pitch: His Life Work\", ''New York Times'', January 18, 2016</ref>\n* [[William E. Macaulay]] (1945\u20132019) \u2013 billionaire businessman; CEO and chairman of [[First Reserve Corporation]]; co-founder of [[William E. Macaulay Honors College]] of [[City University of New York]]<ref>Sam Roberts, \"Wiliam E. Macaulay, 74, Patron of Tuition-Free College\", ''New York Times, December 8, 2019, p. 38.</ref>\n* [[Reuben and Rose Mattus]] (1912\u20131994; 1916\u20132006) \u2013 founders of [[H\u00e4agen-Dazs]] ice cream\n* [[Walton McCarthy]] (born 1951) \u2013 businessman and principal mechanical engineer with NORAD Shelter Systems \n* [[George Meany]] (1894\u20131980) \u2013 labor union leader: first president of the [[AFL-CIO]]\n* [[Jordan L. Mott]] (1799\u20131866) \u2013 inventor of coal kitchen stove, founder of J.L. Mott Ironworks in Mott Haven, and developer of the South Bronx neighborhood now named after him <ref>J.T.Scharf, History of Westchester County New York, Including Morrisania, Kings Bridge, and West Farms, which Have Been Annexed to New York City, Volume 1, Part 2, 1886, p. 831</ref> \n* [[Mark Penn]] (born 1954) \u2013 chief executive officer of the public-relations firm [[Burson-Marsteller]]; president of the polling firm [[Penn, Schoen & Berland|Penn, Schoen and Berland Associates]]\n* [[Sol Price]] (1916\u20132009) \u2013 founder of the [[Price Club]] and [[FedMart]] retail stores<ref>Fox, Margait (December 16, 2009). \"Sol Price, Who Founded Price Club, Is Dead at 93\". ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref>\n* Lewis Salton (1910\u20131997) \u2013 inventor and manufacturer of the Salton Hotray<ref>Malcolm Gladwell. ''What the Dog Saw''. p. 4. New York: Little, Brown; [[Russell Hobbs, Inc]]; \"Lewis L. Salton, 87, a Developer Of Quirky Household Appliances\". ''New York Times'', May 9, 1999. [https://www.nytimes.com/1999/05/09/business/lewis-l-salton-87-a-developer-of-quirky-household-appliances.html]</ref>\n* Fred Schwartz (1931\u20132016) \u2013 furrier, known nationally as \"Fred the Furrier\"<ref>Sam Roberts, \"Fred Schwartz is Dead at 84, Furrier and Philanthropist.\" ''New York Times,'' August 10, 2016</ref>\n* [[Fred Trump]] (1905\u20131999) \u2013 real estate developer; father of [[Donald Trump]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==Attorneys==\n* [[Pat Cipollone]] (born 1966) [Trump lawyer in impeachment case and elsewhere]<ref>Karen Freifeld, \"White House lawyer in Trump trial is both defender and key witness to events\". ''Reuters'', January 21, 2020. https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-impeachment-cipollone/white-house-lawyer-in-trump-trial-is-both-defender-and-key-witness-to-events-idUSKBN1ZK1DD?feedType=RSS&feedName=topNews</ref>\n[[Larry Fleisher]]\n*[[Hal Kant]]\n*[[Irving Picard]]\n*[[Melvyn Weiss]]\n\n==Infamous==\n{{colbegin|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[David Berkowitz]] (born 1953) \u2013 \"Son of Sam\" serial killer\n* [[Larry Davis (criminal)|Larry Davis]] (1966\u20132008) \u2013 drug dealer; shot multiple police officers{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}\n* [[John Gotti]] (1940\u20132002) \u2013 crime boss\n* [[Sidney Gottlieb]] (1918\u20131999) \u2013 American chemist who led the [[Central Intelligence Agency]]'s 1950s-1960s assassination attempts and mind control program, known as Project MKUltra\n* Moshe Lax (born 1974) \u2013 partner in [[Ivanka Trump]] Fine Jewelry; subject of multiple lawsuits<ref>Ben Schreckinger. \"The Trouble With Ivanka\u2019s Business Partner. ''Politico'', August 27, 2017\n [http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/08/27/ivanka-trump-business-partner-215544]</ref>\n*[[Jeffry Picower]] (1942\u20132009) \u2013 investor and philanthropist involved in the Madoff investment scandal\n* [[Morton Sobell]] (1917\u20132018) \u2013  convicted along with [[Julius Rosenberg]] and [[Ethel Rosenberg]] in 1951 of being a spy for the Soviet Union.<ref>[Michael Kaufman and Sam Roberts, \"Morton Sobell, 101, Who Spent Years Denying His Role as Soviet Spy, Dies, ''New York Times'', January 31, 2019]</ref> \n* [[Howard Spira]] \u2013 instrumental in [[George Steinbrenner]]'s ban from baseball\n{{colend}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Lists|New York City}}\n* [[List of people from New York City]]\n** [[List of people from Brooklyn]]<!--\n**[[List of people from Manhattan]]&nbsp;\u2013 added in October 2011, but hidden as list not yet created-->\n** [[List of people from Queens]]\n** [[List of people from Staten Island]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{Bronx}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of people from New York City|Bronx]]\n[[Category:Bronx-related lists|People]]\n[[Category:People from the Bronx| ]]\n", "name_user": "173.195.177.171", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eFilm, television, radio, dance and theatre)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_people_from_the_Bronx"}
{"title_page": "Muscle memory", "text_new": "{{For|the term \"muscle memory\" as related to strength training|Muscle memory (strength training)}}\n{{short description|form of procedural memory that involves consolidating a specific motor task into memory through repetition}}\n{{essay-like|date=February 2018}}\n'''Muscle memory''' is a form of [[procedural memory]] that involves consolidating a specific motor task into memory through repetition, which has been used synonymously with [[motor learning]]. When a movement is repeated over time, a long-term muscle memory is created for that task, eventually allowing it to be performed with little to no conscious effort. This process decreases the need for attention and creates maximum efficiency within the motor and memory systems. Examples of muscle memory are found in many everyday activities that become automatic and improve with practice, such as riding a bicycle, [[touch typing|typing on a keyboard]], entering a [[Personal identification number|PIN]], playing a musical instrument,<ref name = \"Krakauer\">{{cite journal | last1 = Krakauer | first1 = J.W. | last2 = Shadmehr | first2 = R. | year = 2006 | title = Consolidation of motor memory | url = | journal = Trends in Neurosciences | volume = 29 | issue = 1| pages = 58\u201364 | doi=10.1016/j.tins.2005.10.003| pmid = 16290273 | pmc = 2553888 }}</ref> [[poker]],<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=PGScALPm_xAC&pg=PT97&lpg=PT97&dq=muscle+memory+poker&source=bl&ots=oLO_dB9MhD&sig=jaM74OcKHPofUu-BGHYrR5fISFg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyjPvyzdnXAhWka5oKHaE3D6AQ6AEIXjAL#v=onepage&q=muscle%20memory%20poker&f=false Poker Face: How to win poker at the table and online - Judi James.]</ref> martial arts or even dancing.\n\n== History ==\n\nThe origins of research for the acquisition of motor skills stem from philosophers such as [[Plato]], [[Aristotle]] and [[Galen]].  After the break from tradition of the pre-1900s view of [[introspection]], psychologists emphasized research and more scientific methods in observing behaviours.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Adams | first1 = A.J. | year = 1987 | title = Historical Review and Appraisal of Research on the Learning, Retention, and Transfer of Human Motor Skills | url = | journal = Psychological Bulletin | volume = 101 | issue = 1| pages = 41\u201374 | doi=10.1037/0033-2909.101.1.41}}</ref> Thereafter, numerous studies exploring the role of motor learning were conducted. Such studies included the research of handwriting, and various practice methods to maximize motor learning.<ref name = \"Lee\">Lee, D.T., & Schmidt, A.R. (2005). Motor Control and Learning: A Behavioural Emphasis. (4th ed). Windsor, ON: Human Kinetics</ref>\n\n=== Retention ===\nThe retention of motor skills, now referred to as muscle memory, also began to be of great interest in the early 1900s. Most motor skills are thought to be acquired through practice; however, mere observation of the skill has led to learning as well.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Celnik | first1 = P. | last2 = Classen | first2 = J. | last3 = Cohen | first3 = G.L. | last4 = Duque | first4 = J. | last5 = Mazzocchio | first5 = R. | last6 = Sawaki | first6 = L. | last7 = Stephan | first7 = K. | last8 = Ungerleider | first8 = L. | year = 2005 | title = Formation of a Motor Memory by Action Observation | url = | journal = The Journal of Neuroscience | volume = 25 | issue = 41| pages = 9339\u20139346 | doi=10.1523/jneurosci.2282-05.2005| pmid = 16221842 | pmc = 6725701 }}</ref> Research suggests we do not start off with a blank slate with regard to motor memory although we do learn most of our motor memory repertoire during our lifetime.<ref name = \"Flanagan\">{{cite journal | last1 = Flanagan | first1 = R.J. | last2 = Ghahramani | first2 = Z. | last3 = Wolpert | first3 = M.D. | year = 2001 | title = Perspectives and Problems in Motor Learning | url = | journal = Trends in Cognitive Sciences | volume = 5 | issue = 11| pages = 487\u2013494 | doi=10.1016/s1364-6613(00)01773-3| pmid = 11684481 }}</ref> Movements such as facial expressions, which are thought to be learned, can actually be observed in children who are blind; thus there is some evidence for motor memory being genetically pre-wired.<ref name = \"Flanagan\" />\n\nIn the early stages of empirical research of motor memory [[Edward Thorndike]], a leading pioneer in the study of motor memory, was among the first to acknowledge learning can occur without conscious awareness.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Shanks | first1 = D.R. | last2 = St | last3 = John | first3 = M.F. | year = 1994 | title = Characteristics of Dissociable Human Learning Systems | url = http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/142639/1/download2.pdf| journal = Behavioral and Brain Sciences | volume = 17 | issue = 3| pages = 367\u2013447 | doi=10.1017/s0140525x00035032}}</ref> One of the earliest and most notable studies regarding the retention of motor skills was by Hill, Rejall, and Thorndike, who showed savings in relearning typing skills after a 25-year period with no practice.<ref name = \"Lee\" /> Findings related to the retention of learned motor skills have been continuously replicated in studies, suggesting that through subsequent practice, motor learning is stored in the brain as memory. This is why performing skills such as riding a bike or driving a car are effortlessly and 'subconsciously' executed, even if someone had not performed these skills in a long period of time.<ref name = \"Lee\" />\n\n==Physiology==\n\n===Motor behavior===\nWhen first learning a motor task, movement is often slow, stiff and easily disrupted without attention. With practice, execution of motor task becomes smoother, there is a decrease in limb stiffness, and muscle activity necessary to the task is performed without conscious effort.<ref name = \"Shadmehr\">{{cite journal | last1 = Shadmehr | first1 = R | last2 = Holcomb | first2 = HH | year = 1997 | title = Neural correlates of motor memory consolidation | url = | journal = Science | volume = 277 | issue = 5327| pages = 821\u201325 | doi=10.1126/science.277.5327.821}}</ref>\n\n===Muscle memory encoding===\n\nThe [[neuroanatomy of memory]] is widespread throughout the [[brain]]; however, the pathways important to motor memory are separate from the medial [[temporal lobe]] pathways associated with [[declarative memory]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Brashers-Krug | first1 = T | last2 = Shadmehr | first2 = R. | last3 = Bizzi | first3 = E. | year = 1996 | title = Consolidation in human motor memory | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 382 | issue = 6588| pages = 252\u2013255| doi=10.1038/382252a0| pmid = 8717039 | bibcode = 1996Natur.382..252B| citeseerx = 10.1.1.39.3383 }}</ref>  As with declarative memory, motor memory is theorized to have two stages: a short-term [[memory encoding]] stage, which is fragile and susceptible to damage, and a long-term [[memory consolidation]] stage, which is more stable.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Atwell | first1 = P. | last2 = Cooke | first2 = S. | last3 = Yeo | first3 = C. | year = 2002 | title = Cerebellar function in consolidation of motor memory | url = | journal = Neuron | volume = 34 | issue = 6| pages = 1011\u20131020 | doi=10.1016/s0896-6273(02)00719-5}}</ref> \n  \nThe memory encoding stage is often referred to as [[motor learning]], and requires an increase in brain activity in motor areas as well as an increase in attention. Brain areas active during motor learning include the motor and somatosensory cortices; however, these areas of activation decrease once the motor skill is learned. The prefrontal and frontal cortices are also active during this stage due to the need for increased attention on the task being learned.<ref name = \"Shadmehr\" />\n\nThe main area involved in motor learning is the [[cerebellum]]. Some models of cerebellar-dependent motor learning, in particular the Marr-Albus model, propose a single plasticity mechanism involving the cerebellar [[long-term depression]] (LTD) of the parallel fiber synapses onto [[Purkinje cells]].  These modifications in synapse activity would mediate motor input with motor outputs critical to inducing motor learning.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Boyden | first1 = E. | last2 = Katoh | first2 = A. | last3 = Raymond | first3 = J. | year = 2004 | title = Cerebellum-dependent learning: the role of multiple plasticity mechanisms | url = | journal = Annu. Rev. Neurosci. | volume = 27 | issue = | pages = 581\u2013609 | doi=10.1146/annurev.neuro.27.070203.144238 | pmid=15217344}}</ref> However, conflicting evidence suggests that a single plasticity mechanism is not sufficient and a multiple plasticity mechanism is needed to account for the storage of motor memories over time. Regardless of the mechanism, studies of cerebellar-dependent  motor tasks show that cerebral cortical plasticity is crucial for motor learning, even if not necessarily for storage.<ref name = \"Ma\" />\n\nThe [[basal ganglia]] also play an important role in memory and learning, in particular in reference to stimulus-response associations and the formation of habits. The basal ganglia-cerebellar connections are thought to increase with time when learning a motor task.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Packard | first1 = M. | last2 = Knowlton | first2 = B. | year = 2002 | title = Learning and memory functions of the basal ganglia.  | url = | journal = Annu. Rev. Neurosci. | volume = 25 | issue = | pages = 563\u201393 | pmid = 12052921 | doi = 10.1146/annurev.neuro.25.112701.142937 }}</ref>\n\n===Muscle memory consolidation===\nMuscle memory consolidation involves the continuous evolution of neural processes after practicing a task has stopped. The exact mechanism of motor memory consolidation within the brain is controversial. However, most theories assume that there is a general redistribution of information across the brain from encoding to consolidation.  [[Hebb's rule]] states that \"synaptic connectivity changes as a function of repetitive firing.\" In this case, that would mean that the high amount of stimulation coming from practicing a movement would cause the repetition of firing in certain motor networks, presumably leading to an increase in the efficiency of exciting these motor networks over time.<ref name= \"Ma\">{{cite journal | last1 = Ma | first1 = L. | display-authors = etal   | year = 2010| title = ,. (2010). Changes in regional activity are accompanied with changes in inter-regional connectivity during 4 weeks motor learning | journal = Brain Res. | volume =  1318| issue = | pages =  64\u201376| doi = 10.1016/j.brainres.2009.12.073 | pmid=20051230 | pmc=2826520}}</ref>\n\nThough the exact location of muscle memory storage is not known, studies have suggested that it is the inter-regional connections that play the most important role in advancing motor memory encoding to consolidation, rather than decreases in overall regional activity.  These studies have shown a weakened connection from the cerebellum to the primary motor area with practice, it is presumed, because of a decreased need for error correction from the cerebellum. However, the connection between the basal ganglia and the primary motor area is strengthened, suggesting the basal ganglia play an important role in the motor memory consolidation process.<ref name = \"Ma\" />\n\n===Strength training and adaptations===\n{{See also|Muscle memory (strength training)}}\nWhen participating in any sport, new motor skills and movement combinations are frequently being used and repeated. All sports require some degree of strength, endurance training, and skilled reaching in order to be successful in the required tasks. Muscle memory related to [[Muscle memory (strength training)|strength training]]  involves elements of both motor learning, described below, and long-lasting changes in the muscle tissue.\n\nEvidence has shown that increases in strength occur well before muscle [[hypertrophy]], and decreases in strength due to detraining or ceasing to repeat the exercise over an extended period of time precede muscle [[atrophy]].<ref name = \"Adkins\">{{cite journal | last1 = Adkins | first1 = DeAnna L. | last2 = Boychuck | first2 = Jeffery | year = 2006 | title = Motor training induces experience specific patterns of plasticity across motor cortex and spinal cord | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/3d63cc947cfcc449d69c520ee3b6099c9d4bc243| journal = Journal of Applied Physiology | volume = 101 | issue = 6| pages = 1776\u20131782 | doi=10.1152/japplphysiol.00515.2006 | pmid=16959909}}</ref> To be specific, strength training enhances [[motor neuron]] excitability and induces [[synaptogenesis]], both of which would help in enhancing communication between the nervous system and the muscles themselves.<ref name = \"Adkins\" /> [[File:US Navy 071017-N-0995C-008 Chief Mineman Kevin Sperling, an officer recruiter at Navy Recruiting Processing Station Honolulu, presses two 105-pound dumbbells.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A navy man performs strength training exercises.]]However, neuromuscular efficacy is not altered within a two-week time period following cessation of the muscle usage; instead, it is merely the [[neuron]]'s ability to excite the muscle that declines in correlation with the muscle's decrease in strength.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Deschenes Michael | first1 = R. | last2 = Giles Jennifer | first2 = A. | year = 2002 | title = Neural factors account for strength decrements observed after short-term muscle unloading | url = | journal = American Journal of Physiology. Regulatory, Integrative and Comparative Physiology | volume = 282 | issue = 2| pages = R578\u2013R583 | doi=10.1152/ajpregu.00386.2001| pmid = 11792669 }}</ref> This confirms that muscle strength is first influenced by the inner neural circuitry, rather than by external physiological changes in the muscle size.\n\nPreviously untrained muscles acquire newly formed nuclei by fusion of satellite cells preceding the hypertrophy. Subsequent detraining leads to atrophy but no loss of myo-nuclei. The elevated number of nuclei in muscle fibers that had experienced a hypertrophic episode would provide a mechanism for muscle memory, explaining the long-lasting effects of training and the ease with which previously trained individuals are more easily retrained.<ref name = \"bru\">{{cite journal | last1 = Bruusgaard | first1 = J. C. | display-authors = etal   | year = 2010 | title = Myonuclei acquired by overload exercise precede hypertrophy and are not lost on detraining | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences | volume = 107 | issue = 34| pages = 15111\u201315116 | doi=10.1073/pnas.0913935107 | pmid=20713720 | pmc=2930527| bibcode = 2010PNAS..10715111B }}</ref>\n\nOn subsequent detraining, the fibers maintain an elevated number of nuclei that might provide resistance to atrophy; on retraining, a gain in size can be\nobtained by a moderate increase in the protein synthesis rate of each of these many nuclei, skipping the step of adding newly formed nuclei. This shortcut may contribute to the relative ease of retraining compared with the first training of individuals with no\nprevious training history.<ref name = \"bru\" />\n\nReorganization of motor maps within the cortex are not altered in either strength or endurance training. However, within the motor cortex, endurance induces [[angiogenesis]] within as little as three weeks to increase blood flow to the involved regions.<ref name = \"Adkins\" /> In addition, neurotropic factors within the motor cortex are [[upregulated]] in response to endurance training to promote neural survival.<ref name = \"Adkins\" />\n\nSkilled motor tasks have been divided into two distinct phases: a fast-learning phase, in which an optimal plan for performance is established, and a slow-learning phase, in which longer-term structural modifications are made on specific motor modules.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Karni | first1 = Avi | last2 = Meyer | first2 = Gundela | year = 1998 | title = The acquisition of skilled motor performance: Fast and slow experience-driven changes in primary motor cortex | url = | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences | volume = 95| issue = 3| pages = 861\u2013868 | doi=10.1073/pnas.95.3.861| pmid = 9448252 | pmc = 33809| bibcode = 1998PNAS...95..861K}}</ref> Even a small amount of training may be enough to induce neural processes that continue to evolve even after the training has stopped, which provides a potential basis for consolidation of the task. In addition, studying mice while they are learning a new complex reaching task, has found that \"motor learning leads to rapid formation of [[dendritic spines]] (spinogenesis) in the [[motor cortex]] contralateral to the reaching forelimb\".<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Xu | first1 = Tonghui | last2 = Perlik | first2 = Andrew J | year = 2009 | title = Rapid formation and selective stabilisation of synapses for enduring motor memories | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 462| issue = 7275| pages = 915\u201320 | doi=10.1038/nature08389 | pmid=19946267 | pmc=2844762| bibcode = 2009Natur.462..915X}}</ref>  However, motor cortex reorganization itself does not occur at a uniform rate across training periods. It has been suggested that the synaptogenesis and motor map reorganization merely represent the consolidation, and not the acquisition itself, of a specific motor task.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Kleim Jerrery | first1 = L. | last2 = Hogg Theresa | first2 = M. | year = 2004 | title = Cortical Synaptogenesis and Motor Map Reorganization Occur during Late, But not Early, Phase of Motor Skill Learning | url = | journal = The Journal of Neuroscience | volume = 24 | issue = 3| pages = 629\u2013633 | doi=10.1523/jneurosci.3440-03.2004 | pmid=14736848| pmc = 6729261 | citeseerx = 10.1.1.320.2189 }}</ref>  Furthermore, the degree of plasticity in various locations (namely motor cortex versus spinal cord) is dependent on the behavioural demands and nature of the task (i.e., skilled reaching versus strength training).<ref name = \"Adkins\" />\n\nWhether strength or endurance related, it is plausible that the majority of motor movements would require a skilled moving task of some form, whether it be maintaining proper form when paddling a canoe, or bench pressing a heavier weight. Endurance training assists the formation of these new neural representations within the motor cortex by up regulating neurotropic factors that could enhance the survival of the newer neural maps formed due to the skilled movement training.<ref name = \"Adkins\" /> Strength training results are seen in the spinal cord well before any physiological muscular adaptation is established through muscle hypertrophy or atrophy.<ref name = \"Adkins\" /> The results of endurance and strength training, and skilled reaching, therefore, combine to help each other maximize performance output.\n\nMore recently, research has suggested that epigenetics may play a distinct role in orchestrating a muscle memory phenomenon <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sharples|first1=Adam P.|last2=Stewart|first2=Claire E.|last3=Seaborne|first3=Robert A.|title=Does skeletal muscle have an 'epi'-memory? The role of epigenetics in nutritional programming, metabolic disease, aging and exercise|journal=Aging Cell|date=1 August 2016|volume=15|issue=4|pages=603\u2013616|doi=10.1111/acel.12486|pmid=27102569|pmc=4933662|language=en|issn=1474-9726}}</ref> Indeed, previously untrained human participants experienced a chronic period of resistance exercise training (7 weeks) that evoked significant increases in skeletal muscle mass of the vastus lateralis muscle, in the quadriceps muscle group. Following a similar period of physical in-activity (7 weeks), where strength and muscle mass returned to baseline, participants performed a secondary period of resistance exercise.<ref name = \"seaborne\">{{cite journal|last1=Seaborne|first1=Robert A.|last2=Strauss|first2=Juliette|last3=Cocks|first3=Matthew|last4=Shepherd|first4=Sam|last5=O\u2019Brien|first5=Thomas D.|last6=Someren|first6=Ken A. van|last7=Bell|first7=Phillip G.|last8=Murgatroyd|first8=Christopher|last9=Morton|first9=James P.|last10=Stewart|first10=Claire E.|last11=Sharples|first11=Adam P.|title=Human Skeletal Muscle Possesses an Epigenetic Memory of Hypertrophy|journal=Scientific Reports|date=30 January 2018|volume=8|issue=1|pages=1898|doi=10.1038/s41598-018-20287-3|pmid=29382913|pmc=5789890|language=En|issn=2045-2322|bibcode=2018NatSR...8.1898S}}</ref> Importantly, these participants adapted in an enhanced manner, whereby the amount of skeletal muscle mass gained was greater in the second period of muscle growth then the first, suggesting a muscle memory concept. The researchers went on to examine the human epigenome in order to understand how DNA methylation may aid in creating this effect. During the first period of resistance exercise, the authors identify significant adaptations in the human methylome, whereby over 9,000 CpG sites were reported as being significantly hypomethylated, with these adaptations being sustained during the subsequent period of physical in-activity. However, upon secondary exposure to resistance exercise, a greater frequency of hypomethylated CpG sites was observed, where over 18,000 sites reported as being significantly hypomethylated. The authors went on to identify how these changes altered the expression of relevant transcripts, and subsequently correlated these changes with adaptations in skeletal muscle mass. Collectively, the authors conclude that skeletal muscle mass and muscle memory phenomenon is, at least in part, modulated due to changes in DNA methylation.<ref name = \"seaborne\" /> Further work is now needed to confirm and explore these findings.\n\n==Fine motor memory==\n\n[[Fine motor skills]] are often discussed in terms of transitive movements, which are those done when using tools (which could be as simple as a tooth brush or pencil).<ref name = \"Dowell\">{{cite journal | last1 = Dowell | first1 = L. R. | last2 = Mahone | first2 = E. M. | last3 = Mostofsky | first3 = S. H. | year = 2009 | title = Associations of postural knowledge and basic motor skill with dyspraxia in autism: Implication for abnormalities in distributed connectivity and motor learning | url = | journal = Neuropsychology | volume = 23 | issue = 5| pages = 563\u2013570 | doi=10.1037/a0015640| pmid = 19702410 | pmc = 2740626 }}</ref> Transitive movements have representations that become programmed to the [[premotor cortex]], creating motor programs that result in the activation of the [[motor cortex]] and therefore the motor movements.<ref name = \"Dowell\" /> In a study testing the motor memory of patterned finger movements (a fine motor skill) it was found that retention of certain skills is susceptible to disruption if another task interferes with one's motor memory.<ref name = \"Krakauer\"/> However, such susceptibility can be reduced with time. For example, if a finger pattern is learned and another finger pattern is learned six hours later, the first pattern will still be remembered. But attempting to learn two such patterns one immediately after the other could cause the first one to be forgotten.<ref name = \"Krakauer\" /> Furthermore, the heavy use of computers by recent generations has had both positive and negative effects. One of the main positive effects is an enhancement of children's fine motor skills.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Straker | first1 = L. | last2 = Pollock | first2 = C. | last3 = Maslen | first3 = B. | year = 2009 | title = Principles for the wise use of computers by children | url = | journal = Ergonomics | volume = 52 | issue = 11| pages = 1386\u20131401 | doi=10.1080/00140130903067789| pmid = 19851906 | citeseerx = 10.1.1.468.7070 }}</ref> Repetitive behaviors, such as typing on a computer from a young age, can enhance such abilities. Therefore, children who learn to use computer keyboards at an early age could benefit from the early muscle memories.\n\n===Music memory===\n[[File:Playing the piano.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Bimanual synchronized finger movements play an essential role in piano playing.|Playing the piano requires complex actions]]  \nFine motor skills are very important in playing musical instruments. It was found that muscle memory is relied on when playing the clarinet, specifically to help create special effects through certain tongue movements when blowing air into the instrument.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Fritz | first1 = C. | last2 = Wolfe | first2 = J. | year = 2005 | title = How do clarinet players adjust the resonances of their vocal tracts for different playing effects? | url = | journal = Journal of the Acoustical Society of America | volume = 118 | issue = 5| pages = 3306\u20133315 | doi=10.1121/1.2041287| arxiv = physics/0505195 | bibcode = 2005ASAJ..118.3306F }}</ref>\n\nCertain human behaviours, especially actions like the finger movements in musical performances, are very complex and require many interconnected neural networks where information can be transmitted across multiple brain regions.<ref name = \"Kim\">{{cite journal | last1 = Kim | first1 = D. | last2 = Shin | first2 = M. | last3 = Lee | first3 = K. | last4 = Chu | first4 = K. | last5 = Woo | first5 = S. | last6 = Kim | first6 = Y. | last7 = Song | first7 = E. | last8 = Lee | first8 = Jun | last9 = Park | first9 = S. | last10 = Roh | first10 = J. | year = 2004 | title = Musical Training-Induced Functional Reorganization of the Adult Brain: Functional Magnetic Resonance Imaging and Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation Study on Amateur String Players | url = | journal = Human Brain Mapping | volume = 23 | issue = 4| pages = 188\u2013199 | doi=10.1002/hbm.20058| pmid = 15449354 }}</ref>  It has been found that there are often functional differences in the brains of professional musicians, when compared to other individuals. This is thought to reflect the musician's innate ability, which may be fostered by an early exposure to musical training.<ref name = \"Kim\" /> An example of this is bimanual synchronized finger movements, which play an essential role in piano playing. It is suggested that bimanual coordination can come only from years of bimanual training, where such actions become adaptations of the motor areas.<ref name = \"Haslinger\">{{cite journal | last1 = Haslinger | first1 = B. | last2 = Erhard | first2 = P. | last3 = Altenm\u00fcller | first3 = E. | last4 = Hennenlotter | first4 = A. | last5 = Schwaiger | first5 = M. | last6 = von Einsiedel | first6 = H. G. | last7 = Rummeny | first7 = E. | last8 = Conrad | first8 = B. | last9 = Ceballos-Baumann | first9 = A. O. | year = 2004 | title = Reduced Recruitment of Motor Association Areas During Bimanual Coordination in Concert Pianists | url = | journal = Human Brain Mapping | volume = 22 | issue = 3| pages = 206\u2013215 | doi=10.1002/hbm.20028| pmid = 15195287 }}</ref> When comparing professional musicians to a control group in complex bimanual movements, professionals are found to use an extensive motor network much less than those non-professionals.<ref name = \"Haslinger\" /> This is because professionals rely on a motor system that has increased efficiency, and, therefore, those less trained have a network that is more strongly activated.<ref name = \"Haslinger\" />  It is implied that the untrained pianists have to invest more neuronal activity to have the same level of performance that is achieved by professionals.<ref name = \"Haslinger\" /> This, yet again, is said to be a consequence of many years of motor training and experience that helps form a fine motor memory skill of musical performance.\n\nIt is often reported that, when a pianist hears a well-trained piece of music, synonymous fingering can be involuntarily triggered.<ref name = \"Kim\" /> This implies that there is a coupling between the perception of music and the motor activity of those musically trained individuals.<ref name = \"Kim\" /> Therefore, one's muscle memory in the context of music can easily be triggered when one hears certain familiar pieces. Overall, long-term musical fine motor training allows for complex actions to be performed at a lower level of movement control, monitoring, selection, attention, and timing.<ref name = \"Haslinger\" /> This leaves room for musicians to focus attention synchronously elsewhere, such as on the artistic aspect of the performance, without having to consciously control one's fine motor actions.<ref name = \"Haslinger\" />\n\n===Puzzle cube memory===\n{{refimprove section|date=March 2016}}\n[[File:Erik Akkersdijk is solving a 3\u00d73\u00d73 Rubik's Cube in 10.50s.ogv|thumb|[[Erik Akkersdijk]] is solving a 3\u00d73\u00d73 [[Rubik's Cube]] in 10.50s.]]\n[[Speed cubing|Speed cubers]] often will use muscle memory in order to learn large numbers of [[algorithm]]s quickly. It is quickly found that memorization purely of letters corresponding to moves on the cube is extremely difficult. The average beginner will try to do something like this; however, an advanced cuber can learn much more efficiently with muscle memory. A simple repetition of algorithms will create a long-term knowledge of it.  This plays a role in major speedcubing methods such as [[Fridrich method|Fridrich]] for the 3\u00d73\u00d73 [[Rubik's Cube]] and EG for the 2\u00d72\u00d72 [[Pocket cube]].\n\n== Gross motor memory ==\n[[Gross motor skill]]s are concerned with the movement of large muscles, or major body movements, such as those involved in walking or kicking, and are associated with normal development.<ref name = \"Gross\">{{cite web |title=Gross motor Skills \u2013 What are Gross Motor Skills |url=http://learningdisabilities.about.com/od/gi/p/grossmotorskill.htm }}</ref> The extent to which one exhibits gross motor skills depends largely on their muscle tone and the strength.<ref name = \"Gross\" /> In a study looking at people with Down Syndrome, it was found that the pre-existing deficits, with regard to verbal-motor performance, limits the individual's transfer of gross motor skills following visual and verbal instruction to verbal instruction only.<ref name=\"Meegan\">{{cite journal |last=Meegan |first=S. |last2=Maraj |first2=B. K. V. |last3=Weeks |first3=D. |last4=Chua |first4=R. |year=2006 |title=Gross Motor Skill Acquisition in Adolescents With Down Syndrom |journal=Down Syndrome and Practice |volume=9 |issue=3 |pages=75\u201380 |doi= 10.3104/reports.298|pmid=16869378 |url=https://assets.cdn.down-syndrome.org/pubs/a/reports-298.pdf }}</ref> The fact that the individuals could still exhibit two of the three original motor skills may have been a result of positive transfer in which previous exposure allows the individual to remember the motion, under the visual and verbal trial, and then later perform it under the verbal trial.<ref name = \"Meegan\" />\n\n=== Learning in childhood ===\nThe way in which a child learns a gross motor skill can affect how long it takes to consolidate it and be able to reproduce the movement.  In a study with preschoolers, looking at the role of self-instruction on acquiring complex gross motor chains using [[ballet]] positions, it was found that the motor skills were better learned and remembered with the self-instruction procedure over the no-self-instruction procedure.<ref name=\"Vintere\">{{cite journal |last=Vintere |first=P. |last2=Hemmes |first2=N. S. |last3=Brown |first3=B. L. |last4=Poulson |first4=C. L. |year=2004 |title=Gross-Motor Skill Acquisition by Preschool Dance Stoudents Under Self-Instruction Procedures |journal=Journal of Applied Behavior Analysis |volume=37 |issue=3 |pages=305\u2013322 |doi= 10.1901/jaba.2004.37-305|pmc=1284506 |pmid=15529888}}</ref> This suggests that the use of self-instruction will increase the speed with which a preschooler will learn and remember a gross motor skill. It was also found that, once the preschoolers learned and mastered the motor chain movements, they ceased the use of self-instruction. This suggests that the memory for the movements became strong enough that there was no longer a need for self-instruction and the movements could be reproduced without it.<ref name=\"Vintere\" />\n\n=== Effect of Alzheimer's disease ===\nIt has been suggested that consistent practice of a gross motor skill can help a patient with [[Alzheimer's disease]] learn and remember that skill.  It was thought that the damage to the [[hippocampus]] may result in the need for a specific type of learning requirement.<ref name=\"Dick\">{{cite journal |last=Dick |first=M. B. |last2=Shankle |first2=R. W. |last3=Beth |first3=R. E. |last4=Dick-Muehlke |first4=C. |last5=Cotman |first5=C. W. |last6=Kean |first6=M. L. |year=1996 |title=Acquisition and long-term retention of a gross motor skill in Alzheimer's disease patients under constant and varied practice conditions |journal=The Journals of Gerontology Series B: Psychological Sciences and Social Sciences |volume=51B |issue=2 |pages=103\u2013111 |doi=10.1093/geronb/51B.2.P103 }}</ref> A study was created to test this assumption in which the patients were trained to throw a bean bag at a target.<ref name=\"Dick\" /> It was found that the Alzheimer's patients performed better on the task when learning occurred under constant training as opposed to variable.  Also, it was found that gross motor memory in Alzheimer's patients was the same as that of healthy adults when learning occurs under constant practice.<ref name=\"Dick\" /> This suggests that damage to the hippocampal system does not impair an Alzheimer's patient from retaining new gross motor skills, implying that motor memory for gross motor skills is stored elsewhere in the brain. However there isn't much evidence provided on this.\n\n== Impairment ==\nIt is difficult to display cases of \"pure\" motor memory impairment because the memory system is so widespread throughout the brain that damage is not often isolated to one specific type of memory.  Likewise,  diseases commonly associated with motor deficits, such as [[Huntington's]] and [[Parkinson's disease]], have a wide variety of symptoms and associated brain damage that make it impossible to pinpoint whether or not motor memory is in fact impaired.  Case studies have provided some examples of how motor memory has been implemented in patients with brain damage.\n\nAs Edward S. Casey notes in Remembering, Second Edition: A Phenomenological Study,  declarative memory, a process that involves an initial fragile learning period. \"The activity of the past, in short, resides in its habitual enactment in the present.\"\n\n=== Consolidation deficit ===\nA recent issue in motor memory is whether or not it consolidates in a manner similar to declarative memory, a process that involves an initial fragile learning period that eventually becomes stable and less susceptible to damage over time.<ref name = \"Krakauer\" /> An example of stable motor memory consolidation in a patient with brain damage is the case of [[Clive Wearing]]. Clive has severe anterograde and retrograde amnesia owing to damage in his temporal lobes, frontal lobes, and hippocampi, which prevents him from storing any new memories and making him aware of only the present moment. However, Clive still retains access to his procedural memories, to be specific, the motor memories involved in playing the piano. This could be because motor memory is demonstrated through savings over several trials of learning, whereas declarative memory is demonstrated through recall of a single item.<ref name = \"Krakauer\" />  This suggests that lesions in certain brain areas normally associated with declarative memory would not affect motor memory for a well-learned skill.\n\n=== Dysgraphia for the alphabet ===\nCase study: 54-year-old woman with known history of [[epilepsy]]\n\t\nThis patient was diagnosed with a pure form of [[dysgraphia]] of letters, meaning he had no other speech or reading impairments.<ref name=\"Kapur\">{{cite journal |last=Kapur |first=N. |last2=Lawton |first2=N. F. |year=1983 |title=Dysgraphia for Letters: a Form of Motor Memory Deficit? |journal=Journal of Neurological Psychiatry |volume=46 |issue=6 |pages=573\u2013575 |doi=10.1136/jnnp.46.6.573 |pmid=6875593 |pmc=1027454 }}</ref> His impairment was specific to letters in the alphabet. He was able to copy letters from the alphabet, but he was not able to write these letters.<ref name = \"Kapur\" /> He had previously been rated average on the [[Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale]]'s vocabulary subtest for writing ability comparative to his age before his diagnosis.<ref name=\"Kapur\" /> His writing impairment consisted of difficulty remembering motor movements associated with the letters he was supposed to write.<ref name=\"Kapur\" /> He was able to copy the letters, and also form images that were similar to the letters.<ref name=\"Kapur\" /> This suggests that dysgraphia for letters is a deficit related to motor memory.<ref name=\"Kapur\" /> Somehow there is a specific portion of the brain related to writing letters, which is dissociated from copying and drawing letter-like items.\n\n== See also ==\n*{{annotated link|Automaticity}}\n*{{annotated link|Procedural memory}}\n*{{annotated link|Motor learning}}\n*{{annotated link|Motor coordination}}\n*{{annotated link|Muscle}}\n*{{annotated link|Memory consolidation}}\n*{{annotated link|Overlearning}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{memory}}\n{{Muscular system}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Muscle Memory}}\n[[Category:Memory]]\n[[Category:Memory processes]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the term \"muscle memory\" as related to strength training|Muscle memory (strength training)}}\n{{short description|form of procedural memory that involves consolidating a specific motor task into memory through repetition}}\n{{essay-like|date=February 2018}}\n'''Muscle memory''' is a form of [[procedural memory]] that involves consolidating a specific motor task into memory through repetition, which has been used synonymously with [[motor learning]]. When a movement is repeated over time, a long-term muscle memory is created for that task, eventually allowing it to be performed with little to no conscious effort. This process decreases the need for attention and creates maximum efficiency within the motor and memory systems. Examples of muscle memory are found in many everyday activities that become automatic and improve with practice, such as riding a bicycle, [[touch typing|typing on a keyboard]], entering a [[Personal identification number|PIN]], playing a musical instrument,<ref name = \"Krakauer\">{{cite journal | last1 = Krakauer | first1 = J.W. | last2 = Shadmehr | first2 = R. | year = 2006 | title = Consolidation of motor memory | url = | journal = Trends in Neurosciences | volume = 29 | issue = 1| pages = 58\u201364 | doi=10.1016/j.tins.2005.10.003| pmid = 16290273 | pmc = 2553888 }}</ref> [[poker]],<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=PGScALPm_xAC&pg=PT97&lpg=PT97&dq=muscle+memory+poker&source=bl&ots=oLO_dB9MhD&sig=jaM74OcKHPofUu-BGHYrR5fISFg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyjPvyzdnXAhWka5oKHaE3D6AQ6AEIXjAL#v=onepage&q=muscle%20memory%20poker&f=false Poker Face: How to win poker at the table and online - Judi James.]</ref> martial arts or even dancing.\n\n== History ==\n\nThe origins of research for the acquisition of motor skills stem from philosophers such as [[Plato]], [[Aristotle]] and [[Galen]].  After the break from tradition of the pre-1900s view of [[introspection]], psychologists emphasized research and more scientific methods in observing behaviours.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Adams | first1 = A.J. | year = 1987 | title = Historical Review and Appraisal of Research on the Learning, Retention, and Transfer of Human Motor Skills | url = | journal = Psychological Bulletin | volume = 101 | issue = 1| pages = 41\u201374 | doi=10.1037/0033-2909.101.1.41}}</ref> Thereafter, numerous studies exploring the role of motor learning were conducted. Such studies included the research of handwriting, and various practice methods to maximize motor learning.<ref name = \"Lee\">Lee, D.T., & Schmidt, A.R. (2005). Motor Control and Learning: A Behavioural Emphasis. (4th ed). Windsor, ON: Human Kinetics</ref>\n\n=== Retention ===\nThe retention of motor skills, now referred to as muscle memory, also began to be of great interest in the early 1900s. Most motor skills are thought to be acquired through practice; however, mere observation of the skill has led to learning as well.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Celnik | first1 = P. | last2 = Classen | first2 = J. | last3 = Cohen | first3 = G.L. | last4 = Duque | first4 = J. | last5 = Mazzocchio | first5 = R. | last6 = Sawaki | first6 = L. | last7 = Stephan | first7 = K. | last8 = Ungerleider | first8 = L. | year = 2005 | title = Formation of a Motor Memory by Action Observation | url = | journal = The Journal of Neuroscience | volume = 25 | issue = 41| pages = 9339\u20139346 | doi=10.1523/jneurosci.2282-05.2005| pmid = 16221842 | pmc = 6725701 }}</ref> Research suggests we do not start off with a blank slate with regard to motor memory although we do learn most of our motor memory repertoire during our lifetime.<ref name = \"Flanagan\">{{cite journal | last1 = Flanagan | first1 = R.J. | last2 = Ghahramani | first2 = Z. | last3 = Wolpert | first3 = M.D. | year = 2001 | title = Perspectives and Problems in Motor Learning | url = | journal = Trends in Cognitive Sciences | volume = 5 | issue = 11| pages = 487\u2013494 | doi=10.1016/s1364-6613(00)01773-3| pmid = 11684481 }}</ref> Movements such as facial expressions, which are thought to be learned, can actually be observed in children who are blind; thus there is some evidence for motor memory being genetically pre-wired.<ref name = \"Flanagan\" />\n\nIn the early stages of empirical research of motor memory [[Edward Thorndike]], a leading pioneer in the study of motor memory, was among the first to acknowledge learning can occur without conscious awareness.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Shanks | first1 = D.R. | last2 = St | last3 = John | first3 = M.F. | year = 1994 | title = Characteristics of Dissociable Human Learning Systems | url = http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/142639/1/download2.pdf| journal = Behavioral and Brain Sciences | volume = 17 | issue = 3| pages = 367\u2013447 | doi=10.1017/s0140525x00035032}}</ref> One of the earliest and most notable studies regarding the retention of motor skills was by Hill, Rejall, and Thorndike, who showed savings in relearning typing skills after a 25-year period with no practice.<ref name = \"Lee\" /> Findings related to the retention of learned motor skills have been continuously replicated in studies, suggesting that through subsequent practice, motor learning is stored in the brain as memory. This is why performing skills such as riding a bike or driving a car are effortlessly and 'subconsciously' executed, even if someone had not performed these skills in a long period of time.<ref name = \"Lee\" />\n\n==Physiology==\n\n===Motor behavior===\nWhen first learning a motor task, movement is often slow, stiff and easily disrupted without attention. With practice, execution of motor task becomes smoother, there is a decrease in limb stiffness, and muscle activity necessary to the task is performed without conscious effort.<ref name = \"Shadmehr\">{{cite journal | last1 = Shadmehr | first1 = R | last2 = Holcomb | first2 = HH | year = 1997 | title = Neural correlates of motor memory consolidation | url = | journal = Science | volume = 277 | issue = 5327| pages = 821\u201325 | doi=10.1126/science.277.5327.821}}</ref>\n\n===Muscle memory encoding===\n\nThe [[neuroanatomy of memory]] is widespread throughout the [[brain]]; however, the pathways important to motor memory are separate from the medial [[temporal lobe]] pathways associated with [[declarative memory]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Brashers-Krug | first1 = T | last2 = Shadmehr | first2 = R. | last3 = Bizzi | first3 = E. | year = 1996 | title = Consolidation in human motor memory | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 382 | issue = 6588| pages = 252\u2013255| doi=10.1038/382252a0| pmid = 8717039 | bibcode = 1996Natur.382..252B| citeseerx = 10.1.1.39.3383 }}</ref>  As with declarative memory, motor memory is theorized to have two stages: a short-term [[memory encoding]] stage, which is fragile and susceptible to damage, and a long-term [[memory consolidation]] stage, which is more stable.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Atwell | first1 = P. | last2 = Cooke | first2 = S. | last3 = Yeo | first3 = C. | year = 2002 | title = Cerebellar function in consolidation of motor memory | url = | journal = Neuron | volume = 34 | issue = 6| pages = 1011\u20131020 | doi=10.1016/s0896-6273(02)00719-5}}</ref> \n  \nThe memory encoding stage is often referred to as [[motor learning]], and requires an increase in brain activity in motor areas as well as an increase in attention. Brain areas active during motor learning include the motor and somatosensory cortices; however, these areas of activation decrease once the motor skill is learned. The prefrontal and frontal cortices are also active during this stage due to the need for increased attention on the task being learned.<ref name = \"Shadmehr\" />\n\nThe main area involved in motor learning is the [[cerebellum]]. Some models of cerebellar-dependent motor learning, in particular the Marr-Albus model, propose a single plasticity mechanism involving the cerebellar [[long-term depression]] (LTD) of the parallel fiber synapses onto [[Purkinje cells]].  These modifications in synapse activity would mediate motor input with motor outputs critical to inducing motor learning.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Boyden | first1 = E. | last2 = Katoh | first2 = A. | last3 = Raymond | first3 = J. | year = 2004 | title = Cerebellum-dependent learning: the role of multiple plasticity mechanisms | url = | journal = Annu. Rev. Neurosci. | volume = 27 | issue = | pages = 581\u2013609 | doi=10.1146/annurev.neuro.27.070203.144238 | pmid=15217344}}</ref> However, conflicting evidence suggests that a single plasticity mechanism is not sufficient and a multiple plasticity mechanism is needed to account for the storage of motor memories over time. Regardless of the mechanism, studies of cerebellar-dependent  motor tasks show that cerebral cortical plasticity is crucial for motor learning, even if not necessarily for storage.<ref name = \"Ma\" />\n\nThe [[basal ganglia]] also play an important role in memory and learning, in particular in reference to stimulus-response associations and the formation of habits. The basal ganglia-cerebellar connections are thought to increase with time when learning a motor task.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Packard | first1 = M. | last2 = Knowlton | first2 = B. | year = 2002 | title = Learning and memory functions of the basal ganglia.  | url = | journal = Annu. Rev. Neurosci. | volume = 25 | issue = | pages = 563\u201393 | pmid = 12052921 | doi = 10.1146/annurev.neuro.25.112701.142937 }}</ref>\n\n===Muscle memory consolidation===\nMuscle memory consolidation involves the continuous evolution of neural processes after practicing a task has stopped. The exact mechanism of motor memory consolidation within the brain is controversial. However, most theories assume that there is a general redistribution of information across the brain from encoding to consolidation.  [[Hebb's rule]] states that \"synaptic connectivity changes as a function of repetitive firing.\" In this case, that would mean that the high amount of stimulation coming from practicing a movement would cause the repetition of firing in certain motor networks, presumably leading to an increase in the efficiency of exciting these motor networks over time.<ref name= \"Ma\">{{cite journal | last1 = Ma | first1 = L. | display-authors = etal   | year = 2010| title = ,. (2010). Changes in regional activity are accompanied with changes in inter-regional connectivity during 4 weeks motor learning | journal = Brain Res. | volume =  1318| issue = | pages =  64\u201376| doi = 10.1016/j.brainres.2009.12.073 | pmid=20051230 | pmc=2826520}}</ref>\n\nThough the exact location of muscle memory storage is not known, studies have suggested that it is the inter-regional connections that play the most important role in advancing motor memory encoding to consolidation, rather than decreases in overall regional activity.  These studies have shown a weakened connection from the cerebellum to the primary motor area with practice, it is presumed, because of a decreased need for error correction from the cerebellum. However, the connection between the basal ganglia and the primary motor area is strengthened, suggesting the basal ganglia play an important role in the motor memory consolidation process.<ref name = \"Ma\" />\n\n===Strength training and adaptations===\n{{See also|Muscle memory (strength training)}}\nWhen participating in any sport, new motor skills and movement combinations are frequently being used and repeated. All sports require some degree of strength, endurance training, and skilled reaching in order to be successful in the required tasks. Muscle memory related to [[Muscle memory (strength training)|strength training]]  involves elements of both motor learning, described below, and long-lasting changes in the muscle tissue.\n\nEvidence has shown that increases in strength occur well before muscle [[hypertrophy]], and decreases in strength due to detraining or ceasing to repeat the exercise over an extended period of time precede muscle [[atrophy]].<ref name = \"Adkins\">{{cite journal | last1 = Adkins | first1 = DeAnna L. | last2 = Boychuck | first2 = Jeffery | year = 2006 | title = Motor training induces experience specific patterns of plasticity across motor cortex and spinal cord | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/3d63cc947cfcc449d69c520ee3b6099c9d4bc243| journal = Journal of Applied Physiology | volume = 101 | issue = 6| pages = 1776\u20131782 | doi=10.1152/japplphysiol.00515.2006 | pmid=16959909}}</ref> To be specific, strength training enhances [[motor neuron]] excitability and induces [[synaptogenesis]], both of which would help in enhancing communication between the nervous system and the muscles themselves.<ref name = \"Adkins\" /> [[File:US Navy 071017-N-0995C-008 Chief Mineman Kevin Sperling, an officer recruiter at Navy Recruiting Processing Station Honolulu, presses two 105-pound dumbbells.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A navy man performs strength training exercises.]]However, neuromuscular efficacy is not altered within a two-week time period following cessation of the muscle usage; instead, it is merely the [[neuron]]'s ability to excite the muscle that declines in correlation with the muscle's decrease in strength.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Deschenes Michael | first1 = R. | last2 = Giles Jennifer | first2 = A. | year = 2002 | title = Neural factors account for strength decrements observed after short-term muscle unloading | url = | journal = American Journal of Physiology. Regulatory, Integrative and Comparative Physiology | volume = 282 | issue = 2| pages = R578\u2013R583 | doi=10.1152/ajpregu.00386.2001| pmid = 11792669 }}</ref> This confirms that muscle strength is first influenced by the inner neural circuitry, rather than by external physiological changes in the muscle size.\n\nPreviously untrained muscles acquire newly formed nuclei by fusion of satellite cells preceding the hypertrophy. Subsequent detraining leads to atrophy but no loss of myo-nuclei. The elevated number of nuclei in muscle fibers that had experienced a hypertrophic episode would provide a mechanism for muscle memory, explaining the long-lasting effects of training and the ease with which previously trained individuals are more easily retrained.<ref name = \"bru\">{{cite journal | last1 = Bruusgaard | first1 = J. C. | display-authors = etal   | year = 2010 | title = Myonuclei acquired by overload exercise precede hypertrophy and are not lost on detraining | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences | volume = 107 | issue = 34| pages = 15111\u201315116 | doi=10.1073/pnas.0913935107 | pmid=20713720 | pmc=2930527| bibcode = 2010PNAS..10715111B }}</ref>\n\nOn subsequent detraining, the fibers maintain an elevated number of nuclei that might provide resistance to atrophy; on retraining, a gain in size can be\nobtained by a moderate increase in the protein synthesis rate of each of these many nuclei, skipping the step of adding newly formed nuclei. This shortcut may contribute to the relative ease of retraining compared with the first training of individuals with no\nprevious training history.<ref name = \"bru\" />\n\nReorganization of motor maps within the cortex are not altered in either strength or endurance training. However, within the motor cortex, endurance induces [[angiogenesis]] within as little as three weeks to increase blood flow to the involved regions.<ref name = \"Adkins\" /> In addition, neurotropic factors within the motor cortex are [[upregulated]] in response to endurance training to promote neural survival.<ref name = \"Adkins\" />\n\nSkilled motor tasks have been divided into two distinct phases: a fast-learning phase, in which an optimal plan for performance is established, and a slow-learning phase, in which longer-term structural modifications are made on specific motor modules.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Karni | first1 = Avi | last2 = Meyer | first2 = Gundela | year = 1998 | title = The acquisition of skilled motor performance: Fast and slow experience-driven changes in primary motor cortex | url = | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences | volume = 95| issue = 3| pages = 861\u2013868 | doi=10.1073/pnas.95.3.861| pmid = 9448252 | pmc = 33809| bibcode = 1998PNAS...95..861K}}</ref> Even a small amount of training may be enough to induce neural processes that continue to evolve even after the training has stopped, which provides a potential basis for consolidation of the task. In addition, studying mice while they are learning a new complex reaching task, has found that \"motor learning leads to rapid formation of [[dendritic spines]] (spinogenesis) in the [[motor cortex]] contralateral to the reaching forelimb\".<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Xu | first1 = Tonghui | last2 = Perlik | first2 = Andrew J | year = 2009 | title = Rapid formation and selective stabilisation of synapses for enduring motor memories | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 462| issue = 7275| pages = 915\u201320 | doi=10.1038/nature08389 | pmid=19946267 | pmc=2844762| bibcode = 2009Natur.462..915X}}</ref>  However, motor cortex reorganization itself does not occur at a uniform rate across training periods. It has been suggested that the synaptogenesis and motor map reorganization merely represent the consolidation, and not the acquisition itself, of a specific motor task.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Kleim Jerrery | first1 = L. | last2 = Hogg Theresa | first2 = M. | year = 2004 | title = Cortical Synaptogenesis and Motor Map Reorganization Occur during Late, But not Early, Phase of Motor Skill Learning | url = | journal = The Journal of Neuroscience | volume = 24 | issue = 3| pages = 629\u2013633 | doi=10.1523/jneurosci.3440-03.2004 | pmid=14736848| pmc = 6729261 | citeseerx = 10.1.1.320.2189 }}</ref>  Furthermore, the degree of plasticity in various locations (namely motor cortex versus spinal cord) is dependent on the behavioural demands and nature of the task (i.e., skilled reaching versus strength training).<ref name = \"Adkins\" />\n\nWhether strength or endurance related, it is plausible that the majority of motor movements would require a skilled moving task of some form, whether it be maintaining proper form when paddling a canoe, or bench pressing a heavier weight. Endurance training assists the formation of these new neural representations within the motor cortex by up regulating neurotropic factors that could enhance the survival of the newer neural maps formed due to the skilled movement training.<ref name = \"Adkins\" /> Strength training results are seen in the spinal cord well before any physiological muscular adaptation is established through muscle hypertrophy or atrophy.<ref name = \"Adkins\" /> The results of endurance and strength training, and skilled reaching, therefore, combine to help each other maximize performance output.\n\nMore recently, research has suggested that epigenetics may play a distinct role in orchestrating a muscle memory phenomenon <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sharples|first1=Adam P.|last2=Stewart|first2=Claire E.|last3=Seaborne|first3=Robert A.|title=Does skeletal muscle have an 'epi'-memory? The role of epigenetics in nutritional programming, metabolic disease, aging and exercise|journal=Aging Cell|date=1 August 2016|volume=15|issue=4|pages=603\u2013616|doi=10.1111/acel.12486|pmid=27102569|pmc=4933662|language=en|issn=1474-9726}}</ref> Indeed, previously untrained human participants experienced a chronic period of resistance exercise training (7 weeks) that evoked significant increases in skeletal muscle mass of the vastus lateralis muscle, in the quadriceps muscle group. Following a similar period of physical in-activity (7 weeks), where strength and muscle mass returned to baseline, participants performed a secondary period of resistance exercise.<ref name = \"seaborne\">{{cite journal|last1=Seaborne|first1=Robert A.|last2=Strauss|first2=Juliette|last3=Cocks|first3=Matthew|last4=Shepherd|first4=Sam|last5=O\u2019Brien|first5=Thomas D.|last6=Someren|first6=Ken A. van|last7=Bell|first7=Phillip G.|last8=Murgatroyd|first8=Christopher|last9=Morton|first9=James P.|last10=Stewart|first10=Claire E.|last11=Sharples|first11=Adam P.|title=Human Skeletal Muscle Possesses an Epigenetic Memory of Hypertrophy|journal=Scientific Reports|date=30 January 2018|volume=8|issue=1|pages=1898|doi=10.1038/s41598-018-20287-3|pmid=29382913|pmc=5789890|language=En|issn=2045-2322|bibcode=2018NatSR...8.1898S}}</ref> Importantly, these participants adapted in an enhanced manner, whereby the amount of skeletal muscle mass gained was greater in the second period of muscle growth then the first, suggesting a muscle memory concept. The researchers went on to examine the human epigenome in order to understand how DNA methylation may aid in creating this effect. During the first period of resistance exercise, the authors identify significant adaptations in the human methylome, whereby over 9,000 CpG sites were reported as being significantly hypomethylated, with these adaptations being sustained during the subsequent period of physical in-activity. However, upon secondary exposure to resistance exercise, a greater frequency of hypomethylated CpG sites was observed, where over 18,000 sites reported as being significantly hypomethylated. The authors went on to identify how these changes altered the expression of relevant transcripts, and subsequently correlated these changes with adaptations in skeletal muscle mass. Collectively, the authors conclude that skeletal muscle mass and muscle memory phenomenon is, at least in part, modulated due to changes in DNA methylation.<ref name = \"seaborne\" /> Further work is now needed to confirm and explore these findings.\n\n==Fine motor memory==\n\n[[Fine motor skills]] are often discussed in terms of transitive movements, which are those done when using tools (which could be as simple as a tooth brush or pencil).<ref name = \"Dowell\">{{cite journal | last1 = Dowell | first1 = L. R. | last2 = Mahone | first2 = E. M. | last3 = Mostofsky | first3 = S. H. | year = 2009 | title = Associations of postural knowledge and basic motor skill with dyspraxia in autism: Implication for abnormalities in distributed connectivity and motor learning | url = | journal = Neuropsychology | volume = 23 | issue = 5| pages = 563\u2013570 | doi=10.1037/a0015640| pmid = 19702410 | pmc = 2740626 }}</ref> Transitive movements have representations that become programmed to the [[premotor cortex]], creating motor programs that result in the activation of the [[motor cortex]] and therefore the motor movements.<ref name = \"Dowell\" /> In a study testing the motor memory of patterned finger movements (a fine motor skill) it was found that retention of certain skills is susceptible to disruption if another task interferes with one's motor memory.<ref name = \"Krakauer\"/> However, such susceptibility can be reduced with time. For example, if a finger pattern is learned and another finger pattern is learned six hours later, the first pattern will still be remembered. But attempting to learn two such patterns one immediately after the other could cause the first one to be forgotten.<ref name = \"Krakauer\" /> Furthermore, the heavy use of computers by recent generations has had both positive and negative effects. One of the main positive effects is an enhancement of children's fine motor skills.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Straker | first1 = L. | last2 = Pollock | first2 = C. | last3 = Maslen | first3 = B. | year = 2009 | title = Principles for the wise use of computers by children | url = | journal = Ergonomics | volume = 52 | issue = 11| pages = 1386\u20131401 | doi=10.1080/00140130903067789| pmid = 19851906 | citeseerx = 10.1.1.468.7070 }}</ref> Repetitive behaviors, such as typing on a computer from a young age, can enhance such abilities. Therefore, children who learn to use computer keyboards at an early age could benefit from the early muscle memories.\n\n===Music memory===\n[[File:Playing the piano.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Bimanual synchronized finger movements play an essential role in piano playing.|Playing the piano requires complex actions]]  \nFine motor skills are very important in playing musical instruments. It was found that muscle memory is relied on when playing the clarinet, specifically to help create special effects through certain tongue movements when blowing air into the instrument.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Fritz | first1 = C. | last2 = Wolfe | first2 = J. | year = 2005 | title = How do clarinet players adjust the resonances of their vocal tracts for different playing effects? | url = | journal = Journal of the Acoustical Society of America | volume = 118 | issue = 5| pages = 3306\u20133315 | doi=10.1121/1.2041287| arxiv = physics/0505195 | bibcode = 2005ASAJ..118.3306F }}</ref>\n\nCertain human behaviours, especially actions like the finger movements in musical performances, are very complex and require many interconnected neural networks where information can be transmitted across multiple brain regions.<ref name = \"Kim\">{{cite journal | last1 = Kim | first1 = D. | last2 = Shin | first2 = M. | last3 = Lee | first3 = K. | last4 = Chu | first4 = K. | last5 = Woo | first5 = S. | last6 = Kim | first6 = Y. | last7 = Song | first7 = E. | last8 = Lee | first8 = Jun | last9 = Park | first9 = S. | last10 = Roh | first10 = J. | year = 2004 | title = Musical Training-Induced Functional Reorganization of the Adult Brain: Functional Magnetic Resonance Imaging and Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation Study on Amateur String Players | url = | journal = Human Brain Mapping | volume = 23 | issue = 4| pages = 188\u2013199 | doi=10.1002/hbm.20058| pmid = 15449354 }}</ref>  It has been found that there are often functional differences in the brains of professional musicians, when compared to other individuals. This is thought to reflect the musician's innate ability, which may be fostered by an early exposure to musical training.<ref name = \"Kim\" /> An example of this is bimanual synchronized finger movements, which play an essential role in piano playing. It is suggested that bimanual coordination can come only from years of bimanual training, where such actions become adaptations of the motor areas.<ref name = \"Haslinger\">{{cite journal | last1 = Haslinger | first1 = B. | last2 = Erhard | first2 = P. | last3 = Altenm\u00fcller | first3 = E. | last4 = Hennenlotter | first4 = A. | last5 = Schwaiger | first5 = M. | last6 = von Einsiedel | first6 = H. G. | last7 = Rummeny | first7 = E. | last8 = Conrad | first8 = B. | last9 = Ceballos-Baumann | first9 = A. O. | year = 2004 | title = Reduced Recruitment of Motor Association Areas During Bimanual Coordination in Concert Pianists | url = | journal = Human Brain Mapping | volume = 22 | issue = 3| pages = 206\u2013215 | doi=10.1002/hbm.20028| pmid = 15195287 }}</ref> When comparing professional musicians to a control group in complex bimanual movements, professionals are found to use an extensive motor network much less than those non-professionals.<ref name = \"Haslinger\" /> This is because professionals rely on a motor system that has increased efficiency, and, therefore, those less trained have a network that is more strongly activated.<ref name = \"Haslinger\" />  It is implied that the untrained pianists have to invest more neuronal activity to have the same level of performance that is achieved by professionals.<ref name = \"Haslinger\" /> This, yet again, is said to be a consequence of many years of motor training and experience that helps form a fine motor memory skill of musical performance.\n\nIt is often reported that, when a pianist hears a well-trained piece of music, synonymous fingering can be involuntarily triggered.<ref name = \"Kim\" /> This implies that there is a coupling between the perception of music and the motor activity of those musically trained individuals.<ref name = \"Kim\" /> Therefore, one's muscle memory in the context of music can easily be triggered when one hears certain familiar pieces. Overall, long-term musical fine motor training allows for complex actions to be performed at a lower level of movement control, monitoring, selection, attention, and timing.<ref name = \"Haslinger\" /> This leaves room for musicians to focus attention synchronously elsewhere, such as on the artistic aspect of the performance, without having to consciously control one's fine motor actions.<ref name = \"Haslinger\" />\n\n===Puzzle cube memory===\n{{refimprove section|date=March 2016}}\n[[File:Erik Akkersdijk is solving a 3\u00d73\u00d73 Rubik's Cube in 10.50s.ogv|thumb|[[Erik Akkersdijk]] is solving a 3\u00d73\u00d73 [[Rubik's Cube]] in 10.50s.]]\n[[Speed cubing|Speed cubers]] often will use muscle memory in order to learn large numbers of [[algorithm]]s quickly. It is quickly found that memorization purely of letters corresponding to moves on the cube is extremely difficult. The average beginner will try to do something like this; however, an advanced cuber can learn much more efficiently with muscle memory. A simple repetition of algorithms will create a long-term knowledge of it.  This plays a role in major speedcubing methods such as [[Fridrich Method|Fridrich]] for the 3\u00d73\u00d73 [[Rubik's Cube]] and EG for the 2\u00d72\u00d72 [[Pocket cube]].\n\n== Gross motor memory ==\n[[Gross motor skill]]s are concerned with the movement of large muscles, or major body movements, such as those involved in walking or kicking, and are associated with normal development.<ref name = \"Gross\">{{cite web |title=Gross motor Skills \u2013 What are Gross Motor Skills |url=http://learningdisabilities.about.com/od/gi/p/grossmotorskill.htm }}</ref> The extent to which one exhibits gross motor skills depends largely on their muscle tone and the strength.<ref name = \"Gross\" /> In a study looking at people with Down Syndrome, it was found that the pre-existing deficits, with regard to verbal-motor performance, limits the individual's transfer of gross motor skills following visual and verbal instruction to verbal instruction only.<ref name=\"Meegan\">{{cite journal |last=Meegan |first=S. |last2=Maraj |first2=B. K. V. |last3=Weeks |first3=D. |last4=Chua |first4=R. |year=2006 |title=Gross Motor Skill Acquisition in Adolescents With Down Syndrom |journal=Down Syndrome and Practice |volume=9 |issue=3 |pages=75\u201380 |doi= 10.3104/reports.298|pmid=16869378 |url=https://assets.cdn.down-syndrome.org/pubs/a/reports-298.pdf }}</ref> The fact that the individuals could still exhibit two of the three original motor skills may have been a result of positive transfer in which previous exposure allows the individual to remember the motion, under the visual and verbal trial, and then later perform it under the verbal trial.<ref name = \"Meegan\" />\n\n=== Learning in childhood ===\nThe way in which a child learns a gross motor skill can affect how long it takes to consolidate it and be able to reproduce the movement.  In a study with preschoolers, looking at the role of self-instruction on acquiring complex gross motor chains using [[ballet]] positions, it was found that the motor skills were better learned and remembered with the self-instruction procedure over the no-self-instruction procedure.<ref name=\"Vintere\">{{cite journal |last=Vintere |first=P. |last2=Hemmes |first2=N. S. |last3=Brown |first3=B. L. |last4=Poulson |first4=C. L. |year=2004 |title=Gross-Motor Skill Acquisition by Preschool Dance Stoudents Under Self-Instruction Procedures |journal=Journal of Applied Behavior Analysis |volume=37 |issue=3 |pages=305\u2013322 |doi= 10.1901/jaba.2004.37-305|pmc=1284506 |pmid=15529888}}</ref> This suggests that the use of self-instruction will increase the speed with which a preschooler will learn and remember a gross motor skill. It was also found that, once the preschoolers learned and mastered the motor chain movements, they ceased the use of self-instruction. This suggests that the memory for the movements became strong enough that there was no longer a need for self-instruction and the movements could be reproduced without it.<ref name=\"Vintere\" />\n\n=== Effect of Alzheimer's disease ===\nIt has been suggested that consistent practice of a gross motor skill can help a patient with [[Alzheimer's disease]] learn and remember that skill.  It was thought that the damage to the [[hippocampus]] may result in the need for a specific type of learning requirement.<ref name=\"Dick\">{{cite journal |last=Dick |first=M. B. |last2=Shankle |first2=R. W. |last3=Beth |first3=R. E. |last4=Dick-Muehlke |first4=C. |last5=Cotman |first5=C. W. |last6=Kean |first6=M. L. |year=1996 |title=Acquisition and long-term retention of a gross motor skill in Alzheimer's disease patients under constant and varied practice conditions |journal=The Journals of Gerontology Series B: Psychological Sciences and Social Sciences |volume=51B |issue=2 |pages=103\u2013111 |doi=10.1093/geronb/51B.2.P103 }}</ref> A study was created to test this assumption in which the patients were trained to throw a bean bag at a target.<ref name=\"Dick\" /> It was found that the Alzheimer's patients performed better on the task when learning occurred under constant training as opposed to variable.  Also, it was found that gross motor memory in Alzheimer's patients was the same as that of healthy adults when learning occurs under constant practice.<ref name=\"Dick\" /> This suggests that damage to the hippocampal system does not impair an Alzheimer's patient from retaining new gross motor skills, implying that motor memory for gross motor skills is stored elsewhere in the brain. However there isn't much evidence provided on this.\n\n== Impairment ==\nIt is difficult to display cases of \"pure\" motor memory impairment because the memory system is so widespread throughout the brain that damage is not often isolated to one specific type of memory.  Likewise,  diseases commonly associated with motor deficits, such as [[Huntington's]] and [[Parkinson's disease]], have a wide variety of symptoms and associated brain damage that make it impossible to pinpoint whether or not motor memory is in fact impaired.  Case studies have provided some examples of how motor memory has been implemented in patients with brain damage.\n\nAs Edward S. Casey notes in Remembering, Second Edition: A Phenomenological Study,  declarative memory, a process that involves an initial fragile learning period. \"The activity of the past, in short, resides in its habitual enactment in the present.\"\n\n=== Consolidation deficit ===\nA recent issue in motor memory is whether or not it consolidates in a manner similar to declarative memory, a process that involves an initial fragile learning period that eventually becomes stable and less susceptible to damage over time.<ref name = \"Krakauer\" /> An example of stable motor memory consolidation in a patient with brain damage is the case of [[Clive Wearing]]. Clive has severe anterograde and retrograde amnesia owing to damage in his temporal lobes, frontal lobes, and hippocampi, which prevents him from storing any new memories and making him aware of only the present moment. However, Clive still retains access to his procedural memories, to be specific, the motor memories involved in playing the piano. This could be because motor memory is demonstrated through savings over several trials of learning, whereas declarative memory is demonstrated through recall of a single item.<ref name = \"Krakauer\" />  This suggests that lesions in certain brain areas normally associated with declarative memory would not affect motor memory for a well-learned skill.\n\n=== Dysgraphia for the alphabet ===\nCase study: 54-year-old woman with known history of [[epilepsy]]\n\t\nThis patient was diagnosed with a pure form of [[dysgraphia]] of letters, meaning he had no other speech or reading impairments.<ref name=\"Kapur\">{{cite journal |last=Kapur |first=N. |last2=Lawton |first2=N. F. |year=1983 |title=Dysgraphia for Letters: a Form of Motor Memory Deficit? |journal=Journal of Neurological Psychiatry |volume=46 |issue=6 |pages=573\u2013575 |doi=10.1136/jnnp.46.6.573 |pmid=6875593 |pmc=1027454 }}</ref> His impairment was specific to letters in the alphabet. He was able to copy letters from the alphabet, but he was not able to write these letters.<ref name = \"Kapur\" /> He had previously been rated average on the [[Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale]]'s vocabulary subtest for writing ability comparative to his age before his diagnosis.<ref name=\"Kapur\" /> His writing impairment consisted of difficulty remembering motor movements associated with the letters he was supposed to write.<ref name=\"Kapur\" /> He was able to copy the letters, and also form images that were similar to the letters.<ref name=\"Kapur\" /> This suggests that dysgraphia for letters is a deficit related to motor memory.<ref name=\"Kapur\" /> Somehow there is a specific portion of the brain related to writing letters, which is dissociated from copying and drawing letter-like items.\n\n== See also ==\n*{{annotated link|Automaticity}}\n*{{annotated link|Procedural memory}}\n*{{annotated link|Motor learning}}\n*{{annotated link|Motor coordination}}\n*{{annotated link|Muscle}}\n*{{annotated link|Memory consolidation}}\n*{{annotated link|Overlearning}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{memory}}\n{{Muscular system}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Muscle Memory}}\n[[Category:Memory]]\n[[Category:Memory processes]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePuzzle cube memory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muscle_memory"}
{"title_page": "USS Eagle Boat 56", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|US Navy Eagle-class patrol boat}}\n{{For|ships with a similar name|USS Eagle}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Eagle boat.jpg\n|Ship caption=USS ''Eagle 2'', an identical sister ship of ''Eagle 56''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1945}}\n|Ship name=USS ''Eagle 56''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Ford Motor Company]]\n|Ship laid down=25 March 1919\n|Ship launched=15 August 1919\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=26 October 1919\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship fate=Torpedoed, 23 April 1945\n|Ship status=Found near Maine in June 2018\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass2-|Eagle|patrol craft}}\n|Ship displacement={{convert|615|LT|t|abbr=on}}\n|Ship length={{convert|200|ft|9|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|33|ft|1|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft={{convert|8|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=\n|Ship speed={{convert|18.32|kn|mph km/h|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement=Officers: 5, Enlisted: 56\n|Ship armament=*2 \u00d7 [[4\"/50 caliber gun]]s\n*1 \u00d7 [[3\"/50 caliber gun]]\n*2 \u00d7 [[M2 Browning machine gun|{{convert|.50|in|mm|abbr=on}}]] [[machine gun]]s\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''USS ''Eagle 56'' (PE-56)''' was a [[United States Navy]] [[World War I]]\u2013era [[patrol boat]] that remained in service through [[World War II]]. On 23 April 1945, while towing targets for U.S. Navy bomber exercises off the coast of [[Maine]], ''Eagle 56'' was sunk by the {{GS|U-853}}. Only 13 of the 62 crew survived. The loss was classified as a [[boiler]] explosion until 2001, because the navy brass didn't want to admit that they screwed up, so they decided to initiate the officer protection society (OPS).  They covered up the real cause even though every survivor testified under oath that they witnessed torpedoes and saw the U-Boat.  But the navy didn't want their college buddies to be embarrassed so they wrote up a bull shit story and blamed the crew.  This screwed the crew members of PE-56 because those guys were war heroes that deserved purple hearts.  Finally the navy was forced to change their bull shit story when they were presented with overwhelming evidence.  In 2018 historical evidence convinced the US Navy to reclassify the sinking as a combat loss due to enemy action; yet another government coverup discovered and righted by Americans who did the right thing.\n\n==Service history==\n''Eagle 56'' was one of 60 {{sclass2-|Eagle|patrol craft}} built by [[Henry Ford]] late in World War I as [[submarine chaser]]s, none of which saw action. Unpopular due to their poor sea handling, only eight remained in service at the time of [[World War II]].<ref name=\"green\">{{cite web|url=http://www.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=6892|title= Navy Senior Archivist Helps Solve 57 Year Old USS Eagle 56 Mystery|author=Jack A. Green|publisher=navy.mil| accessdate=2007-10-07|date=25 April 2003}}</ref> ''Eagle 56'' was patrolling off the [[Delaware Capes]] in January 1942.<ref name=\"proceedings\">Cianflone, Frank A. \"The Eagle Boats of World War I\" ''United States Naval Institute Proceedings'' June 1973 pp. 76\u201380</ref> ''Eagle 56'' remained almost constantly at sea during the [[Second Happy Time]]<ref name=\"proceedings\"/> of the [[Battle of the Atlantic]], during which Axis submarines attacked merchant shipping along the east coast of North America. When her [[depth charge]]s were expended, a small ship from [[Cape May, New Jersey]], would bring out a new supply.<ref name=\"proceedings\"/> ''Eagle 56'' rescued survivors of {{USS|Jacob Jones|DD-130|2}} off Cape May in February 1942.<ref name=\"proceedings\"/> It was damaged by collision with the submerged wreck of ''Gypsum Prince'' while rescuing survivors from the British freighter that had collided with the British tanker ''Voco'' on 4 March at the entrance to Delaware Bay,<ref name=\"proceedings\"/> and was repaired using parts from another ''Eagle'' boat, and then assigned to the [[Key West]] [[sonar]] school in May 1942.<ref name=\"proceedings\"/>\n\n===Sinking and investigation===\n''Eagle 56'' was assigned to [[Naval Air Station Brunswick]] from 28 June 1944.<ref name=\"proceedings\"/> At noon on 23 April 1945, ''Eagle 56'' exploded amidships, and broke into two pieces<ref name=\"green\"/> {{convert|3|mi|km|abbr=on}} off [[Cape Elizabeth, Maine]].<ref name=\"elizabeth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.capeelizabeth.com/news/eaglememorial.html |title=Dedication of Navy warship marker set for Saturday at Portland Head Light |date=22 April 2005 |accessdate=2007-10-07 |publisher=capeelizabeth.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061019105221/http://www.capeelizabeth.com/news/eaglememorial.html |archivedate=19 October 2006 }}</ref> The [[destroyer]] {{USS|Selfridge|DD-357|2}} was operating near ''Eagle 56'' and arrived 30 minutes after the explosion to rescue 13 survivors from the crew of 62.<ref name=\"proceedings\"/> ''Selfridge'' obtained a sharp, well-defined sonar contact during the rescue and dropped nine Mark IX Mod 2 [[depth charge]]s without obvious result.<ref name=\"proceedings\"/> According to a classified Navy report, {{GS|U-853||2}} had been operating in the waters off Maine.<ref name=\"green\"/> At a [[Naval Board of Inquiry]] in [[Portland, Maine|Portland]] the following week, five of the 13 survivors claimed to have seen a submarine. Several spotted a red and yellow emblem on the submarine's [[Sail (submarine)|sail]].<ref name=\"holland\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollandsentinel.com/stories/090901/fea_0909010041.shtml |title=56 years later, Navy rewrites record |publisher=hollandsentinel.com |accessdate=2007-10-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050302093022/http://www.hollandsentinel.com/stories/090901/fea_0909010041.shtml |archivedate=2 March 2005 }}</ref> These insignia match the markings of ''U-853'': a red horse on a yellow shield.<ref name=\"green\"/> ''Eagle 56''{{'}}s boiler was overhauled just two weeks before the sinking, and none of the boilers on the other 59 ''Eagle Boats'' had failed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tspweb02.tsp.utexas.edu/webarchive/08-30-01/2001083003_s03_New.html|title=Navy changes ship's records|date=30 August 2001|publisher=utexas.edu|accessdate=2007-10-07}}</ref> Nevertheless, the official Navy inquiry concluded that ''Eagle 56'' had suffered a boiler explosion.<ref name=\"green\" />\n\n==Later events==\nOn 5 May 1945, ''U-853'' sank the [[Collier (ship type)|collier]] ''Black Point'' off the coast of [[Point Judith, Rhode Island]], causing the loss of 12 lives. During the ensuing [[German submarine U-853#Battle of Point Judith|Battle of Point Judith]], ''U-853'' was chased and sunk by Navy and [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guard]] ships on 6 May.\n\nOn 1 June 1945, [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[Felix X. Gygax]] wrote, \"at least equal evidence to support the conclusion that the explosion was that of a device outside the ship, the exact nature of which is undetermined. It might have been an enemy [[naval mine|mine]] or an enemy [[torpedo]].\" Ultimately, though, he endorsed the court's findings.<ref name=\"holland\"/>\n\nBecause the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] had [[Ultra|cracked Germany's codes]], United States intelligence knew in 1945 that U-boats had been sent across the [[Atlantic Ocean|North Atlantic]] to disrupt shipping in hopes of obtaining better surrender terms. However, only general warnings rather than specific information about this plan were passed to commanders.<ref name=\"boston\"/>\n\n===Reclassification===\n[[file:Memorial USS Eagle-56.jpg|thumb|Plaque at Portland remembering the loss]]\nIn 2001, the [[Naval Historical Center]] reviewed the case and reclassified the sinking as a combat loss. In June 2001, [[Purple Heart]] medals were awarded to three survivors and the next of kin of those killed.<ref name=\"green\"/> As of 2007, this is the only time that the US Navy has overruled its own Court of Inquiry.<ref name=\"boston\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2006/04/06/the_truth_about_the_uss_eagle_56/|title=The truth about the USS Eagle 56|author=Robert Knox|date=6 April 2006|publisher=boston.com|accessdate=2007-10-07}}</ref>\n\nA commemorative plaque was erected on the grounds of [[Fort Williams Park]] near [[Portland Head Light]].\n\n===Wreck discovery===\nThe ship's wreckage was located in June 2018, and visited by a civilian dive team later the same month. It lies {{convert|5|mi|km|spell=in}} off the coast of Maine at a depth of {{convert|300|ft|m}}.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vigdor |first1=Neil |title=U.S. Navy Ship Sunk in World War II by German Sub Is Found Off Maine Coast |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/19/us/sunken-warship-discovered.html?action=click&module=Latest&pgtype=Homepage |accessdate=19 July 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=19 July 2019}}</ref> A video taken by the divers shows that USS ''Eagle 56''{{'}}s boilers are intact.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sharp |first1=David |title=Navy vessel sunk by German sub in WWII finally found |url=https://www.navytimes.com/news/your-navy/2019/07/18/navy-vessel-sunk-by-german-sub-in-wwii-finally-found/ |accessdate=19 July 2019 |work=Navy Times |date=19 July 2019}}</ref> The ship's steel plating is starting to rust away, but the site has been designated a [[war grave]], and it has all the protections associated with that designation.<ref>{{cite web|title=This Navy warship went down in World War II with 49 crew members aboard. Divers finally found it after 75 years|website=CNN|language=en|date=19 July 2019|author=Michelle Lou|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/this-navy-warship-went-down-in-world-war-ii-with-49-crew-members-aboard-divers-finally-found-it-after-75-years/ar-AAEx6Jr?ocid=spartanntp}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/patrol/eagles.htm DANFS entry: Eagle-class patrol craft (PE)]\n\n{{coord|43.5577|-70.1621|type:event_globe:earth_region:US-ME|display=title}}\n\n{{Eagle class patrol craft}}\n{{April 1945 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eagle (Pe-56)}}\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of the Maine coast]]\n[[Category:World War II patrol vessels of the United States]]\n[[Category:Patrol vessels of the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:1919 ships]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in April 1945]]\n[[Category:Ships sunk by German submarines in World War II]]\n[[Category:Ford vehicles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|US Navy Eagle-class patrol boat}}\n{{For|ships with a similar name|USS Eagle}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Eagle boat.jpg\n|Ship caption=USS ''Eagle 2'', an identical sister ship of ''Eagle 56''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1945}}\n|Ship name=USS ''Eagle 56''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Ford Motor Company]]\n|Ship laid down=25 March 1919\n|Ship launched=15 August 1919\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=26 October 1919\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship fate=Torpedoed, 23 April 1945\n|Ship status=Found near Maine in June 2018\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass2-|Eagle|patrol craft}}\n|Ship displacement={{convert|615|LT|t|abbr=on}}\n|Ship length={{convert|200|ft|9|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|33|ft|1|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft={{convert|8|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=\n|Ship speed={{convert|18.32|kn|mph km/h|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement=Officers: 5, Enlisted: 56\n|Ship armament=*2 \u00d7 [[4\"/50 caliber gun]]s\n*1 \u00d7 [[3\"/50 caliber gun]]\n*2 \u00d7 [[M2 Browning machine gun|{{convert|.50|in|mm|abbr=on}}]] [[machine gun]]s\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''USS ''Eagle 56'' (PE-56)''' was a [[United States Navy]] [[World War I]]\u2013era [[patrol boat]] that remained in service through [[World War II]]. On 23 April 1945, while towing targets for U.S. Navy bomber exercises off the coast of [[Maine]], ''Eagle 56'' was sunk by the {{GS|U-853}}. Only 13 of the 62 crew survived. The loss was classified as a [[boiler]] explosion until 2001, when historical evidence convinced the US Navy to reclassify the sinking as a combat loss due to enemy action.\n\n==Service history==\n''Eagle 56'' was one of 60 {{sclass2-|Eagle|patrol craft}} built by [[Henry Ford]] late in World War I as [[submarine chaser]]s, none of which saw action. Unpopular due to their poor sea handling, only eight remained in service at the time of [[World War II]].<ref name=\"green\">{{cite web|url=http://www.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=6892|title= Navy Senior Archivist Helps Solve 57 Year Old USS Eagle 56 Mystery|author=Jack A. Green|publisher=navy.mil| accessdate=2007-10-07|date=25 April 2003}}</ref> ''Eagle 56'' was patrolling off the [[Delaware Capes]] in January 1942.<ref name=\"proceedings\">Cianflone, Frank A. \"The Eagle Boats of World War I\" ''United States Naval Institute Proceedings'' June 1973 pp. 76\u201380</ref> ''Eagle 56'' remained almost constantly at sea during the [[Second Happy Time]]<ref name=\"proceedings\"/> of the [[Battle of the Atlantic]], during which Axis submarines attacked merchant shipping along the east coast of North America. When her [[depth charge]]s were expended, a small ship from [[Cape May, New Jersey]], would bring out a new supply.<ref name=\"proceedings\"/> ''Eagle 56'' rescued survivors of {{USS|Jacob Jones|DD-130|2}} off Cape May in February 1942.<ref name=\"proceedings\"/> It was damaged by collision with the submerged wreck of ''Gypsum Prince'' while rescuing survivors from the British freighter that had collided with the British tanker ''Voco'' on 4 March at the entrance to Delaware Bay,<ref name=\"proceedings\"/> and was repaired using parts from another ''Eagle'' boat, and then assigned to the [[Key West]] [[sonar]] school in May 1942.<ref name=\"proceedings\"/>\n\n===Sinking and investigation===\n''Eagle 56'' was assigned to [[Naval Air Station Brunswick]] from 28 June 1944.<ref name=\"proceedings\"/> At noon on 23 April 1945, ''Eagle 56'' exploded amidships, and broke into two pieces<ref name=\"green\"/> {{convert|3|mi|km|abbr=on}} off [[Cape Elizabeth, Maine]].<ref name=\"elizabeth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.capeelizabeth.com/news/eaglememorial.html |title=Dedication of Navy warship marker set for Saturday at Portland Head Light |date=22 April 2005 |accessdate=2007-10-07 |publisher=capeelizabeth.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061019105221/http://www.capeelizabeth.com/news/eaglememorial.html |archivedate=19 October 2006 }}</ref> The [[destroyer]] {{USS|Selfridge|DD-357|2}} was operating near ''Eagle 56'' and arrived 30 minutes after the explosion to rescue 13 survivors from the crew of 62.<ref name=\"proceedings\"/> ''Selfridge'' obtained a sharp, well-defined sonar contact during the rescue and dropped nine Mark IX Mod 2 [[depth charge]]s without obvious result.<ref name=\"proceedings\"/> According to a classified Navy report, {{GS|U-853||2}} had been operating in the waters off Maine.<ref name=\"green\"/> At a [[Naval Board of Inquiry]] in [[Portland, Maine|Portland]] the following week, five of the 13 survivors claimed to have seen a submarine. Several spotted a red and yellow emblem on the submarine's [[Sail (submarine)|sail]].<ref name=\"holland\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollandsentinel.com/stories/090901/fea_0909010041.shtml |title=56 years later, Navy rewrites record |publisher=hollandsentinel.com |accessdate=2007-10-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050302093022/http://www.hollandsentinel.com/stories/090901/fea_0909010041.shtml |archivedate=2 March 2005 }}</ref> These insignia match the markings of ''U-853'': a red horse on a yellow shield.<ref name=\"green\"/> ''Eagle 56''{{'}}s boiler was overhauled just two weeks before the sinking, and none of the boilers on the other 59 ''Eagle Boats'' had failed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tspweb02.tsp.utexas.edu/webarchive/08-30-01/2001083003_s03_New.html|title=Navy changes ship's records|date=30 August 2001|publisher=utexas.edu|accessdate=2007-10-07}}</ref> Nevertheless, the official Navy inquiry concluded that ''Eagle 56'' had suffered a boiler explosion.<ref name=\"green\" />\n\n==Later events==\nOn 5 May 1945, ''U-853'' sank the [[Collier (ship type)|collier]] ''Black Point'' off the coast of [[Point Judith, Rhode Island]], causing the loss of 12 lives. During the ensuing [[German submarine U-853#Battle of Point Judith|Battle of Point Judith]], ''U-853'' was chased and sunk by Navy and [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guard]] ships on 6 May.\n\nOn 1 June 1945, [[Rear admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[Felix X. Gygax]] wrote, \"at least equal evidence to support the conclusion that the explosion was that of a device outside the ship, the exact nature of which is undetermined. It might have been an enemy [[naval mine|mine]] or an enemy [[torpedo]].\" Ultimately, though, he endorsed the court's findings.<ref name=\"holland\"/>\n\nBecause the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] had [[Ultra|cracked Germany's codes]], United States intelligence knew in 1945 that U-boats had been sent across the [[Atlantic Ocean|North Atlantic]] to disrupt shipping in hopes of obtaining better surrender terms. However, only general warnings rather than specific information about this plan were passed to commanders.<ref name=\"boston\"/>\n\n===Reclassification===\n[[file:Memorial USS Eagle-56.jpg|thumb|Plaque at Portland remembering the loss]]\nIn 2001, the [[Naval Historical Center]] reviewed the case and reclassified the sinking as a combat loss. In June 2001, [[Purple Heart]] medals were awarded to three survivors and the next of kin of those killed.<ref name=\"green\"/> As of 2007, this is the only time that the US Navy has overruled its own Court of Inquiry.<ref name=\"boston\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2006/04/06/the_truth_about_the_uss_eagle_56/|title=The truth about the USS Eagle 56|author=Robert Knox|date=6 April 2006|publisher=boston.com|accessdate=2007-10-07}}</ref>\n\nA commemorative plaque was erected on the grounds of [[Fort Williams Park]] near [[Portland Head Light]].\n\n===Wreck discovery===\nThe ship's wreckage was located in June 2018, and visited by a civilian dive team later the same month. It lies {{convert|5|mi|km|spell=in}} off the coast of Maine at a depth of {{convert|300|ft|m}}.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vigdor |first1=Neil |title=U.S. Navy Ship Sunk in World War II by German Sub Is Found Off Maine Coast |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/19/us/sunken-warship-discovered.html?action=click&module=Latest&pgtype=Homepage |accessdate=19 July 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=19 July 2019}}</ref> A video taken by the divers shows that USS ''Eagle 56''{{'}}s boilers are intact.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sharp |first1=David |title=Navy vessel sunk by German sub in WWII finally found |url=https://www.navytimes.com/news/your-navy/2019/07/18/navy-vessel-sunk-by-german-sub-in-wwii-finally-found/ |accessdate=19 July 2019 |work=Navy Times |date=19 July 2019}}</ref> The ship's steel plating is starting to rust away, but the site has been designated a [[war grave]], and it has all the protections associated with that designation.<ref>{{cite web|title=This Navy warship went down in World War II with 49 crew members aboard. Divers finally found it after 75 years|website=CNN|language=en|date=19 July 2019|author=Michelle Lou|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/this-navy-warship-went-down-in-world-war-ii-with-49-crew-members-aboard-divers-finally-found-it-after-75-years/ar-AAEx6Jr?ocid=spartanntp}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/patrol/eagles.htm DANFS entry: Eagle-class patrol craft (PE)]\n\n{{coord|43.5577|-70.1621|type:event_globe:earth_region:US-ME|display=title}}\n\n{{Eagle class patrol craft}}\n{{April 1945 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eagle (Pe-56)}}\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of the Maine coast]]\n[[Category:World War II patrol vessels of the United States]]\n[[Category:Patrol vessels of the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:1919 ships]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in April 1945]]\n[[Category:Ships sunk by German submarines in World War II]]\n[[Category:Ford vehicles]]\n", "name_user": "97.112.254.97", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/USS_Eagle_Boat_56"}
{"title_page": "Nxchange", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox exchange\n|name      = Nxchange\n|alt_name  = \n|logo      = Nxchange logo.svg\n|image     = Amsterdam - Herengracht 454.JPG\n|type      = [[Stock exchange]]\n|city      = [[Amsterdam]]\n|country   = [[Netherlands]]\n|coor      = {{coord|52|21|56.6|N|4|53|22.1|E|type:landmark}}\n|foundation= {{date and age|February 20, 2015}}\n|closed    =\n|owner     = Nxchange [[Besloten vennootschap|B.V.]]<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.afm.nl/en/professionals/registers/vergunningenregisters/beleggingsondernemingen/details?id=17DF40E4-A686-E411-BA3E-005056BE011C |title = Nxchange B.V. |access-date = April 1, 2020 |website = [[Netherlands Authority for the Financial Markets]] }}</ref>\n|key_people= Marleen Evertsz <small>[[Chief Executive Officer|(CEO)]]</small>\n|currency  = [[Euro]] (EUR)\n|commodity = \n|listings  = 7<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.nxchange.com/invest/debt |title = Secondary market debt |access-date = April 1, 2020 |website = Nxchange }}</ref>\n|mcap      = \n|volume    = \n|indexes   = \n|homepage  = {{URL|www.nxchange.com}}\n|footnotes = \n}}\n'''Nxchange''' (stylized as '''nx\u2019change''') is Dutch [[stock exchange]], that is headquartered along the [[Herengracht]] in [[Amsterdam]]. Founded in 2015, it is one of three stock exchanges operating in the Netherlands.<ref name=\"fd1\">{{Cite news |url = https://fd.nl/beurs/1147370/nieuwe-beurs-nxchange-zet-tussenpersoon-buitenspel |title = Nieuwe beurs Nxchange zet tussenpersoon buitenspel |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |website = [[Het Financieele Dagblad]] |date = April 14, 2016 |last1 = Kuppeveld |first1 = Joost van |last2 = Dobber |first2 = Joost }}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]] Marleen Evertsz, Nxchange is aimed at companies with a large following that wish to raise funds.<ref name=\"fd1\"/> They can list [[stock]]s, [[stock certificate]]s, [[bond (finance)|bonds]], and [[investment fund|funds]] on the exchange without a minimum issue amount.<ref name=\"fd1\"/><ref name=\"faq\"/> Investors are able to buy and sell stocks [[24/7]] without a [[broker]] and can upload reports with [[financial analyses]] on the Nxchange platform.<ref name=\"fd1\"/><ref name=\"faq\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.nxchange.com/learn/investors/faq |title = Investors FAQ |website = Nxchange |access-date = April 1, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nTransactions are [[settlement (finance)|settled]] through [[delivery versus payment]]. Clearing and settling is done by Nxchange itself, and the [[securities]] are held at the giro depot of [[Euroclear]] Netherlands.<ref name=\"faq\"/>\n\n== History ==\nNxchange [[besloten vennootschap|B.V.]] was founded by Marleen Evertsz in February 2015, and the stock exchange opened for trading on April 14, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.rtlnieuws.nl/geld-en-werk/artikel/568281/nxchange-slaagt-deze-nieuwe-beurs-wel |website = [[RTL Nieuws]] |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |date = April 14, 2016 |title = Nx'change, slaagt deze nieuwe beurs wel? |last = Clercq |first = Paul le }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url = https://drimble.nl/bedrijf/sc/amsterdam/31696775/nxchange-bv.html |title = Nxchange BV |website = Drimble |access-date = April 3, 2020 |language = Dutch }}</ref> [[Charging infrastructure]] provider [[Fastned]] was the first company listed and managed to raise \u20ac3 million during the first month by issuing stock certificates.<ref>{{Cite news |url = https://fd.nl/beurs/1152749/fastned-haalt-3-mln-op-met-emissie-op-alternatieve-beurs |title = Fastned haalt \u20ac 3 mln op met emissie alternatieve beurs |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |date = May 23, 2016 |last = Grol |first = Carel |website = Het Financieele Dagblad }}</ref> The stock exchange did not succeed in attracting more companies in its first year.<ref>{{Cite news |url = https://fd.nl/beurs/1212747/plank-beurs-veel-ambitie-weinig-verstoring-op-de-beurs |title = Veel ambitie, weinig verstoring op de beurs |last = Rein |first = Erik van |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |date = August 27, 2017 |website = Het Financieele Dagblad }}</ref> Nxchange received a [[Golden Bull (broker award)|Golden Bull]] in 2016 in the category \"best investment innovation\".<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://img.iex.nl/goudenstier/GoudenStier_Juryrapport2016_DEF.pdf |date = September 21, 2016 |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |title = Juryrapport |page = 5 }}</ref>\n\nThe company was granted a license to operate as a [[multilateral trading facility]] in August 2018 by the [[Netherlands Authority for the Financial Markets|Authority for the Financial Markets]]. It was previously classified solely as a regulated market.<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.afm.nl/en/professionals/registers/vergunningenregisters/handelsplatformen |title = Register trading platforms |access-date = April 1, 2020 |website = Netherlands Authority for the Financial Markets }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url = https://fd.nl/beurs/1267645/afm-verleent-vergunning-aan-nieuwe-mkb-beurs |last = Betlem |first = Rutger |title = AFM verleent vergunning aan nieuwe mkb-beurs |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |date = August 31, 2018 |website = Het Financieele Dagblad }}</ref> In December, Nxchange and [[Rabobank]] announced a cooperation called \"Rabo&Crowd\", allowing companies to raise money partly by [[loan|borrowing]] from the bank and partly by issuing bonds on Nxchange.<ref>{{Cite news |url = https://fd.nl/beurs/1280360/rabobank-en-nxchange-stappen-samen-in-mkb-financiering |last = Rein |first = Erik van |title = Rabobank en Nxchange stappen samen in mkb-financiering |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |date = December 3, 2018 |website = Het Financieele Dagblad }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url = https://www.rtlz.nl/beurs/artikel/4756966/toekomst-nxchange-fastned-beursgang-marleenevertsz |title = Wat is de toekomst van Nxchange, beurs met slechts 4 noteringen? |last = Clercq |first = Paul le |website = RTL Z |date = July 10, 2019 |language = Dutch |access-date = April 1, 2020 }}</ref> Several smaller companies have issued bonds using Rabo&Crowd in the subsequent years.<ref>{{Cite news |url = https://fd.nl/beurs/1302277/fastned-aandelen-blijven-ook-op-alternatieve-beurs |title = Fastned-aandelen blijven ook op alternatieve beurs Nxchange |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |date = May 22, 2019 |website = Het Financieele Dagblad }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Fastned started a listing on the larger stock exchange [[Euronext]], but its certificates remained tradable on Nxchange. However, it was possible to convert the stock certificates.<ref>{{Cite news |url = https://fd.nl/beurs/1305970/fastned-kost-op-de-ene-beurs-41-en-op-de-andere-19 |last = Dobber |first = Joost |title = Fastned kost op de ene beurs \u20ac41, en op de andere \u20ac19 |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |date = June 24, 2019 |website = Het Financieele Dagblad }}</ref> Later that year, a number of [[startups]] selected by [[Startupbootcamp]] jointly issued share certificates on Nxchange under the name \"SBC [[Fintech]] Amsterdam 1921\".<ref>{{Cite news |url = https://fd.nl/ondernemen/1320961/mandje-van-start-ups-samen-naar-de-beurs |last = Hueck |first = Hella |title = Mandje van start-ups naar de beurs |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |date = October 21, 2019 |website = Het Financieele Dagblad }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of European stock exchanges]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.nxchange.com Official website]\n\n[[Category:2015 establishments in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 2015]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies of the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Stock exchanges in the Netherlands]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox exchange\n|name      = Nxchange\n|alt_name  = \n|logo      = Nxchange logo.svg\n|image     = Amsterdam - Herengracht 454.JPG\n|type      = [[Stock exchange]]\n|city      = [[Amsterdam]]\n|country   = [[Netherlands]]\n|coor      = {{coord|52|21|56.6|N|4|53|22.1|E|type:landmark}}\n|foundation= {{date and age|February 20, 2015}}\n|closed    =\n|owner     = Nxchange [[Besloten vennootschap|B.V.]]<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.afm.nl/en/professionals/registers/vergunningenregisters/beleggingsondernemingen/details?id=17DF40E4-A686-E411-BA3E-005056BE011C |title = Nxchange B.V. |access-date = April 1, 2020 |website = [[Netherlands Authority for the Financial Markets]] }}</ref>\n|key_people= Marleen Evertsz <small>[[Chief Executive Officer|(CEO)]]</small>\n|currency  = [[Euro]] (EUR)\n|commodity = \n|listings  = 7<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.nxchange.com/invest/debt |title = Secondary market debt |access-date = April 1, 2020 |website = Nxchange }}</ref>\n|mcap      = \n|volume    = \n|indexes   = \n|homepage  = {{URL|www.nxchange.com}}\n|footnotes = \n}}\n'''Nxchange''' (stylized as '''nx\u2019change''') is Dutch [[stock exchange]], that is headquartered along the [[Herengracht]] in [[Amsterdam]]. Founded in 2015, it is one of three stock exchanges operating in the Netherlands.<ref name=\"fd1\">{{Cite news |url = https://fd.nl/beurs/1147370/nieuwe-beurs-nxchange-zet-tussenpersoon-buitenspel |title = Nieuwe beurs Nxchange zet tussenpersoon buitenspel |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |website = [[Het Financieele Dagblad]] |date = April 14, 2016 |last1 = Kuppeveld |first1 = Joost van |last2 = Dobber |first2 = Joost }}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]] Marleen Evertsz, Nxchange is aimed at companies with a large following that wish to raise funds.<ref name=\"fd1\"/> They can list [[stock]]s, [[stock certificate]]s, [[bond (finance)|bonds]], and [[investment fund|funds]] on the exchange without a minimum issue amount.<ref name=\"fd1\"/><ref name=\"faq\"/> Investors are able to buy and sell stocks [[24/7]] without a [[broker]] and can upload reports with [[financial analyses]] on the Nxchange platform.<ref name=\"fd1\"/><ref name=\"faq\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.nxchange.com/learn/investors/faq |title = Investors FAQ |website = Nxchange |access-date = April 1, 2020 }}</ref>\n\nTransaction are [[settlement (finance)|settled]] through [[delivery versus payment]]. Clearing and settling is done by Nxchange itself, and the [[securities]] are held at the giro depot of [[Euroclear]] Netherlands.<ref name=\"faq\"/>\n\n== History ==\nNxchange [[besloten vennootschap|B.V.]] was founded by Marleen Evertsz in February 2015, and the stock exchange opened for trading on April 14, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.rtlnieuws.nl/geld-en-werk/artikel/568281/nxchange-slaagt-deze-nieuwe-beurs-wel |website = [[RTL Nieuws]] |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |date = April 14, 2016 |title = Nx'change, slaagt deze nieuwe beurs wel? |last = Clercq |first = Paul le }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url = https://drimble.nl/bedrijf/sc/amsterdam/31696775/nxchange-bv.html |title = Nxchange BV |website = Drimble |access-date = April 3, 2020 |language = Dutch }}</ref> [[Charging infrastructure]] provider [[Fastned]] was the first company listed and managed to raise \u20ac3 million during the first month by issuing stock certificates.<ref>{{Cite news |url = https://fd.nl/beurs/1152749/fastned-haalt-3-mln-op-met-emissie-op-alternatieve-beurs |title = Fastned haalt \u20ac 3 mln op met emissie alternatieve beurs |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |date = May 23, 2016 |last = Grol |first = Carel |website = Het Financieele Dagblad }}</ref> The stock exchange did not succeed in attracting more companies in its first year.<ref>{{Cite news |url = https://fd.nl/beurs/1212747/plank-beurs-veel-ambitie-weinig-verstoring-op-de-beurs |title = Veel ambitie, weinig verstoring op de beurs |last = Rein |first = Erik van |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |date = August 27, 2017 |website = Het Financieele Dagblad }}</ref> Nxchange received a [[Golden Bull (broker award)|Golden Bull]] in 2016 in the category \"best investment innovation\".<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://img.iex.nl/goudenstier/GoudenStier_Juryrapport2016_DEF.pdf |date = September 21, 2016 |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |title = Juryrapport |page = 5 }}</ref>\n\nThe company was granted a license to operate as a [[multilateral trading facility]] in August 2018 by the [[Netherlands Authority for the Financial Markets|Authority for the Financial Markets]]. It was previously classified solely as a regulated market.<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.afm.nl/en/professionals/registers/vergunningenregisters/handelsplatformen |title = Register trading platforms |access-date = April 1, 2020 |website = Netherlands Authority for the Financial Markets }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url = https://fd.nl/beurs/1267645/afm-verleent-vergunning-aan-nieuwe-mkb-beurs |last = Betlem |first = Rutger |title = AFM verleent vergunning aan nieuwe mkb-beurs |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |date = August 31, 2018 |website = Het Financieele Dagblad }}</ref> In December, Nxchange and [[Rabobank]] announced a cooperation called \"Rabo&Crowd\", allowing companies to raise money partly by [[loan|borrowing]] from the bank and partly by issuing bonds on Nxchange.<ref>{{Cite news |url = https://fd.nl/beurs/1280360/rabobank-en-nxchange-stappen-samen-in-mkb-financiering |last = Rein |first = Erik van |title = Rabobank en Nxchange stappen samen in mkb-financiering |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |date = December 3, 2018 |website = Het Financieele Dagblad }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url = https://www.rtlz.nl/beurs/artikel/4756966/toekomst-nxchange-fastned-beursgang-marleenevertsz |title = Wat is de toekomst van Nxchange, beurs met slechts 4 noteringen? |last = Clercq |first = Paul le |website = RTL Z |date = July 10, 2019 |language = Dutch |access-date = April 1, 2020 }}</ref> Several smaller companies have issued bonds using Rabo&Crowd in the subsequent years.<ref>{{Cite news |url = https://fd.nl/beurs/1302277/fastned-aandelen-blijven-ook-op-alternatieve-beurs |title = Fastned-aandelen blijven ook op alternatieve beurs Nxchange |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |date = May 22, 2019 |website = Het Financieele Dagblad }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Fastned started a listing on the larger stock exchange [[Euronext]], but its certificates remained tradable on Nxchange. However, it was possible to convert the stock certificates.<ref>{{Cite news |url = https://fd.nl/beurs/1305970/fastned-kost-op-de-ene-beurs-41-en-op-de-andere-19 |last = Dobber |first = Joost |title = Fastned kost op de ene beurs \u20ac41, en op de andere \u20ac19 |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |date = June 24, 2019 |website = Het Financieele Dagblad }}</ref> Later that year, a number of [[startups]] selected by [[Startupbootcamp]] jointly issued share certificates on Nxchange under the name \"SBC [[Fintech]] Amsterdam 1921\".<ref>{{Cite news |url = https://fd.nl/ondernemen/1320961/mandje-van-start-ups-samen-naar-de-beurs |last = Hueck |first = Hella |title = Mandje van start-ups naar de beurs |access-date = April 1, 2020 |language = Dutch |date = October 21, 2019 |website = Het Financieele Dagblad }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of European stock exchanges]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.nxchange.com Official website]\n\n[[Category:2015 establishments in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 2015]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies of the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Stock exchanges in the Netherlands]]\n", "name_user": "Tristan Surtel", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nxchange"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Robertson", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Andrew Robertson\n| image = LFC Parade 2019 01 Andy Robertson.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Robertson with the victory parade after [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] won the [[2019 UEFA Champions League Final]]\n| fullname = Andrew Henry Robertson<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tournament.fifadata.com/documents/FCWC/2019/pdf/FCWC_2019_SQUADLISTS.PDF |title=FIFA Club World Cup Qatar 2019: List of Players: Liverpool |publisher=FIFA |page=7 |date=21 December 2019 |accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1994|3|11|df=y}}<ref name=PremProfile>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/10458/Andrew-Robertson/overview |title=Andrew Robertson: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=13 October 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| height = {{convert|1.78|m|order=flip}}<ref name=PremProfile/>\n| position = [[Left back]]\n| currentclub = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| clubnumber = 26\n| youthyears1 = {{0|0000}}\u20132009\n| youthclubs1 = [[Celtic F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Celtic]]\n| youthyears2 = 2009\u20132012\n| youthclubs2 = [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]]\n| years1 = 2012\u20132013\n| clubs1 = [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]]\n| caps1 = 34\n| goals1 = 2\n| years2 = 2013\u20132014\n| clubs2 = [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]\n| caps2 = 36\n| goals2 = 3\n| years3 = 2014\u20132017\n| clubs3 = [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]]\n| caps3 = 99\n| goals3 = 3\n| years4 = 2017\u2013\n| clubs4 = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| caps4 = 86\n| goals4 = 2\n<!--Use domestic league appearances only-->| nationalyears1 = 2013\u20132015\n| nationalcaps1 = 4\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland U21]]\n| nationalyears2 = 2014\u2013\n| nationalcaps2 = 34\n| nationalgoals2 = 3\n| nationalteam2 = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| club-update = 19:25, 29 February 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 07:47, 14 October 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Andrew Henry Robertson''' (born 11 March 1994) is a Scottish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[left back]] for [[Premier League|Irish]] Club Portrane Athletic, and captains the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team.]]\n\nRobertson began his senior career with [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]] in 2012 before joining [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] a year later. His form in his first season as a professional led to him being named [[SPFA Young Player of the Year]] and also making his international debut. He joined [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] in July 2014 for a fee of \u00a32.85&nbsp;million, before joining Liverpool in July 2017 for an undisclosed fee, believed to be an initial \u00a38&nbsp;million. He appeared in successive [[List of European Cup and UEFA Champions League finals|UEFA Champions League finals]] in his first two seasons, winning the second in [[2019 UEFA Champions League Final|2019]]. For his performances in the [[2018\u201319 Premier League]] season, he was named in the [[PFA Team of the Year (2010s)#Premier League 10|PFA Team of the Year]].\n\nRobertson made his full international debut for [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] in May 2014, and he was appointed [[list of Scotland national football team captains|Scotland captain]] in September 2018.\n\n==Early life and career==\nRobertson was born in [[Glasgow]] and was a childhood [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] fan.<ref name=places/> His father Brian, nicknamed 'Pop', who grew up in the [[Maryhill]] area (specifically the [[Wyndford]] estate where he was a childhood friend of footballers [[Jim Duffy (footballer)|Jim Duffy]] and [[Charlie Nicholas]]),<ref name=places>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48413180|title=Liverpool's Andy Robertson: The people & places behind Scotland defender's rise|last=Greig|first=Martin|date=30 May 2019|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=30 May 2019}}</ref> was a keen amateur player, although a spinal injury requiring him to wear a back brace prevented him from pursuing sport as a career.<ref name=places/> \n\nHe attended [[St Ninian's High School, Giffnock|St Ninian's High School]] in [[Giffnock]], [[East Renfrewshire]], from 2006 to 2012, where he captained the football team. He also played for Giffnock Soccer Centre and joined Celtic as a youth, but was released at under-15 level because he was considered to be too small.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/dundee-united-starlet-andy-roberston-2900858|title=Dundee United starlet Andy Roberston: Celtic made a small blunder the day they let me go|work=Daily Record|date=7 December 2013|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref> He then signed for [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]].<ref name=places/>\n\n==Club career==\n===Queen's Park===\nFocusing on his studies, Robertson was on the brink of starting university at undergraduate degree level before he was called up to the Queen's Park first team at the beginning of the [[2012\u201313 in Scottish football|2012\u201313 season]]. He made his debut for the club in the [[Scottish Challenge Cup]] in a penalty shoot out win against [[Berwick Rangers]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19027896 |title=Ramsdens Cup: Berwick Rangers 2\u20132 Queen's Park (aet, 2\u20133 pens) |website=BBC Sport |date=28 July 2012 |accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref> and went on to make a total of forty appearances during the season,<ref name=\"Andrew Robertson\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dundeeunitedfc.co.uk/index.asp?tm=124&ID=415|title=Andrew Robertson|accessdate=5 August 2013|date=5 August 2013}}{{dead link|date=June 2015}}{{cbignore}}</ref> helping the club to a third-place finish in the [[2012-13 Scottish Third Division|Scottish Third Division]]. His first goal for the club came in a 2\u20131 defeat to [[East Stirlingshire F.C.|East Stirlingshire]] on 13 November 2012.<ref name=\"Andrew Robertson\"/>\n\n===Dundee United===\nRobertson signed for [[Scottish Premiership]] side [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]], along with Queen's Park teammate [[Aidan Connolly]], on 3 June 2013;<ref name=\"Dundee United sign Robertson and Connolly\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22762888|title=Dundee Utd sign Queen's Park's Robertson and Connolly|accessdate=5 August 2013|date=3 June 2013|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> he took the squad place of the departing [[Barry Douglas]] who had made the same move three years earlier.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.dundeeunitedfc.co.uk/news/2895/BARRY-DOUGLAS-JOINS-UNITED.html|author=|title= Barry Douglas joins United|work=|date=21 June 2010|publisher= [[Dundee United F.C.]] |accessdate=9 January 2019 }}</ref> Having been ignored in their requests for a transfer fee for Douglas, Queen's Park (an amateur club) protested at the prospect of more players departing to United for nothing and eventually agreed a deal involving a percentage of future transfers, which would later prove beneficial.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/13172018.300k-robertson-boost-a-cut-above-for-queens-park/|author=|title= \u00a3300k Robertson boost a cut above for Queen's Park|work=The Herald |date=27 July 2014|publisher= |accessdate=9 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\nRobertson immediately became part of manager [[Jackie McNamara]]'s first team plans, making his debut for the club on the opening day of the season in a 0\u20130 draw with [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]. On 22 September 2013, Robertson scored his first goal for Dundee United, in a 2\u20132 draw against [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Dundee United 2\u20132 Motherwell|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24098544|website=BBC Sport|date=22 September 2013|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> He ran from his own half before sending a low left-foot drive in to the goal from 22 yards.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/dundee-utd-2-2-motherwell-ainsworth-stuns-utd-1-3106278 |title=Dundee Utd 2\u20132 Motherwell: Ainsworth stuns Utd |newspaper= The Scotsman|date=22 September 2013|accessdate=5 August 2014}}</ref> Soon afterwards he agreed a new contract with United, until May 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dundee secure Robertson extension|url=http://www.dundeeunitedfc.co.uk/index.asp?tm=2&nid=4617&cd=2013|publisher= Dundee United F.C. |date=4 October 2013|accessdate=5 August 2014}}</ref> He was voted [[Scottish Professional Football League monthly awards|SPFL young player of the month]] for September 2013 and player of the month for November 2013.<ref name=\"pom1113\">{{cite news|title=Dundee United defender wins player award|url=http://www.eveningtelegraph.co.uk/sport/dundee-united/dundee-united-defender-wins-player-award-1.162529|work=Evening Telegraph|date=7 December 2013|accessdate=24 November 2014}}</ref> On 12 April 2014, Robertson played in the [[2013\u201314 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]] Semi-final against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] at [[Ibrox Stadium|Ibrox]], which United won 3\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rangers 1\u20133 Dundee United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26898652|website=BBC Sport|last=Wilson|first=Richard|date=12 April 2014|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref> In April 2014, Robertson won the [[PFA Scotland Young Player of the Year]] award<ref name=\"ypoy14\">{{cite news|title=Three Celtic players make player of year shortlist|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27052382|website=BBC Sport|date=17 April 2014|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Andrew Robertson: Dundee United defender wins PFA prize|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27183894|website=BBC Sport|date=27 April 2014|accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref> and was also named in the [[PFA Scotland Team of the Year]] for the [[2013\u201314 Scottish Premiership]].<ref name=\"toy14\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27080030|title=Celtic and Dundee United trios in SPFL Premiership team of year|date=18 April 2014|accessdate=24 April 2014|website=BBC Sport }}</ref>\n\n===Hull City===\n[[File: Andy Robertson (19596759769).jpg|thumb|upright|Robertson playing for [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] in 2015]]\n\nIn July 2014, Dundee United accepted an offer of \u00a32.85&nbsp;million for Robertson from English [[Premier League]] club [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28442322 |title=Andrew Robertson: Dundee United agree fee with Hull City |website=BBC Sport |date=24 July 2014 |accessdate=24 July 2014 |first=Jim |last=Spence}}</ref> The transfer was completed on 29 July, as Robertson signed a three-year contract with Hull.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/clubs/dundee-united/284200-andrew-robertson-completes-transfer-from-dundee-united-to-hull/|title=Andrew Robertson completes transfer from Dundee United to Hull|work=STV Sport|date=29 July 2014|accessdate=20 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730093640/http://sport.stv.tv/football/clubs/dundee-united/284200-andrew-robertson-completes-transfer-from-dundee-united-to-hull/|archive-date=30 July 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> As Stan Ternent, Hull City\u2019s chief scout explained, \"I'd been looking at [[Stuart Armstrong]] but [Robertson] was the no brainer \u2026 he'd a history with Celtic and he was always a determined lad given how he'd recovered from his setbacks. You could see straight away he had ability and he can only get better.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/how-hull-city-helped-andy-1610379|title=How Hull City helped Andy Robertson to win the Champions League|last=Buckingham|first=Philip|last2=Colman|first2=Jonty|date=2 June 2019|website=Hull Daily Mail|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe made his competitive debut on the opening day of the season in a 1\u20130 victory away to [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|QPR]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2726678/QPR-0-1-Hull-City-Charlie-Austin-rues-penalty-miss-James-Chester-beats-Rio-Ferdinand-ball-head-home-winner.html|title=QPR 0\u20131 Hull City: Charlie Austin rues penalty miss as James Chester beats Rio Ferdinand to the ball to head home winner|website=Daily Mail|last=Mokbel|first=Sami|date=16 August 2014|accessdate=16 August 2014}}</ref> Robertson quickly settled at Hull and established himself in the side, winning the club's Player of the Month award for August 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Robertson|first1=Neil|title=Andrew Robertson named Hull City's player of the month|url=http://www.thecourier.co.uk/sport/football/dundee-united/andrew-robertson-named-hull-city-s-player-of-the-month-1.581056|publisher=The Courier (Dundee)|accessdate=24 November 2014|date=17 September 2014}}</ref> He made 24 appearances in his debut season at the [[KC Stadium]], but was unable to prevent the team from being relegated to [[EFL Championship|the Championship]].<ref name=\"TFT\">{{cite web|url=https://thesefootballtimes.co/2019/02/19/how-andy-robertson-rose-from-rejection-and-amateur-football-to-become-one-of-europes-best-left-backs/|title=How Andy Robertson rose from rejection and amateur football to become one of Europe's best left-backs|last=Henderson|first=Lewis|date=19 February 2019|website=These Football Times|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nDespite the release of several other first-team players, Robertson opted to stay at City. His first goal for the club came on 3 November 2015 away to [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] where he opened the scoring in a 2\u20130 win to put Hull top of the Championship table on goal difference.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34644748|title=Brentford 0\u20132 Hull|date=3 November 2015|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref> He started the [[2016 Football League play-offs#Championship|2016 Championship Play-off Final]] against [[Sheffield Wednesday]], which Hull won 1\u20130 to secure promotion to the [[Premier League]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Williams |title=Hull City 1\u20130 Sheffield Wednesday |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36348885 |website=BBC Sport |date=28 May 2016 |accessdate=22 December 2017}}</ref> The team spent just one season back in the top flight, however, before being relegated yet again.<ref name=\"TFT\"/>\n\n===Liverpool===\n[[File:Liver-RM (10).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Robertson playing for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the [[2018 UEFA Champions League Final]]]]\n\nOn 21 July 2017, Robertson signed a long-term deal with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] for an initial fee of \u00a38&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|title=Andrew Robertson: Liverpool sign defender from Hull City for \u00a310m|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40666486|website=BBC Sport|date=21 July 2017|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/269167-liverpool-fc-complete-andy-robertson-signing|title=Liverpool FC complete Andy Robertson signing|date=21 July 2017|publisher=Liverpool FC|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref> On 19 August, he made his debut in a 1\u20130 win over [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/andy-robertson-thanks-liverpool-fans-13501385|title=Robertson thanks Liverpool fans after impressing on Reds debut|last=Gorst|first=Paul|date=19 August 2017|work=Liverpool Echo|accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref> winning the Man of the Match award.<ref name=places/> Robertson started the 2017\u201318 season as understudy to [[Alberto Moreno]], but got a run of games when the Spaniard was injured in December. His performance in the 4\u20133 victory against league leaders [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on 14 January earned praise from the Liverpool supporters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/klopps-patience-key-andy-robertson-14164148|title=Klopp's patience was key for Andy Robertson and Alex Oxlade-Chamberlain|last=Jones|first=Paul|date=16 January 2018|work=Liverpool Echo|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club on the final match day of the 2017\u201318 season against [[Brighton and Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] in a 4\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44020158|title=Salah breaks record as Liverpool secure top four spot|last=Jennings|first=Patrick|date=13 May 2018|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=13 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box|width=32%|align=right|quote=Marauding runs down the left have seen Andy Robertson establish himself as a fan favourite since his \u00a38m move from Hull City in 2017. One of the world's best left-backs cost Liverpool just \u00a38m.|source = \u2014 Sam Harris writing for the [[BBC]] after the [[2019 UEFA Champions League Final]]<ref>{{cite news |title=The amazing back stories behind Liverpool's European champions |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48500373 |accessdate=4 June 2019 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>}}\nRobertson continued to play regularly for Liverpool during the 2018&ndash;19 season when Liverpool were runners-up in the Premier League.<ref name = \"contract\"/> He signed a new contract with the club in January 2019, which is due to run until 2024.<ref name = \"contract\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46911501 |title=Andy Robertson: Liverpool & Scotland defender signs new contract until 2024 |website=BBC Sport |date=17 January 2019 |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref> He has been hailed as the best left back in the Premier League by [[Kevin Kilbane]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/andy-robertson-labelled-best-left-15703038|title=Andy Robertson labelled the best left-back in the Premier League|last=Marshall-Bailey|first=Tom|date=19 January 2019|website=Liverpool Echo|accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref> and the best left back in the world by [[Phil Neville]].<ref name=\"Neville\">{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/scotland/scotland-and-liverpool-ace-andy-robertson-best-left-back-in-the-world-says-neville-1-4886956|title=Scotland and Liverpool ace Andy Robertson 'best left-back in the world' says Neville|last=Sked|first=Joel|date=11 March 2019|website=The Scotsman|accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref> On 25 April, he was named in the [[PFA Team of the Year]] alongside Liverpool teammates, [[Trent Alexander-Arnold]], [[Sadio Man\u00e9]] and [[Virgil van Dijk]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thepfa.com/news/2019/4/25/premier-league-team-of-the-year|title=PFA Premier League Team of the Year|publisher=The Player's Football Association|date=25 April 2019|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 June 2019, Robertson played the full 90 minutes of the [[2019 UEFA Champions League Final|Champions League final]] as Liverpool beat [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] to secure their sixth European Cup.<ref name = \"2019 CL\"/> He became the first Scot to win the tournament since [[Darren Fletcher]] (an unused substitute in [[2008 UEFA Champions League Final|2008]])<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/sport/17678775.scotland-captain-andy-robertson-and-his-liverpool-teammates-join-the-greats/|title=Scotland captain Andy Robertson, and his Liverpool teammates, join the greats|date=1 June 2019|website=Evening Times|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> and the first to actually be on the field in a winning team since [[Paul Lambert]] in [[1997 UEFA Champions League Final|1997]].<ref name = \"2019 CL\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48489952 |title=Liverpool can 'kick-on' from 'incredible' Champions League win - Andy Robertson |website=BBC Sport |date=2 June 2019 |accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the European champions' first home game of the Champions League for the 2019\u201320 campaign, Robertson scored his first European goal in a dramatic 4\u20133 victory against [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/andy-robertson-hails-liverpool-teammate-20392395|title=Andy Robertson hails Liverpool teammate after goal against Red Bull Salzburg|last=Bicknell|first=Gareth|date=3 October 2019|website=mirror|access-date=3 October 2019}}</ref> On 2 November 2019, Robertson scored his second Premier League goal for Liverpool, equalising in the 87th minute against [[Aston Villa]], with Liverpool eventually winning 2\u20131 in stoppage time.<ref>{{cite news |title=Leaders Liverpool fight back to down Villa |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50190998 |date=2 November 2019 |accessdate=2 November 2019 |agency=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Andrew Robertson 2019.jpg|thumb|upright|Robertson captaining [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] in 2019]]\n\nRobertson was first selected by the [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland under-21 team]] in October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/24352061|title=Billy Stark names Scotland Under-21 squad for Euro 2015 ties|date=1 October 2013|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He made his debut as a substitute in a 2\u20131 win against [[Slovakia national under-21 football team|Slovakia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2015/teams/player=250066157/index.html|title=Under-21 \u2013 Andrew Robertson \u2013 UEFA}}</ref> \nRobertson was selected for the under-21 team in November 2015, as the full national team did not have a fixture.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34701509 |title=Scotland U21s include Andy Robertson for Ukraine match |website=BBC Sport |date=2 November 2015 |accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nRobertson was first named in the full [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] squad for a friendly against [[Poland national football team|Poland]] on 5 March 2014. He came on as a substitute in the second half, as Scotland won 1\u20130 in Warsaw.<ref name = \"poland\"/> Scotland manager [[Gordon Strachan]] said afterwards \"Andy came on there and the first time he picked it up he drove about 30 yards. I thought 'that's fantastic'. Absolutely no grey area, I'm going to do what I do. I loved seeing that first touch.\"<ref name = \"poland\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/mar/05/poland-scotland-friendly-international-match-report |title=Scott Brown late show gives Scotland impressive win over Poland in Warsaw |work=The Guardian |date=5 March 2014 |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> Robertson made his first start for the national team in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] on 28 May 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27383284 |quote=Scotland's new-look back four, which included Dundee United's Andrew Robertson making his first international start, found themselves under pressure when they conceded possession to Uchebo but Allan McGregor saved the shot. |title=Nigeria 2\u20132 Scotland |first=Andy |last=Campbell |website=BBC Sport |date=28 May 2014 |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nRobertson scored his first international goal in a friendly against [[England national football team|England]] at [[Celtic Park]] in November 2014, scoring Scotland's only goal as they were beaten 3\u20131.<ref name = \"eng goal\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29999555|title=Scotland 1 \u2013 3 England|date=18 November 2014|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 September 2018, Robertson was appointed as [[List of Scotland national football team captains|Scotland captain]] by manager [[Alex McLeish]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/314927-andy-robertson-scotland-captain|title=Andy Robertson appointed new Scotland captain|publisher=Liverpool FC|last=Shaw|first=Chris|date=3 September 2018|accessdate=3 September 2018}}</ref> After a 2\u20131 defeat against [[Israel national football team|Israel]] in October 2018, Robertson said that both he and fellow left-back [[Kieran Tierney]] were being played out of position in the 3\u20135\u20132 system adopted by [[Alex McLeish]] to accommodate both players.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45832123 |title=Andy Robertson: Kieran Tierney and I are 'both out of position' |website=BBC Sport |date=12 October 2018 |accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a [[UEFA Euro 2020]] [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying Group I|qualifier]] against Cyprus on 8 June 2019, Robertson scored the opening goal of the game with a long-range strike. Scotland eventually won 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/scotland-vs-cyprus-result-euro-2020-qualifying-oliver-burke-goal-john-mcginn-a8950926.html|title=Scotland vs Cyprus result: Euro 2020 qualifying hopes still alive after last-gasp win says John McGinn|last=Esplin|first=Ronnie|date=9 June 2019|work=The Independent|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> In November, he was one of five Scotland players to withdraw from the national squad due to injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/scotland/50389854|title=Scotland: Andy Robertson, Ryan Fraser and Scott McTominay withdraw from squad|date=12 November 2019|accessdate=12 November 2019|website=BBC Sport|first=Jane|last=Lewis}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nRobertson is considered by former [[England national football team|England]] defender [[Phil Neville]] to be one of the best left-backs in the world, due to his pace, energy, and [[Cross (football)|crossing]] ability.<ref name=\"Neville\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nRobertson is engaged to Rachel Roberts,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/showbiz-news/meet-new-everton-livepool-wags-13305301|title=Meet the new Everton and Liverpool WAGS|last=McCoid|first=Sophie|date=4 August 2017|work=Liverpool Echo|accessdate=4 September 2018|quote=...his girlfriend Rachel Roberts is due to give birth to the couple's first child.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://heavy.com/sports/2019/01/andy-robertson-girlfriend-rachel-roberts/|title=Rachel Roberts, Andy Robertson's Girlfriend: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|last=Farrell|first=Paul|date=3 January 2019|website=Heavy.com|accessdate=1 June 2019}}</ref> who gave birth to their son, Rocco, on 26 August 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/andy-robertson-reveals-liverpool-icon-11090277|title=Andy Robertson reveals Liverpool icon Kenny Dalglish told him he's got his back|last=McDermott|first=Scott|date=1 September 2017|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|accessdate=8 September 2017}}</ref> In January 2019, the couple welcomed their second child and first daughter, Aria.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpool-victory-perfect-end-special-15672380|title=Liverpool victory was perfect end to special week for Andy Robertson|last=Pearce|first=James|date=13 January 2019|work=Liverpool Echo|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Robertson donated a signed Liverpool shirt of his teammate [[Roberto Firmino]] to a young boy who had given his pocket money to a local [[food bank]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/scotland/43324198 |title=Andrew Robertson gifts Liverpool top to young fan for making foodbank donation |website=BBC Sport |date=8 March 2018 |accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref> ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' reported in March 2020 that Robertson had donated significant sums to food banks in the Glasgow area.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/sport/liverpools-andy-robertson-believed-to-be-player-behind-huge-foodbank-donation-in-scotland-hvzfmrjpb |title=Liverpool\u2019s Andy Robertson believed to be player behind huge foodbank donation in Scotland |newspaper=The Sunday Times |publisher= |first=Jonathan |last=Northcroft |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 11 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|National Cup{{efn|Includes [[Scottish Cup]], [[FA Cup]]}}\n!colspan=2|League Cup{{efn|Includes [[Scottish League Cup]], [[EFL Cup|League/EFL Cup]]}}\n!colspan=2|Europe\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]]\n|[[2012\u201313 Queen's Park F.C. season|2012\u201313]]<ref name=\"Soccerway\">{{cite web|title=A. Robertson|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/andrew-robertson/254527/|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref>\n|[[Scottish Football League Third Division|Scottish Third Division]]\n|34||2||2||0||3||0||colspan=2|\u2014||4<ref group=\"lower-alpha\">Two appearances in the [[Scottish Challenge Cup]], two in Second Division play-offs</ref>||0||43||2\n|-\n|[[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]\n|[[2013\u201314 Dundee United F.C. season|2013\u201314]]<ref name=\"Soccerway\"/>\n|[[Scottish Premiership]]\n|36||3||5||2||3||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||44||5\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]]\n|[[2014\u201315 Hull City A.F.C. season|2014\u201315]]<ref name=\"Soccerway\"/>\n|[[Premier League]]\n|24||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||24||0\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 Hull City A.F.C. season|2015\u201316]]<ref name=\"Soccerway\"/>\n|[[EFL Championship|Championship]]\n|42||2||2||0||5||1||colspan=2|\u2014||3<ref group=\"lower-alpha\">Appearances in [[2016 Football League play-offs#Championship|Championship play-offs]]</ref>||1||52||4\n|-\n|[[2016\u20