 2013<ref name=\"pom1113\"/>\n*[[List of Scottish Professional Football League monthly award winners|SPFL Young Player of the Month]]: September 2013<ref name=\"pom1113\" />\n*[[PFA Team of the Year]]: [[PFA Team of the Year (2010s)#Premier League 10|2018\u201319 Premier League]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48028713|title=PFA Team of the Year: Paul Pogba, Raheem Sterling and Sadio Mane included in side|website=BBC Sport|date=25 April 2019|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n*UEFA Champions League Squad of the Season: [[2018\u201319 UEFA Champions League#Squad of the Season|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2607890.html |title=UEFA Champions League Squad of the Season |publisher=UEFA.com |date=2 June 2019 |accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n*[[FIFPro#FIFA FIFPro Men's World11|FIFA FIFPro World11]] nominee: [[The Best FIFA Football Awards 2019#FIFA FIFPro Men's World11|2019]] (7th defender)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fifpro.org/news/rankings-how-all-55-male-players-finished/en/|title=Rankings: How All 55 Male Players Finished|website=FIFPro World Players' Union|date=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA Team of the Year]]: [[UEFA Team of the Year#Team of the Year 2019|2019]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2637433.html |title=UEFA.com fans' Team of the Year 2019 revealed |publisher=UEFA |date=15 January 2020 |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://www.liverpoolfc.com/team/first-team/player/andy-robertson Profile] at the Liverpool F.C. website\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{Liverpool F.C. squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| list1 = \n{{PFA Scotland Young Player of the Year}}\n{{2013\u201314 PFA Scotland Scottish Premiership Team of the Year}}\n{{2018\u201319 Premier League PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{2019 UEFA Team of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robertson, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football fullbacks]]\n[[Category:Queen's Park F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dundee United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hull City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Champions League winning players]]\n[[Category:Scotland under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland international footballers]]\n", "name_user": "95.44.124.74", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Robertson"}
{"title_page": "Robert L. Caslen", "text_new": "{{short description|university administrator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Robert L. Caslen\n|image = Bob Caslen (cropped).jpg\n|order = 29th\n|title = [[President of the University of South Carolina|President of the {{nowrap|University of South Carolina}}]]\n|term_start = August 1, 2019\n|term_end = \n|predecessor = [[Harris Pastides]]\n|successor = \n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1953|11|30}}\n|birth_place = [[Connecticut]], United States\n|death_date = \n|death_place = \n|alma_mater = [[United States Military Academy]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[Long Island University]] (MBA)<br>[[Kansas State University]] ([[Master of Science]])<br>[[Long Island University]] ([[Honorary PhD]])\n|allegiance = United States\n|branch = [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears = 1975\u20132018\n|rank = [[Lieutenant general (United States)|Lieutenant General]]\n|commands = [[Superintendent of the United States Military Academy|United States Military Academy]]<br/>[[25th Infantry Division (United States)|25th Infantry Division]]\n|battles = [[Gulf War]]<br/>[[Operation Uphold Democracy]]<br/>[[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]<br/>[[Iraq War]]\n|mawards = [[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]]<br/>[[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]] (3)<br/>[[Defense Superior Service Medal]] (2)<br/>[[Legion of Merit]] (5)<br/>[[Bronze Star Medal]] (3)\n|website = [https://sc.edu/about/our_leadership/president/index.php/ Office of the President]\n}}\n'''Robert Louis Caslen Jr.''' (born November 30, 1953) is the 29th and current President of the [[University of South Carolina]]. He is a retired [[United States Army]] officer who served as the 59th [[Superintendent of the United States Military Academy|superintendent]] of West Point from 2013 until 2018.<ref> {{cite web |title=General Officer Announcements |url=http://www.defense.gov/releases/release.aspx?releaseid=15788|work=News Release|publisher=US Department of Defense |accessdate=January 27, 2013}} {{cite web|title=Office of the Superintendent |url=http://www.usma.edu/superintendent/SitePages/Biography.aspx |work=Bio|publisher=US Military Academy|accessdate=August 6, 2013}}</ref> Between January and May 2019, Caslen was Senior Counsel to the President and Interim Chief Financial Officer at the [[University of Central Florida]].<ref>[https://www.sc.edu/about/presidential_search/president_elect/ Robert L. Caslen Jr. University of South Carolina President-Elect.] University of South Carolina. Retrieved July 27, 2019.</ref> On July 19, 2019, the Board of Trustees of the [[University of South Carolina]] elected him as the school's 29th President, a position he assumed on August 1, 2019.<ref>[https://www.wltx.com/article/news/local/usc-president-elect-bob-caslen-addresses-his-selection-challenges-ahead-and-vision-for-university/101-31a03f53-dece-4516-baf9-fa3319e88ea7 USC president-elect 'Bob' Caslen addresses his selection, challenges ahead and vision for University.] WLTX, July 22, 2019.</ref> Caslen now serves as HigherEchelon's Special Advisor on Executive Leadership and Character Development.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.higherechelon.com/robert-caslen/ |title = Robert Caslen}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nCaslen was born in [[Connecticut]],<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=Register of Graduates and Former Cadets of the United States Military Academy|author1=West Point Alumni Foundation, inc|author2=United States Military Academy. Association of Graduates |date=1991|publisher=Association of Graduates, USMA.|issn=0090-2357|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=xXreAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> and grew up in Connecticut, [[Massachusetts]], and [[Vermont]]. In 1971 he graduated from [[North Country Union High School]] in [[Newport (city), Vermont|Newport, Vermont]].<ref>{{cite news |date=April 29, 2014 |title=National Football Foundation Vermont Chapter Honors Finest From 2013 Football Season |url=http://www.footballfoundation.org/News/NewsDetail/tabid/567/Article/54761/national-football-foundation-vermont-chapter-honors-finest-from-2013-football-s.aspx |newspaper=National Football Foundation |location=Irving, TX}}</ref> He graduated from the [[United States Military Academy at West Point]] in 1975 and played [[Center (gridiron football)|center]] for the [[Army Black Knights football]] team. He also earned a master's degree in business administration from [[Long Island University]], and in 1989 he received a Master of Science degree in industrial engineering from [[Kansas State University]].<ref name=\"allgov1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allgov.com/Appointments_and_Resignations/ViewNews/Commander_of_Army_Combined_Arms_Center__Who_is_Robert_Caslen_Jr_101125 |title=News \u2013 Commander of Army Combined Arms Center: Who is Robert Caslen, Jr.? |publisher=AllGov |date=September 11, 2001 |accessdate=November 25, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"KansasState\">{{cite web|url=http://www.engg.ksu.edu/news/archive/jan-june14/hall-of-fame2014.html |title=College of Engineering Hall of Fame gained two new members |publisher=KansasStateUniversity |date=June 1, 2014 |accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> Caslen also received an honorary doctorate from Long Island University.<ref>[https://sc.edu/docs/caslen_cv.pdf Robert L. Caslen, Jr.] Curriculum Vitae. Retrieved 26 July 2019.</ref>\n\n==Military career==\nDuring [[Operation Desert Storm]], Caslen served as executive officer of the 2nd Battalion, 187th Infantry, 101st Airborne Division (Air Assault).<ref name=\"allgov1\"/>\n\nCaslen served as brigade operations officer, 3rd Brigade, 101st Airborne Division (Air Assault); J-3 in [[Honduras]] for Joint Task Force Bravo in 1998; executive officer to the deputy commander in [[Haiti]] during [[Operation Uphold Democracy]] in 1994\u20131995; commander of the 1st Battalion, 14th Infantry, 25th Infantry Division (Light); senior brigade C2 observer/controller, Operations Group, Joint Readiness Training Center; chief of staff of the 101st Airborne Division; and commander of the 2nd Brigade, 101st Airborne Division (1999).<ref name=\"allgov1\"/>\n\nCaslen was at the [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]] during the [[September 11 attacks]]. Following the attack, he re-entered the Pentagon, helping search for wounded and working on reversing the air conditioning system in order to remove smoke from the building.<ref name=\"allgov1\"/> Caslen was also chief of staff of the 10th Mountain Division (Light) (2003) at [[Fort Drum]]; assistant division commander (Maneuver) of the 3rd Infantry Division (Mechanized) (2004); deputy director for the War on Terrorism, J-5, the Joint Staff (2005&nbsp;\u2013 June 2006); director of the Joint Staff's Detainee Affairs Division and commandant of cadets for the Military Academy at West Point, a post he left in May 2008. Caslen was chief of staff for the [[Combined Joint Task Force 180]] in Afghanistan from May through September 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cgsc.cdmhost.com/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/p4013coll13&CISOPTR=967&CISOBOX=1&REC=17 |title=Combined Arms Research Library Digital Library : Item Viewer |publisher=Cgsc.cdmhost.com |date=April 4, 2008 |accessdate=November 25, 2010}}</ref> He was a commander of [[Operation Champion Sword]].\n\nAccording to a report by the [[Office of Inspector General]], Caslen, fellow Army General [[Vincent K. Brooks]] and Air Force generals Peter U. Sutton and Jack J. Catton Jr \"violated the ethical guidelines of the military that forbid officers to promote private organizations\" when they appeared in a video for an [[evangelical]] organization [[Christian Embassy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/bps/additionalcontent/18/27689400/Report-Says-Pentagon-Erred-In-Allowing-Christian-Video|title=Report Says Pentagon Erred In Allowing Christian Video \u2013 Church and State \u2013 September 2007|publisher=|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref> At the time he was [[List of United States Military Academy alumni (Commandants of Cadets)|Commandant of Cadets]] at West Point. In a letter, he said he would be more vigilant about such improprieties going forward.<ref name=\"washingtonpost\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/08/03/AR2007080301907.html |title=Officers' Roles in Christian Video Are Called Ethics Breach |work=Washington Post|date=August 4, 2007 |accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrom May 2008 to December 2009, Caslen served as commander of the [[25th Infantry Division (United States)|25th Infantry Division]]. In October, he returned from a tour with the division in the [[Iraq War]]. Prior to this, he had served two tours in [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan]] and one tour in the [[Gulf War]].<ref name=\"armytimes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2009/12/ap_cg_leavenworth_120709/ |title=Caslen tapped to command Fort Leavenworth \u2013 Army Times \u2013 December 7, 2009 |publisher=armytimes.com|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> In December 2009, Caslen was nominated to be a [[Lieutenant general (United States)|lieutenant general]] in conjunction with his nomination to be [[Commandant of the United States Army Command and General Staff College]] at [[Fort Leavenworth]] which took effect in March 2010. In July 2011, Caslen was nominated to be chief of [[Office of Security Cooperation]] in Iraq.<ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Will |url=https://www.army.mil/article/35389/combined_arms_center_welcomes_new_commander |title=Combined Arms Center welcomes new commander |publisher=Fort Leavenworth Lamp |date=March 5, 2010 |accessdate=May 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCaslen was appointed as [[Superintendent of the United States Military Academy]] on July 17, 2013. After five years of service, in April 2018 it was announced that Caslen would retire later in the year.<ref>{{cite news |date=April 19, 2018 |title=USMA superintendent to retire |url=https://www.midhudsonnews.com/News/2018/April/19/USMA_Caslen_retire-19Apr18.html |work=Mid-Hudson News |location=Middletown, NY |ref={{sfnRef|\"USMA superintendent to retire\"}}}}</ref> In July, the army announced Lieutenant General [[Darryl A. Williams]] as Caslen's successor.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |date=July 1, 2018 |title=West Point gets 1st black superintendent in 216-year history |url=https://www.armytimes.com/news/your-army/2018/07/01/west-point-gets-1st-black-superintendent-in-216-year-history/ |work=[[Army Times]] |location=Springfield, Virginia}}</ref> The ceremonial relinquishing of command took place on June 22, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.armytimes.com/news/your-army/2018/06/21/after-43-years-in-the-army-west-points-beloved-supe-daddy-retires|title=After 43 years in the Army, West Point's beloved Supe Daddy retires |first=Noah|last=Nash|date=June 21, 2018|publisher=Army Times}}</ref> \n\nOver the course of his military career, Caslen received numerous civilian and military awards, including [[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]], [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]], [[Defense Superior Service Medal]], [[Bronze Star Medal]], [[German Armed Forces Badge for Military Proficiency]], [[Defense Meritorious Service Medal]], [[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]], [[Humanitarian Service Medal]], Lifetime of Service Award from the [[American_Red_Cross| American Red Cross]], and [[National_Collegiate_Athletic_Association| NCAA]] [[Theodore_Roosevelt_Award| Theodore Roosevelt Award]], amongst others.<ref>[https://www.sc.edu/docs/caslen_bio.pdf Robert L. Caslen, Jr Biography.] Retrieved July 28, 2019.</ref>\n\nFollowing his retirement from West Point, Caslen was in January 2019 appointed as chief accountability officer at the [[University of Central Florida]] to oversee the reformation of the finance and administration operations, a position from which he resigned in May. \n\n==University of South Carolina Presidency==\nOn July 19, 2019, Caslen was selected as the 29th President of the [[University of South Carolina]]. He was initially among a group of four finalists for the position. While Caslen was reported to be the front-runner,<ref>[https://www.postandcourier.com/news/usc-reopens-president-search-after-campus-backlash-over-former-west/article_4105af96-67ad-11e9-b274-d3feaa89f4ee.html USC reopens president search after campus backlash over former West Point leader.] The Post and Courier, April 26, 2019.</ref> there was significant controversy about his nomination, given that he does not possess an [[Doctoral degree|earned doctorate]] and because of alleged comments made during open campus sessions regarding binge drinking and sexual assault; <ref>{{cite news |last=Daprile |first=Lucas |url=https://www.thestate.com/news/local/article229689994.html |title=Amid protests, USC reopens search to replace Pastides, names interim president |publisher=The State |date=April 26, 2019 |accessdate=July 19, 2019}} {{cite news |last=WLTX |url=https://www.wltx.com/article/news/local/street-squad/usc/sudden-usc-president-vote-draws-criticism-support/101-b528d060-1de6-4d29-a4fc-dc7244569e66 |title=Sudden USC president vote draws criticism, support |publisher=WLTX |date=April 26, 2019 |accessdate=July 19, 2019}}</ref> among faculty and students, 82% opposed Caslen's candidacy.<ref>{{cite news |last=WLTX |url=https://www.wltx.com/article/news/local/street-squad/usc/sudden-usc-president-vote-draws-criticism-support/101-b528d060-1de6-4d29-a4fc-dc7244569e66 |title=Sudden USC president vote draws criticism, support |publisher=WLTX |date=26 April 2019 |accessdate=19 July 2019}}</ref> It was later discovered by the [[The Post and Courier|Charleston Post and Courier]] that Mr. Caslen's name was added to the finalist list only after the intervention of the Chairman of the Board of Trustees as Caslen was not originally a finalist or an agreed upon alternate nominated by the presidential search committee<ref>{{cite news |last=Shain |first=Andy |url=https://www.postandcourier.com/politics/usc-faculty-chair-caslen-got-help-after-not-making-semifinalist/article_99468b7e-c033-11e9-9863-f7f6f0424f80.html |title=USC faculty chair: Caslen got help after not making semifinalist list for president |publisher=Charleston Post and Courier |date=August 16, 2019 |accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref>. On April 26, the university [[University_of_South_Carolina_System#Board_of_Trustees| Board of Trustees]] decided to reopen the search. However, it was revealed on July 8, that [[South Carolina]] Governor [[Henry McMaster]] was urging members of the Board to meet by the end of the week to vote on Caslen's candidacy for President.<ref>{{cite news |last=WLTX |url=https://www.wltx.com/article/news/local/street-squad/usc/sudden-usc-president-vote-draws-criticism-support/101-b528d060-1de6-4d29-a4fc-dc7244569e66 |title=Sudden USC president vote draws criticism, support |publisher=WLTX |date=April 26, 2019 |accessdate=July 19, 2019}}</ref> This caused further controversy, with the university's faculty senate unanimously passing motions to formally criticize the lack of transparency in the search process and to issue a vote of [[Motion_of_no_confidence| no confidence]] in Caslen to lead the university.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bland |first=David Travis |url=https://www.thestate.com/news/local/education/article232559127.html |title=USC faculty rebukes McMaster's role in search, expresses 'no confidence' in Caslen |publisher=The State |date=July 11, 2019 |accessdate=July 19, 2019}}</ref>. Several alumni and donors also opposed the intervention of the governor in the presidential search; notably businesswoman [[Darla Moore]], writing as \"the largest donor to the university and the namesake of one of the largest [[Darla_Moore_School_of_Business| schools]],\" urged the board to abide by the April 26 decision to continue the search.<ref>{{cite news |last=WLTX |url=https://www.wltx.com/article/news/usc-donor-darla-moore-asks-for-usc-president-search-to-restart/101-be106168-e092-4423-8320-59bfdf92e629 |title=USC donor Darla Moore asks for USC president search to restart |publisher=WLTX |date=July 18, 2019 |accessdate=July 27, 2019}}</ref> and the [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools|SACS]] Commission on Colleges opening an inquiry into the search to determine if there was undue outside influence.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ardis |first=Susan |url=https://www.wltx.com/article/news/local/usc-accreditation-could-be-at-risk-over-president-search/101-46216655-b792-4647-aa9d-054ede7acb3a |title=USC accreditation could be at risk over president search |publisher=WLTX |date=July 16, 2019 |accessdate=July 19, 2019}}</ref> One trustee, Egerton Burroughs, believed that the opposition to Caslen was entirely political, stating, without evidence, \"A lot of the people that are demonstrating are from out of town. I heard some of that [[Kamala Harris]] crowd is there \u2026 got this thing all tied into the Democratic primary,\" though Burroughs was unaware his comments were being broadcast.<ref>{{cite news |last=WLTX Staff |url=https://www.wltx.com/article/news/local/usc-board-member-makes-statement-on-hot-mic/101-810b2b30-faeb-46ef-9ee7-4fbefc77f879 |title=USC board member makes statement on hot mic |publisher=WLTX |date=July 19, 2019 |accessdate=July 30, 2019}}</ref> Despite the opposition of faculty and students, on July 19, Caslen was elected as the 29th President of the University by the Board of Trustees by a vote of 11\u20138, with one member voting \"present\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Daprile |first=Lucas |url=https://www.thestate.com/news/local/education/article232875112.html |title=Despite opposition, USC board hires retired general Caslen as school's next president |publisher=The State |date=July 19, 2019 |accessdate=July 20, 2009}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his selection, Caslen stated that he recognized \"the challenges the board addressed to get to this point\" and expressed he would \"listen to all of our students, faculty, staff, board members, and all our constituents.\"<ref>[https://www.sc.edu/about/presidential_search/president_elect/ Robert L. Caslen Jr. University of South Carolina President-Elect.] University of South Carolina. Retrieved 27 July 2019.</ref> On July 22, 2019, Caslen held a press conference to announce his desire to raise the profile of the university by boosting the school's rankings, improving diversity, bolstering research, and beating in-state rival [[Clemson\u2013South Carolina rivalry|Clemson University]] in more athletic competitions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Glantz |first=Tracy |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/news/state/south-carolina/article232962627.html |title=Incoming USC President Robert Caslen lays out his vision for the school's future |publisher=The Charlotte Observer |date=July 23, 2019}}</ref> He also met with students, faculty, donors, and lawmakers, pledging to listen and learn.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leonard |first=Joseph |url=https://www.dailygamecock.com/article/2019/07/columbia-usc-caslen-president-elect |title=Robert Caslen pledges to listen to USC community as leader. |publisher=The Daily Gamecock |date=July 22, 2019 |accessdate=}}</ref> Caslen formally took office as the 29th President of the University of South Carolina on August 1, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dean |first=Rochelle |url=https://www.abccolumbia.com/2019/07/31/uofsc-welcomes-new-president-as-past-leader-retires |title=UofSC welcomes new president as past leader retires |publisher=WOLO |date=July 31, 2019 |accessdate=August 1, 2019}}</ref> On October 7, the SACS Commission on Colleges announced that it had opened an official inquiry into Mr. Caslen's selection as university president, SACS notified the university that there was \"evidence of a significant accreditation-related issue\" and opened a formal investigation into whether or not there was undue external influence on the search.<ref>{{cite news |last=Welch |first=Rodney |url=https://www.postandcourier.com/free-times/usc-faculty-open-up-about-the-controversial-hiring-of-new/article_853fc676-ef73-11e9-80e3-1f9d94654317.html |title=Bod and Weave: USC Faculty Open Up About the Controversial Hiring of a New President |publisher=Free Times (Charleston Post and Courier) |date=October 16, 2019 |accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref> Caslen himself acknowledging that the inquiry was legitimate and that trust between himself and the wider university community had been damaged.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mock |first=Andrea |url=https://www.wltx.com/article/news/local/street-squad/usc/bob-caslen-reacts-to-probe-into-his-hiring/101-ae6f208b-0a85-4111-85e3-69261bf75667 |title=USC president responds to controversy over his hiring |publisher=WLTX |date=October 8, 2019 |accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref> Though stated that the theSACS inquiry would result in no formal sanctions,<ref>{{cite news |last=Daprile |first=Lucas |url=https://www.thestate.com/news/local/education/article238230709.html |title=USC's presidential search will not result in formal sanctions, school says |publisher=The State |date=December 10, 2019 |accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref> the report did state that there was, in fact, undue political influence from the Governor in the selection of Mr. Caslen; Governor McMaster's office denied the finding by arguing that the Governor's influence is permissible as he is a member of the board of trustees ''ex officio''. The University will be subject to enhanced monitoring, a compliance report, and a site visit in Fall 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=WLTX |url=https://www.wltx.com/article/news/sacs-findings-usc-presidential-search/101-745b69f2-ae01-42cf-bbcb-7cb8705c64d9 |title='Undue influence' from Governor in USC's presidential search, board finds |publisher=WLTX |date= January 17, 2020 |accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn tandem with the SACS inquiry, the [[South Carolina Senate]] formed a bi-partisan committee to review the presidential search, looking into how to improve the process for future searches rather than remove Caslen as incumbent, though at least one member, [[Katrina Shealy]], proposed was to \"listen to the issues\" people had expressed with the search and then \"move on\" without any changes to improve the search process for the future.<ref>{{cite news |last=Scott |first=Tim |url=https://www.abccolumbia.com/2019/10/08/new-senate-committee-looks-to-address-issues-with-usc-presidential-search/ |title=New Senate committee looks to examine issues with USC presidential search |publisher=WOLO |date=October 8, 2019 |accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCaslen is married to Michele (Shelly) Caslen ({{nee}} Pastin) from Highland Falls, New York. They have three sons: Robert Caslen III, a firefighter; Jeffrey (Jeff) Caslen, a captain in the Army; and Nicholas (Nick) Caslen, an FBI special agent.<ref name=\"allgov1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Robert L. Caslen Jr.}}\n*[https://www.sc.edu/about/presidential_search/president_elect/ Robert L. Caslen Jr., University of South Carolina President-Elect] - University of South Carolina. Retrieved July 27, 2019.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160815140235/https://westpoint.edu/superintendent/SitePages/Biography.aspx Lieutenant General Robert L. Caslen, Jr] - Biography page, Office of the Superintendent. Archived. Retrieved July 27, 2019.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William B. Caldwell IV]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Commandant of the United States Army Command and General Staff College]]|years=2010\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[David G. Perkins]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[David H. Huntoon]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Superintendent of the United States Military Academy]]|years=2013\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Darryl A. Williams]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{United States Military Academy superintendents}}\n{{NCAA Theodore Roosevelt Award}}\n{{University of South Carolina presidents}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caslen, Robert}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Army Black Knights football players]]\n[[Category:Commandants of the Corps of Cadets of the United States Military Academy]]\n[[Category:Commandants of the United States Army Command and General Staff College]]\n[[Category:Kansas State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Long Island University alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Medal (US Army)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Defense Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Defense Superior Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|university administrator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Robert L. Caslen\n|image = Bob Caslen (cropped).jpg\n|order = 29th\n|title = [[President of the University of South Carolina|President of the {{nowrap|University of South Carolina}}]]\n|term_start = August 1, 2019\n|term_end = \n|predecessor = [[Harris Pastides]]\n|successor = \n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1953|11|30}}\n|birth_place = [[Connecticut]], United States\n|death_date = \n|death_place = \n|alma_mater = [[United States Military Academy]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[Long Island University]] (MBA)<br>[[Kansas State University]] ([[Master of Science]])<br>[[Long Island University]] ([[Honorary PhD]])\n|allegiance = United States\n|branch = [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears = 1975\u20132018\n|rank = [[Lieutenant general (United States)|Lieutenant General]]\n|commands = [[Superintendent of the United States Military Academy|United States Military Academy]]<br/>[[25th Infantry Division (United States)|25th Infantry Division]]\n|battles = [[Gulf War]]<br/>[[Operation Uphold Democracy]]<br/>[[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]<br/>[[Iraq War]]\n|awards = [[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]]<br/>[[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]] (3)<br/>[[Defense Superior Service Medal]] (2)<br/>[[Legion of Merit]] (5)<br/>[[Bronze Star Medal]] (3)\n|website = [https://sc.edu/about/our_leadership/president/index.php/ Office of the President]\n}}\n\n'''Robert Louis Caslen Jr.''' (born November 30, 1953) is the 29th and current President of the [[University of South Carolina]]. He is a retired [[United States Army]] officer who served as the 59th [[Superintendent of the United States Military Academy|superintendent]] of West Point from 2013 until 2018.<ref> {{cite web |title=General Officer Announcements |url=http://www.defense.gov/releases/release.aspx?releaseid=15788|work=News Release|publisher=US Department of Defense |accessdate=January 27, 2013}} {{cite web|title=Office of the Superintendent |url=http://www.usma.edu/superintendent/SitePages/Biography.aspx |work=Bio|publisher=US Military Academy|accessdate=August 6, 2013}}</ref> Between January and May 2019, Caslen was Senior Counsel to the President and Interim Chief Financial Officer at the [[University of Central Florida]].<ref>[https://www.sc.edu/about/presidential_search/president_elect/ Robert L. Caslen Jr. University of South Carolina President-Elect.] University of South Carolina. Retrieved July 27, 2019.</ref> On July 19, 2019, the Board of Trustees of the [[University of South Carolina]] elected him as the school's 29th President, a position he assumed on August 1, 2019.<ref>[https://www.wltx.com/article/news/local/usc-president-elect-bob-caslen-addresses-his-selection-challenges-ahead-and-vision-for-university/101-31a03f53-dece-4516-baf9-fa3319e88ea7 USC president-elect 'Bob' Caslen addresses his selection, challenges ahead and vision for University.] WLTX, July 22, 2019.</ref> Caslen now serves as HigherEchelon's Special Advisor on Executive Leadership and Character Development.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.higherechelon.com/robert-caslen/ |title = Robert Caslen}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nCaslen was born in [[Connecticut]],<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=Register of Graduates and Former Cadets of the United States Military Academy|author1=West Point Alumni Foundation, inc|author2=United States Military Academy. Association of Graduates |date=1991|publisher=Association of Graduates, USMA.|issn=0090-2357|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=xXreAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> and grew up in Connecticut, [[Massachusetts]], and [[Vermont]]. In 1971 he graduated from [[North Country Union High School]] in [[Newport (city), Vermont|Newport, Vermont]].<ref>{{cite news |date=April 29, 2014 |title=National Football Foundation Vermont Chapter Honors Finest From 2013 Football Season |url=http://www.footballfoundation.org/News/NewsDetail/tabid/567/Article/54761/national-football-foundation-vermont-chapter-honors-finest-from-2013-football-s.aspx |newspaper=National Football Foundation |location=Irving, TX}}</ref> He graduated from the [[United States Military Academy at West Point]] in 1975 and played [[Center (gridiron football)|center]] for the [[Army Black Knights football]] team. He also earned a master's degree in business administration from [[Long Island University]], and in 1989 he received a Master of Science degree in industrial engineering from [[Kansas State University]].<ref name=\"allgov1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allgov.com/Appointments_and_Resignations/ViewNews/Commander_of_Army_Combined_Arms_Center__Who_is_Robert_Caslen_Jr_101125 |title=News \u2013 Commander of Army Combined Arms Center: Who is Robert Caslen, Jr.? |publisher=AllGov |date=September 11, 2001 |accessdate=November 25, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"KansasState\">{{cite web|url=http://www.engg.ksu.edu/news/archive/jan-june14/hall-of-fame2014.html |title=College of Engineering Hall of Fame gained two new members |publisher=KansasStateUniversity |date=June 1, 2014 |accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> Caslen also received an honorary doctorate from Long Island University.<ref>[https://sc.edu/docs/caslen_cv.pdf Robert L. Caslen, Jr.] Curriculum Vitae. Retrieved 26 July 2019.</ref>\n\n==Military career==\nDuring [[Operation Desert Storm]], Caslen served as executive officer of the 2nd Battalion, 187th Infantry, 101st Airborne Division (Air Assault).<ref name=\"allgov1\"/>\n\nCaslen served as brigade operations officer, 3rd Brigade, 101st Airborne Division (Air Assault); J-3 in [[Honduras]] for Joint Task Force Bravo in 1998; executive officer to the deputy commander in [[Haiti]] during [[Operation Uphold Democracy]] in 1994\u20131995; commander of the 1st Battalion, 14th Infantry, 25th Infantry Division (Light); senior brigade C2 observer/controller, Operations Group, Joint Readiness Training Center; chief of staff of the 101st Airborne Division; and commander of the 2nd Brigade, 101st Airborne Division (1999).<ref name=\"allgov1\"/>\n\nCaslen was at the [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]] during the [[September 11 attacks]]. Following the attack, he re-entered the Pentagon, helping search for wounded and working on reversing the air conditioning system in order to remove smoke from the building.<ref name=\"allgov1\"/> Caslen was also chief of staff of the 10th Mountain Division (Light) (2003) at [[Fort Drum]]; assistant division commander (Maneuver) of the 3rd Infantry Division (Mechanized) (2004); deputy director for the War on Terrorism, J-5, the Joint Staff (2005&nbsp;\u2013 June 2006); director of the Joint Staff's Detainee Affairs Division and commandant of cadets for the Military Academy at West Point, a post he left in May 2008. Caslen was chief of staff for the [[Combined Joint Task Force 180]] in Afghanistan from May through September 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cgsc.cdmhost.com/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/p4013coll13&CISOPTR=967&CISOBOX=1&REC=17 |title=Combined Arms Research Library Digital Library : Item Viewer |publisher=Cgsc.cdmhost.com |date=April 4, 2008 |accessdate=November 25, 2010}}</ref> He was a commander of [[Operation Champion Sword]].\n\nAccording to a report by the [[Office of Inspector General]], Caslen, fellow Army General [[Vincent K. Brooks]] and Air Force generals Peter U. Sutton and Jack J. Catton Jr \"violated the ethical guidelines of the military that forbid officers to promote private organizations\" when they appeared in a video for an [[evangelical]] organization [[Christian Embassy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/bps/additionalcontent/18/27689400/Report-Says-Pentagon-Erred-In-Allowing-Christian-Video|title=Report Says Pentagon Erred In Allowing Christian Video \u2013 Church and State \u2013 September 2007|publisher=|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref> At the time he was [[List of United States Military Academy alumni (Commandants of Cadets)|Commandant of Cadets]] at West Point. In a letter, he said he would be more vigilant about such improprieties going forward.<ref name=\"washingtonpost\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/08/03/AR2007080301907.html |title=Officers' Roles in Christian Video Are Called Ethics Breach |work=Washington Post|date=August 4, 2007 |accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrom May 2008 to December 2009, Caslen served as commander of the [[25th Infantry Division (United States)|25th Infantry Division]]. In October, he returned from a tour with the division in the [[Iraq War]]. Prior to this, he had served two tours in [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan]] and one tour in the [[Gulf War]].<ref name=\"armytimes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2009/12/ap_cg_leavenworth_120709/ |title=Caslen tapped to command Fort Leavenworth \u2013 Army Times \u2013 December 7, 2009 |publisher=armytimes.com|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> In December 2009, Caslen was nominated to be a [[Lieutenant general (United States)|lieutenant general]] in conjunction with his nomination to be [[Commandant of the United States Army Command and General Staff College]] at [[Fort Leavenworth]] which took effect in March 2010. In July 2011, Caslen was nominated to be chief of [[Office of Security Cooperation]] in Iraq.<ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Will |url=https://www.army.mil/article/35389/combined_arms_center_welcomes_new_commander |title=Combined Arms Center welcomes new commander |publisher=Fort Leavenworth Lamp |date=March 5, 2010 |accessdate=May 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCaslen was appointed as [[Superintendent of the United States Military Academy]] on July 17, 2013. After five years of service, in April 2018 it was announced that Caslen would retire later in the year.<ref>{{cite news |date=April 19, 2018 |title=USMA superintendent to retire |url=https://www.midhudsonnews.com/News/2018/April/19/USMA_Caslen_retire-19Apr18.html |work=Mid-Hudson News |location=Middletown, NY |ref={{sfnRef|\"USMA superintendent to retire\"}}}}</ref> In July, the army announced Lieutenant General [[Darryl A. Williams]] as Caslen's successor.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |date=July 1, 2018 |title=West Point gets 1st black superintendent in 216-year history |url=https://www.armytimes.com/news/your-army/2018/07/01/west-point-gets-1st-black-superintendent-in-216-year-history/ |work=[[Army Times]] |location=Springfield, Virginia}}</ref> The ceremonial relinquishing of command took place on June 22, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.armytimes.com/news/your-army/2018/06/21/after-43-years-in-the-army-west-points-beloved-supe-daddy-retires|title=After 43 years in the Army, West Point's beloved Supe Daddy retires |first=Noah|last=Nash|date=June 21, 2018|publisher=Army Times}}</ref> \n\nOver the course of his military career, Caslen received numerous civilian and military awards, including [[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]], [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]], [[Defense Superior Service Medal]], [[Bronze Star Medal]], [[German Armed Forces Badge for Military Proficiency]], [[Defense Meritorious Service Medal]], [[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]], [[Humanitarian Service Medal]], Lifetime of Service Award from the [[American_Red_Cross| American Red Cross]], and [[National_Collegiate_Athletic_Association| NCAA]] [[Theodore_Roosevelt_Award| Theodore Roosevelt Award]], amongst others.<ref>[https://www.sc.edu/docs/caslen_bio.pdf Robert L. Caslen, Jr Biography.] Retrieved July 28, 2019.</ref>\n\nFollowing his retirement from West Point, Caslen was in January 2019 appointed as chief accountability officer at the [[University of Central Florida]] to oversee the reformation of the finance and administration operations, a position from which he resigned in May. \n\n==University of South Carolina Presidency==\nOn July 19, 2019, Caslen was selected as the 29th President of the [[University of South Carolina]]. He was initially among a group of four finalists for the position. While Caslen was reported to be the front-runner,<ref>[https://www.postandcourier.com/news/usc-reopens-president-search-after-campus-backlash-over-former-west/article_4105af96-67ad-11e9-b274-d3feaa89f4ee.html USC reopens president search after campus backlash over former West Point leader.] The Post and Courier, April 26, 2019.</ref> there was significant controversy about his nomination, given that he does not possess an [[Doctoral degree|earned doctorate]] and because of alleged comments made during open campus sessions regarding binge drinking and sexual assault; <ref>{{cite news |last=Daprile |first=Lucas |url=https://www.thestate.com/news/local/article229689994.html |title=Amid protests, USC reopens search to replace Pastides, names interim president |publisher=The State |date=April 26, 2019 |accessdate=July 19, 2019}} {{cite news |last=WLTX |url=https://www.wltx.com/article/news/local/street-squad/usc/sudden-usc-president-vote-draws-criticism-support/101-b528d060-1de6-4d29-a4fc-dc7244569e66 |title=Sudden USC president vote draws criticism, support |publisher=WLTX |date=April 26, 2019 |accessdate=July 19, 2019}}</ref> among faculty and students, 82% opposed Caslen's candidacy.<ref>{{cite news |last=WLTX |url=https://www.wltx.com/article/news/local/street-squad/usc/sudden-usc-president-vote-draws-criticism-support/101-b528d060-1de6-4d29-a4fc-dc7244569e66 |title=Sudden USC president vote draws criticism, support |publisher=WLTX |date=26 April 2019 |accessdate=19 July 2019}}</ref> It was later discovered by the [[The Post and Courier|Charleston Post and Courier]] that Mr. Caslen's name was added to the finalist list only after the intervention of the Chairman of the Board of Trustees as Caslen was not originally a finalist or an agreed upon alternate nominated by the presidential search committee<ref>{{cite news |last=Shain |first=Andy |url=https://www.postandcourier.com/politics/usc-faculty-chair-caslen-got-help-after-not-making-semifinalist/article_99468b7e-c033-11e9-9863-f7f6f0424f80.html |title=USC faculty chair: Caslen got help after not making semifinalist list for president |publisher=Charleston Post and Courier |date=August 16, 2019 |accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref>. On April 26, the university [[University_of_South_Carolina_System#Board_of_Trustees| Board of Trustees]] decided to reopen the search. However, it was revealed on July 8, that [[South Carolina]] Governor [[Henry McMaster]] was urging members of the Board to meet by the end of the week to vote on Caslen's candidacy for President.<ref>{{cite news |last=WLTX |url=https://www.wltx.com/article/news/local/street-squad/usc/sudden-usc-president-vote-draws-criticism-support/101-b528d060-1de6-4d29-a4fc-dc7244569e66 |title=Sudden USC president vote draws criticism, support |publisher=WLTX |date=April 26, 2019 |accessdate=July 19, 2019}}</ref> This caused further controversy, with the university's faculty senate unanimously passing motions to formally criticize the lack of transparency in the search process and to issue a vote of [[Motion_of_no_confidence| no confidence]] in Caslen to lead the university.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bland |first=David Travis |url=https://www.thestate.com/news/local/education/article232559127.html |title=USC faculty rebukes McMaster's role in search, expresses 'no confidence' in Caslen |publisher=The State |date=July 11, 2019 |accessdate=July 19, 2019}}</ref>. Several alumni and donors also opposed the intervention of the governor in the presidential search; notably businesswoman [[Darla Moore]], writing as \"the largest donor to the university and the namesake of one of the largest [[Darla_Moore_School_of_Business| schools]],\" urged the board to abide by the April 26 decision to continue the search.<ref>{{cite news |last=WLTX |url=https://www.wltx.com/article/news/usc-donor-darla-moore-asks-for-usc-president-search-to-restart/101-be106168-e092-4423-8320-59bfdf92e629 |title=USC donor Darla Moore asks for USC president search to restart |publisher=WLTX |date=July 18, 2019 |accessdate=July 27, 2019}}</ref> and the [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools|SACS]] Commission on Colleges opening an inquiry into the search to determine if there was undue outside influence.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ardis |first=Susan |url=https://www.wltx.com/article/news/local/usc-accreditation-could-be-at-risk-over-president-search/101-46216655-b792-4647-aa9d-054ede7acb3a |title=USC accreditation could be at risk over president search |publisher=WLTX |date=July 16, 2019 |accessdate=July 19, 2019}}</ref> One trustee, Egerton Burroughs, believed that the opposition to Caslen was entirely political, stating, without evidence, \"A lot of the people that are demonstrating are from out of town. I heard some of that [[Kamala Harris]] crowd is there \u2026 got this thing all tied into the Democratic primary,\" though Burroughs was unaware his comments were being broadcast.<ref>{{cite news |last=WLTX Staff |url=https://www.wltx.com/article/news/local/usc-board-member-makes-statement-on-hot-mic/101-810b2b30-faeb-46ef-9ee7-4fbefc77f879 |title=USC board member makes statement on hot mic |publisher=WLTX |date=July 19, 2019 |accessdate=July 30, 2019}}</ref> Despite the opposition of faculty and students, on July 19, Caslen was elected as the 29th President of the University by the Board of Trustees by a vote of 11\u20138, with one member voting \"present\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Daprile |first=Lucas |url=https://www.thestate.com/news/local/education/article232875112.html |title=Despite opposition, USC board hires retired general Caslen as school's next president |publisher=The State |date=July 19, 2019 |accessdate=July 20, 2009}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his selection, Caslen stated that he recognized \"the challenges the board addressed to get to this point\" and expressed he would \"listen to all of our students, faculty, staff, board members, and all our constituents.\"<ref>[https://www.sc.edu/about/presidential_search/president_elect/ Robert L. Caslen Jr. University of South Carolina President-Elect.] University of South Carolina. Retrieved 27 July 2019.</ref> On July 22, 2019, Caslen held a press conference to announce his desire to raise the profile of the university by boosting the school's rankings, improving diversity, bolstering research, and beating in-state rival [[Clemson\u2013South Carolina rivalry|Clemson University]] in more athletic competitions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Glantz |first=Tracy |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/news/state/south-carolina/article232962627.html |title=Incoming USC President Robert Caslen lays out his vision for the school's future |publisher=The Charlotte Observer |date=July 23, 2019}}</ref> He also met with students, faculty, donors, and lawmakers, pledging to listen and learn.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leonard |first=Joseph |url=https://www.dailygamecock.com/article/2019/07/columbia-usc-caslen-president-elect |title=Robert Caslen pledges to listen to USC community as leader. |publisher=The Daily Gamecock |date=July 22, 2019 |accessdate=}}</ref> Caslen formally took office as the 29th President of the University of South Carolina on August 1, 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dean |first=Rochelle |url=https://www.abccolumbia.com/2019/07/31/uofsc-welcomes-new-president-as-past-leader-retires |title=UofSC welcomes new president as past leader retires |publisher=WOLO |date=July 31, 2019 |accessdate=August 1, 2019}}</ref> On October 7, the SACS Commission on Colleges announced that it had opened an official inquiry into Mr. Caslen's selection as university president, SACS notified the university that there was \"evidence of a significant accreditation-related issue\" and opened a formal investigation into whether or not there was undue external influence on the search.<ref>{{cite news |last=Welch |first=Rodney |url=https://www.postandcourier.com/free-times/usc-faculty-open-up-about-the-controversial-hiring-of-new/article_853fc676-ef73-11e9-80e3-1f9d94654317.html |title=Bod and Weave: USC Faculty Open Up About the Controversial Hiring of a New President |publisher=Free Times (Charleston Post and Courier) |date=October 16, 2019 |accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref> Caslen himself acknowledging that the inquiry was legitimate and that trust between himself and the wider university community had been damaged.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mock |first=Andrea |url=https://www.wltx.com/article/news/local/street-squad/usc/bob-caslen-reacts-to-probe-into-his-hiring/101-ae6f208b-0a85-4111-85e3-69261bf75667 |title=USC president responds to controversy over his hiring |publisher=WLTX |date=October 8, 2019 |accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref> Though stated that the theSACS inquiry would result in no formal sanctions,<ref>{{cite news |last=Daprile |first=Lucas |url=https://www.thestate.com/news/local/education/article238230709.html |title=USC's presidential search will not result in formal sanctions, school says |publisher=The State |date=December 10, 2019 |accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref> the report did state that there was, in fact, undue political influence from the Governor in the selection of Mr. Caslen; Governor McMaster's office denied the finding by arguing that the Governor's influence is permissible as he is a member of the board of trustees ''ex officio''. The University will be subject to enhanced monitoring, a compliance report, and a site visit in Fall 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=WLTX |url=https://www.wltx.com/article/news/sacs-findings-usc-presidential-search/101-745b69f2-ae01-42cf-bbcb-7cb8705c64d9 |title='Undue influence' from Governor in USC's presidential search, board finds |publisher=WLTX |date= January 17, 2020 |accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn tandem with the SACS inquiry, the [[South Carolina Senate]] formed a bi-partisan committee to review the presidential search, looking into how to improve the process for future searches rather than remove Caslen as incumbent, though at least one member, [[Katrina Shealy]], proposed was to \"listen to the issues\" people had expressed with the search and then \"move on\" without any changes to improve the search process for the future.<ref>{{cite news |last=Scott |first=Tim |url=https://www.abccolumbia.com/2019/10/08/new-senate-committee-looks-to-address-issues-with-usc-presidential-search/ |title=New Senate committee looks to examine issues with USC presidential search |publisher=WOLO |date=October 8, 2019 |accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCaslen is married to Michele (Shelly) Caslen ({{nee}} Pastin) from Highland Falls, New York. They have three sons: Robert Caslen III, a firefighter; Jeffrey (Jeff) Caslen, a captain in the Army; and Nicholas (Nick) Caslen, an FBI special agent.<ref name=\"allgov1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Robert L. Caslen Jr.}}\n*[https://www.sc.edu/about/presidential_search/president_elect/ Robert L. Caslen Jr., University of South Carolina President-Elect] - University of South Carolina. Retrieved July 27, 2019.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160815140235/https://westpoint.edu/superintendent/SitePages/Biography.aspx Lieutenant General Robert L. Caslen, Jr] - Biography page, Office of the Superintendent. Archived. Retrieved July 27, 2019.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William B. Caldwell IV]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Commandant of the United States Army Command and General Staff College]]|years=2010\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[David G. Perkins]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[David H. Huntoon]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Superintendent of the United States Military Academy]]|years=2013\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Darryl A. Williams]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{United States Military Academy superintendents}}\n{{NCAA Theodore Roosevelt Award}}\n{{University of South Carolina presidents}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caslen, Robert}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Army Black Knights football players]]\n[[Category:Commandants of the Corps of Cadets of the United States Military Academy]]\n[[Category:Commandants of the United States Army Command and General Staff College]]\n[[Category:Kansas State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Long Island University alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Medal (US Army)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Defense Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Defense Superior Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n", "name_user": "Abraham, B.S.", "label": "safe", "comment": "tweak infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_L._Caslen"}
{"title_page": "(278361) 2007 JJ43", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:{{mp|(278361) 2007 JJ|43}}}}\n{{Infobox planet\n | minorplanet        = yes\n | background         = #C2E0FF\n | discovery_ref      = &thinsp;<ref name=jpldata />\n | discoverer         = [[Palomar Observatory]]\n | discovered         = 14 May 2007\n | name               = {{mp|({{val|278361}}) 2007 JJ|43}}\n | note               = yes\n | alt_names          = {{mp|2007 JJ|43}}\n | mp_category        = {{Hlist\n  | [[trans-Neptunian object|TNO]]&thinsp;<ref name=jpldata />\n  | [[Classical Kuiper belt object|cubewano]]&thinsp;<ref name=johnston />{{Failed verification|reason=listed as other|date=March 2018}}\n  | ScatNear<ref name=\"Buie\"/>\n  }}\n | orbit_ref          = <ref name=AstDys /><ref name=jpldata />\n | epoch              = 27 August 2011 ([[Julian day|JD]]&nbsp;2455800.5)\n | uncertainty        = 2\n | observation_arc    = 4813 days (13.18&nbsp;yr)\n | earliest_precovery_date = 10 May 2002 ([[Near-Earth Asteroid Tracking|NEAT]])\n | semimajor          = {{val|47.82|u=AU}}\n | perihelion         = {{val|40.2776|u=AU}}\n | aphelion           = {{val|55.3707|ul=AU}}\n | eccentricity       = {{val|0.1578}}\n | period             = 330.74&nbsp;[[Julian year (astronomy)|a]] ({{val|120801|ul=d}})\n | inclination        = 12.0623[[degree (angle)|\u00b0]]\n | asc_node           = 272.493\u00b0\n | arg_peri           = 9.02\u00b0\n | mean_anomaly       = 331.84\u00b0\n | dimensions         = {{Ubl\n  | {{val|610|+170|-140|u=km}} <small>(0.13 albedo, H=3.9)</small><ref name=\"P\u00e1l2015\" />\n  | \u2248530&nbsp;km <small>(0.08 albedo, H=4.8)</small><ref name=\"Brown-dplist\" />\n  | \u2248558&nbsp;km <small>(0.09 albedo, H=4.5)</small><ref name=johnston />\n  }}\n | mass               =\n | albedo             =\n | rotation           = {{Ubl\n  | 12.097&nbsp;h<ref name=\"P\u00e1l2015\"/>\n  | 6.04&nbsp;h<ref name=jpldata />\n  }}\n | magnitude          = 20.8&thinsp;<ref name=\"AstDyS-E\" />\n | abs_magnitude      = {{Ubl\n  | 3.2 (R-band)<ref name=SSGPsurvey>[https://arxiv.org/pdf/1107.5309v1.pdf A Southern Sky and Galactic Plane Survey for Bright Kuiper Belt Object]</ref>\n  | 4.5&thinsp;<ref name=jpldata /> \n  }}\n}}\n'''{{mp|(268361) 2007 JJ|43}}''' is a [[trans-Neptunian object]] (TNO) orbiting the [[Sun]] near the outer edge of the [[Kuiper belt]]. If size estimates based on its absolute magnitude are correct, it is a [[possible dwarf planet]].\n\nIts discovery images were taken in 2007, and its [[absolute magnitude]] of 4.5 is one of the twenty brightest exhibited by TNOs. Assuming it has a typical [[albedo]], this would make it roughly the same size as [[28978 Ixion|Ixion]] (about 530\u2013620&nbsp;km diameter). [[Michael E. Brown|Michael Brown]]'s website lists it as a \"likely\" dwarf planet.<ref name=\"Brown-dplist\">{{cite web\n |title=How many dwarf planets are there in the outer solar system? (updates daily) \n |publisher=[[California Institute of Technology]] \n |author=Michael E. Brown \n |author-link=Michael E. Brown \n |url=http://web.gps.caltech.edu/~mbrown/dps.html\n |accessdate=2019-08-13 \n |url-status=live\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531134353/http://web.gps.caltech.edu/~mbrown/dps.html\n |archivedate=2019-05-20\n }}</ref>\nIn a paper in the Astrophysical Journal Letters Andr\u00e1s P\u00e1l and colleagues estimate a diameter for {{mp|(278361) 2007 JJ|43}} of {{val|610|+170|-140|u=km}}.<ref name=\"P\u00e1l2015\"/>\n\nObservations by Brown in 2012, using the [[W. M. Keck Observatory]], suggest that {{mp|(278361) 2007 JJ|43}} does not have a [[Minor planet moon|companion]].<ref name=\"plutokiller\">{{cite web\n  |title=2007 JJ43 doesn't have a big moon. There could be a small one hiding in there\n  |date=2012-02-03\n  |publisher=[[Twitter]]\n  |author=Plutokiller\n  |url=https://twitter.com/#!/plutokiller/status/165453799052423168\n  |accessdate=2012-02-03}} [https://twitter.com/#!/plutokiller/status/165470395003183104 (moonless)]</ref>\n\n{{As of|2014}}, it is about 41.3&nbsp;[[Astronomical unit|AU]] from the Sun.<ref name=\"AstDyS-E\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Solar System objects by size]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist\n|30em\n|refs=\n\n<ref name=jpldata>\n[http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=2007%20JJ43 JPL Small-Body Database Browser: 2007 JJ43] Retrieved: 2011-06-18\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=AstDys>\n[https://newton.spacedys.com/astdys/index.php?pc=1.1.0&n=2007JJ43 AstDys 2007 JJ<sub>43</sub> Summary] Retrieved: 2012-02-03\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=johnston>{{cite web\n |date=20 August 2011\n |title=List of Known Trans-Neptunian Objects\n |publisher=Johnston's Archive\n |author=Wm. Robert Johnston\n |url=http://www.johnstonsarchive.net/astro/tnoslist.html\n |accessdate=2012-02-03}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AstDyS-E\">{{cite web\n |title=AstDys 2007 JJ<sub>43</sub> Ephemerides\n |publisher=Department of Mathematics, University of Pisa, Italy\n |url=https://newton.spacedys.com/astdys/index.php?pc=1.1.3.0&n=2007JJ43\n |accessdate=2012-02-03}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"P\u00e1l2015\">{{cite journal | title=Pushing the Limits: K2 Observations of the Trans-Neptunian Objects 2002 GV31 and (278361) 2007 JJ43 | last1=P\u00e1l | first1=A. | last2=Szab\u00f3 | first2=R. | last3=Szab\u00f3 | first3=Gy. M. | last4=Kiss | first4=L. L. | last5=Moln\u00e1r | first5=L. | last6=S\u00e1rneczky | first6=K. | last7=Kiss | first7=Cs. | display-authors=1 | journal=The Astrophysical Journal Letters | volume=804 | issue=2 | at=L45 | year=2015 | arxiv=1504.03671 | bibcode=2015ApJ...804L..45P | doi=10.1088/2041-8205/804/2/L45 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Buie\">{{cite web\n  |author=Marc W. Buie\n  |author-link=Marc W. Buie\n  |title=Orbit Fit and Astrometric record for 278361\n  |publisher=SwRI (Space Science Department)\n  |url=http://www.boulder.swri.edu/~buie/kbo/astrom/278361.html\n  |accessdate=2018-02-18}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Dwarf planets}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:278361 2007 JJ43}}\n[[Category:Classical Kuiper belt objects]]\n[[Category:Possible dwarf planets]]\n[[Category:Astronomical objects discovered in 2007|20070514]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:{{mp|(278361) 2007 JJ|43}}}}\n{{Infobox planet\n | minorplanet        = yes\n | background         = #C2E0FF\n  | discovery_ref      = &thinsp;<ref name=jpldata />\n  | discoverer         = [[Palomar Observatory]]\n | discovered         = 14 May 2007\n | name               = {{mp|({{val|278361}}) 2007 JJ|43}}\n | note               = yes\n | alt_names          = {{mp|2007 JJ|43}}\n | mp_category        = [[trans-Neptunian object|TNO]]&thinsp;<ref name=jpldata />{{\u00b7}}[[Classical Kuiper belt object|cubewano]]&thinsp;<ref name=johnston />{{Failed verification|reason=listed as other|date=March 2018}}<br>ScatNear<ref name=\"Buie\"/>\n | orbit_ref          = <ref name=AstDys /><ref name=jpldata />\n | epoch              = 2011-08-27 0:00UTC ([[Julian day|JD]] {{val|2455800.5}})\n | uncertainty        = 2\n | observation_arc    = 4813 days (13.18 yr)\n | earliest_precovery_date = 10 May 2002 ([[Near-Earth Asteroid Tracking|NEAT]])\n | semimajor          = {{val|47.82|u=AU}}\n | perihelion         = {{val|40.2776|u=AU}}\n | aphelion           = {{val|55.3707|ul=AU}}\n | eccentricity       = {{val|0.1578}}\n | period             = 330.74 [[Julian year (astronomy)|a]] ({{val|120801|ul=d}})\n | inclination        = 12.0623[[degree (angle)|\u00b0]]\n | asc_node           = 272.493\u00b0\n | arg_peri           = 9.02\u00b0\n | mean_anomaly       = 331.84\u00b0\n | dimensions         = {{val|610|+170|-140|u=km}} <small>(0.13 albedo, H=3.9)</small><ref name=\"P\u00e1l2015\" /><br/>\u2248530&nbsp;km <small>(0.08 albedo, H=4.8)</small><ref name=\"Brown-dplist\" /><br/>\u2248558&nbsp;km <small>(0.09 albedo, H=4.5)</small><ref name=johnston />\n | mass               =\n | albedo             =\n | rotation           = 12.097 h<ref name=\"P\u00e1l2015\"/> <br> 6.04 hr?<ref name=jpldata />\n | magnitude          = 20.8&thinsp;<ref name=\"AstDyS-E\" />\n | abs_magnitude      = 3.2&thinsp;(R-band)<ref name=SSGPsurvey>[https://arxiv.org/pdf/1107.5309v1.pdf A Southern Sky and Galactic Plane Survey for Bright Kuiper Belt Object]</ref><br>4.5&thinsp;<ref name=jpldata /> \n}}\n\n'''{{mp|(268361) 2007 JJ|43}}''' is a [[trans-Neptunian object]] (TNO) orbiting the [[Sun]] near the outer edge of the [[Kuiper belt]]. If size estimates based on its absolute magnitude are correct, it is a [[possible dwarf planet]].\n\nIts discovery images were taken in 2007, and its [[absolute magnitude]] of 4.5 is one of the twenty brightest exhibited by TNOs. Assuming it has a typical [[albedo]], this would make it roughly the same size as [[28978 Ixion|Ixion]] (about 530\u2013620&nbsp;km diameter). [[Michael E. Brown|Michael Brown]]'s website lists it as a \"likely\" dwarf planet.<ref name=\"Brown-dplist\">{{cite web\n |title=How many dwarf planets are there in the outer solar system? (updates daily) \n |publisher=[[California Institute of Technology]] \n |author=Michael E. Brown \n |author-link=Michael E. Brown \n |url=http://web.gps.caltech.edu/~mbrown/dps.html\n |accessdate=2019-08-13 \n |url-status=live\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531134353/http://web.gps.caltech.edu/~mbrown/dps.html\n |archivedate=2019-05-20\n |df= \n}}</ref>\nIn a paper in the Astrophysical Journal Letters Andr\u00e1s P\u00e1l and colleagues estimate a diameter for {{mp|(278361) 2007 JJ|43}} of {{val|610|+170|-140|u=km}}.<ref name=\"P\u00e1l2015\"/>\n\nObservations by Brown in 2012, using the [[W. M. Keck Observatory]], suggest that {{mp|(278361) 2007 JJ|43}} does not have a [[Minor planet moon|companion]].<ref name=\"plutokiller\">{{cite web\n  |title=2007 JJ43 doesn't have a big moon. There could be a small one hiding in there\n  |date=2012-02-03\n  |publisher=[[Twitter]]\n  |author=Plutokiller\n  |url=https://twitter.com/#!/plutokiller/status/165453799052423168\n  |accessdate=2012-02-03}} [https://twitter.com/#!/plutokiller/status/165470395003183104 (moonless)]</ref>\n\n{{As of|2014}}, it is about 41.3 [[Astronomical unit|AU]] from the Sun.<ref name=\"AstDyS-E\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Solar System objects by size]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist\n|30em\n|refs=\n\n<ref name=jpldata>\n[http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=2007%20JJ43 JPL Small-Body Database Browser: 2007 JJ43] Retrieved: 2011-06-18\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=AstDys>\n[http://hamilton.dm.unipi.it/astdys/index.php?pc=1.1.0&n=2007JJ43 AstDys 2007 JJ<sub>43</sub> Summary] Retrieved: 2012-02-03\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=johnston>{{cite web\n |date=20 August 2011\n |title=List of Known Trans-Neptunian Objects\n |publisher=Johnston's Archive\n |author=Wm. Robert Johnston\n |url=http://www.johnstonsarchive.net/astro/tnoslist.html\n |accessdate=2012-02-03}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"AstDyS-E\">{{cite web\n |title=AstDys 2007 JJ<sub>43</sub> Ephemerides\n |publisher=Department of Mathematics, University of Pisa, Italy\n |url=http://hamilton.dm.unipi.it/astdys/index.php?pc=1.1.3.0&n=2007JJ43\n |accessdate=2012-02-03}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"P\u00e1l2015\">{{cite journal | title=Pushing the Limits: K2 Observations of the Trans-Neptunian Objects 2002 GV31 and (278361) 2007 JJ43 | last1=P\u00e1l | first1=A. | last2=Szab\u00f3 | first2=R. | last3=Szab\u00f3 | first3=Gy. M. | last4=Kiss | first4=L. L. | last5=Moln\u00e1r | first5=L. | last6=S\u00e1rneczky | first6=K. | last7=Kiss | first7=Cs. | display-authors=1 | journal=The Astrophysical Journal Letters | volume=804 | issue=2 | at=L45 | year=2015 | arxiv=1504.03671 | bibcode=2015ApJ...804L..45P | doi=10.1088/2041-8205/804/2/L45 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Buie\">{{cite web\n  |author=Marc W. Buie\n  |author-link=Marc W. Buie\n  |title=Orbit Fit and Astrometric record for 278361\n  |publisher=SwRI (Space Science Department)\n  |url=http://www.boulder.swri.edu/~buie/kbo/astrom/278361.html\n  |accessdate=2018-02-18}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Dwarf planets}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:278361 2007 JJ43}}\n[[Category:Classical Kuiper 